(function(){const rareTreasureFix={"selections":[{"selection_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure","grade":4,"curriculum":"myView Literacy","unit":1,"week":2,"title":"Rare Treasure: Mary Anning and Her Remarkable Discoveries","author":"Don Brown","genre":"Biography","essential_question":"How can a person\u0027s curiosity lead to important discoveries?","weekly_question":"How did Mary Anning\u0027s curiosity and persistence lead to remarkable fossil discoveries?","reading_skill":"Selection Assessment","reading_strategy":"Use text evidence","vocabulary":["poor","wealthy","fossils","poverty","discoveries"],"text_policy":"This prototype uses short assessment excerpts and questions only. Students should read the full selection in their licensed myView Literacy textbook or classroom materials.","read_aloud":"Rare Treasure: Mary Anning and Her Remarkable Discoveries. How did Mary Anning\u0027s curiosity and persistence lead to remarkable fossil discoveries?. Read the full selection in your textbook, then answer each question using text evidence.","assessment_levels":[{"level":1,"level_name":"Level 1","difficulty_band":"foundation","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l01-q001","read_aloud":"What does the word \"poor\" most likely mean in this sentence? A. Having a lot of money and toys B. Having very little money or possessions C. Being very happy all the time D. Being sick and unable to work","excerpt":"\"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\"","stem":"What does the word \"poor\" most likely mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Having a lot of money and toys","B":"Having very little money or possessions","C":"Being very happy all the time","D":"Being sick and unable to work"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Poor\" means not having much money. The text says Mary\u0027s life was hard, which shows she did not have many things.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l01-q002","read_aloud":"Where was Mary Anning born? A. London, England B. Lyme Regis, England C. Paris, France D. New York, America","excerpt":"\"In 1799, Mary Anning was born in Lyme Regis, a small English port tucked tightly between cliffs and coast.\"","stem":"Where was Mary Anning born?","choices":{"A":"London, England","B":"Lyme Regis, England","C":"Paris, France","D":"New York, America"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says Mary Anning was born in Lyme Regis, a small English port.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1799, Mary Anning was born in Lyme Regis, a small English port tucked tightly between cliffs and coast.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l01-q003","read_aloud":"Who taught Mary and Joseph how to hunt for fossils? A. Their mother B. Their teacher C. Their father Richard Anning D. Their neighbor Mrs. Stock","excerpt":"\"Mary and her older brother, Joseph, were just a few years old when they began visiting the nearby rocky beaches with their father. Richard Anning taught them how to hunt for fossils.\"","stem":"Who taught Mary and Joseph how to hunt for fossils?","choices":{"A":"Their mother","B":"Their teacher","C":"Their father Richard Anning","D":"Their neighbor Mrs. Stock"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says \"Richard Anning taught them how to hunt for fossils.\" Richard Anning was their father.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary and her older brother, Joseph, were just a few years old when they began visiting the nearby rocky beaches with their father. Richard Anning taught them how to hunt for fossils.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l01-q004","read_aloud":"What happened to Mary during the storm when she was a baby? A. She was not outside during the storm B. She was the only one who survived the lightning strike C. She was hiding in a cave D. She ran away from her nursemaid","excerpt":"\"Mary\u0027s life started with a bang-the bang of thunder. Infant Mary was outdoors with her nursemaid when a sudden and terrible storm burst. The nursemaid grabbed Mary and, with two other young women, raced to the cover of a nearby elm. The sky exploded and lightning struck the tree! Only Mary survived.\"","stem":"What happened to Mary during the storm when she was a baby?","choices":{"A":"She was not outside during the storm","B":"She was the only one who survived the lightning strike","C":"She was hiding in a cave","D":"She ran away from her nursemaid"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says \"Only Mary survived\" after lightning struck the tree where the group was hiding.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary\u0027s life started with a bang-the bang of thunder. Infant Mary was outdoors with her nursemaid when a sudden and terrible storm burst. The nursemaid grabbed Mary and, with two other young women, raced to the cover of a nearby elm. The sky exploded and lightning struck the tree! Only Mary survived.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l01-q005","read_aloud":"What are fossils? A. Rocks that are found only in the ocean B. The remains of animals or plants that lived long ago C. Jewels that are hidden underground D. Tools that ancient people made from stone","excerpt":"\"Fossils were strange and mysterious. Although they had been found before, scientists were just beginning to understand that they were the remains of animals or plants that no longer existed, living things that had died many, many years ago.\"","stem":"What are fossils?","choices":{"A":"Rocks that are found only in the ocean","B":"The remains of animals or plants that lived long ago","C":"Jewels that are hidden underground","D":"Tools that ancient people made from stone"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says fossils are \"the remains of animals or plants that no longer existed, living things that had died many, many years ago.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Fossils were strange and mysterious. Although they had been found before, scientists were just beginning to understand that they were the remains of animals or plants that no longer existed, living things that had died many, many years ago.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l01-q006","read_aloud":"What does the word \"poverty\" most likely mean in this story? A. having lots of money and toys B. being extremely poor with little money C. living in a big, fancy house D. having many friends to help","excerpt":"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone.","stem":"What does the word \"poverty\" most likely mean in this story?","choices":{"A":"having lots of money and toys","B":"being extremely poor with little money","C":"living in a big, fancy house","D":"having many friends to help"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Poverty means being very poor and not having enough money. The text says Mary\u0027s life was hard, which matches this meaning.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l01-q007","read_aloud":"Who taught Mary and Joseph to hunt for fossils? A. their mother B. their teacher at school C. their father, Richard Anning D. a scientist from London","excerpt":"Mary and her older brother, Joseph, were just a few years old when they began visiting the nearby rocky beaches with their father.","stem":"Who taught Mary and Joseph to hunt for fossils?","choices":{"A":"their mother","B":"their teacher at school","C":"their father, Richard Anning","D":"a scientist from London"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says their father, Richard Anning, taught them how to hunt for fossils. The other people are not mentioned here.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Mary and her older brother, Joseph, were just a few years old when they began visiting the nearby rocky beaches with their father."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l01-q008","read_aloud":"What happened when lightning struck the tree where Mary was hiding? A. Mary was hurt badly. B. Mary was the only one who survived. C. Everyone ran away safely. D. The nursemaid saved everyone.","excerpt":"Only Mary survived. It was a miraculous escape.","stem":"What happened when lightning struck the tree where Mary was hiding?","choices":{"A":"Mary was hurt badly.","B":"Mary was the only one who survived.","C":"Everyone ran away safely.","D":"The nursemaid saved everyone."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says only Mary survived the lightning strike. The other choices do not match what happened.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Only Mary survived. It was a miraculous escape."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l01-q009","read_aloud":"Why did Mary think her rocks were precious? A. They were worth a lot of money. B. They were beautiful and belonged to her. C. Her father gave them to her. D. Scientists wanted to buy them.","excerpt":"Those rocks were precious, they were beautiful, and-most importantly-they were mine.","stem":"Why did Mary think her rocks were precious?","choices":{"A":"They were worth a lot of money.","B":"They were beautiful and belonged to her.","C":"Her father gave them to her.","D":"Scientists wanted to buy them."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Mary says the rocks were precious because they were beautiful and hers. The text does not mention money, her father, or scientists here.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Those rocks were precious, they were beautiful, and-most importantly-they were mine."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l01-q010","read_aloud":"What does the word poor mean in this sentence? A. Mary had many friends B. Mary did not have much money C. Mary was not very smart D. Mary was feeling sick","excerpt":"\"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone.\"","stem":"What does the word poor mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Mary had many friends","B":"Mary did not have much money","C":"Mary was not very smart","D":"Mary was feeling sick"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text tells us Mary\u0027s family \"struggled to survive\" and later \"sold their furniture to pay their rent.\" This shows poor means not having much money.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l01-q011","read_aloud":"What is this paragraph mostly about? A. The cliffs near the sea B. Where and when Mary Anning was born C. Mary\u0027s favorite place to visit D. The weather in England","excerpt":"\"In 1799, Mary Anning was born in Lyme Regis, a small English port tucked tightly between cliffs and coast.\"","stem":"What is this paragraph mostly about?","choices":{"A":"The cliffs near the sea","B":"Where and when Mary Anning was born","C":"Mary\u0027s favorite place to visit","D":"The weather in England"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The sentence gives two key facts: the year Mary was born (1799) and the place she was born (Lyme Regis). These tell us about her birth.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1799, Mary Anning was born in Lyme Regis, a small English port tucked tightly between cliffs and coast.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l01-q012","read_aloud":"According to the text, what happened when Mary was a baby? A. She got lost at the beach B. She was in a terrible storm with her nursemaid C. She found her first fossil D. She moved to a new town","excerpt":"\"Mary\u0027s life started with a bang-the bang of thunder. Infant Mary was outdoors with her nursemaid when a sudden and terrible storm burst.\"","stem":"According to the text, what happened when Mary was a baby?","choices":{"A":"She got lost at the beach","B":"She was in a terrible storm with her nursemaid","C":"She found her first fossil","D":"She moved to a new town"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt says baby Mary was \"outdoors with her nursemaid when a sudden and terrible storm burst.\" This matches answer b.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary\u0027s life started with a bang-the bang of thunder. Infant Mary was outdoors with her nursemaid when a sudden and terrible storm burst.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l01-q013","read_aloud":"How did the family get extra money? A. By fishing in the sea B. By selling the fossils they found C. By working at a museum D. By teaching other people","excerpt":"\"The family struggled to survive on the earnings of Richard\u0027s carpentry work, and the extra money they earned by selling fossils helped.\"","stem":"How did the family get extra money?","choices":{"A":"By fishing in the sea","B":"By selling the fossils they found","C":"By working at a museum","D":"By teaching other people"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says \"the extra money they earned by selling fossils helped.\" This means they sold fossils to get more money.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The family struggled to survive on the earnings of Richard\u0027s carpentry work, and the extra money they earned by selling fossils helped.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l01-q014","read_aloud":"What does the word poverty mean in this sentence? A. Being extremely poor B. Being very wealthy C. Being extremely happy D. Being very healthy","excerpt":"\"Then Mary\u0027s father died and the family was thrown into bitter poverty.\"","stem":"What does the word poverty mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Being extremely poor","B":"Being very wealthy","C":"Being extremely happy","D":"Being very healthy"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Poverty means the state of being extremely poor and not having enough money.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Then Mary\u0027s father died and the family was thrown into bitter poverty.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l01-q015","read_aloud":"Who taught Mary to hunt for fossils? A. Her mother B. Her brother C. Her father D. A scientist","excerpt":"\"Richard Anning taught them how to hunt for fossils.\"","stem":"Who taught Mary to hunt for fossils?","choices":{"A":"Her mother","B":"Her brother","C":"Her father","D":"A scientist"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says that Richard Anning, who was her father, taught them how to hunt for fossils.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Richard Anning taught them how to hunt for fossils.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l01-q016","read_aloud":"What happened to Mary when she was a baby? A. She got lost in the woods. B. She was caught in a storm. C. She found a fossil on the beach. D. She moved to a new house.","excerpt":"\"Mary\u0027s life started with a bang-the bang of thunder. Infant Mary was outdoors with her nursemaid when a sudden and terrible storm burst.\"","stem":"What happened to Mary when she was a baby?","choices":{"A":"She got lost in the woods.","B":"She was caught in a storm.","C":"She found a fossil on the beach.","D":"She moved to a new house."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says she was outdoors when a sudden and terrible storm burst.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary\u0027s life started with a bang-the bang of thunder. Infant Mary was outdoors with her nursemaid when a sudden and terrible storm burst.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l01-q017","read_aloud":"How does the author describe Mary\u0027s survival? A. As a sad ending B. As a lucky event C. As a scary dream D. As a funny story","excerpt":"\"Only Mary survived. It was a miraculous escape.\"","stem":"How does the author describe Mary\u0027s survival?","choices":{"A":"As a sad ending","B":"As a lucky event","C":"As a scary dream","D":"As a funny story"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author calls it a \"miraculous escape,\" which means it was a very lucky and amazing event.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Only Mary survived. It was a miraculous escape.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l01-q018","read_aloud":"What does the word \"wealthy\" mean in this sentence? A. Having a lot of money B. Being very young C. Visiting from far away D. Enjoying looking at rocks","excerpt":"\"The Annings displayed the puzzling yet delightful fossils that they found on a table near Richard\u0027s shop on Bridge Street. Wealthy tourists visiting the popular Lyme Regis shore bought them.\"","stem":"What does the word \"wealthy\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Having a lot of money","B":"Being very young","C":"Visiting from far away","D":"Enjoying looking at rocks"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"\"Wealthy\" means rich or having a lot of money. Wealthy tourists could afford to buy fossils.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Annings displayed the puzzling yet delightful fossils that they found on a table near Richard\u0027s shop on Bridge Street. Wealthy tourists visiting the popular Lyme Regis shore bought them.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l01-q019","read_aloud":"What happened to Mary\u0027s family after her father died? A. They became very rich B. They moved to a big city C. They were thrown into bitter poverty D. They stopped selling fossils","excerpt":"\"The family struggled to survive on the earnings of Richard\u0027s carpentry work, and the extra money they earned by selling fossils helped. Then Mary\u0027s father died and the family was thrown into bitter poverty.\"","stem":"What happened to Mary\u0027s family after her father died?","choices":{"A":"They became very rich","B":"They moved to a big city","C":"They were thrown into bitter poverty","D":"They stopped selling fossils"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says after Mary\u0027s father died, \"the family was thrown into bitter poverty,\" meaning they became very poor.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The family struggled to survive on the earnings of Richard\u0027s carpentry work, and the extra money they earned by selling fossils helped. Then Mary\u0027s father died and the family was thrown into bitter poverty.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l01-q020","read_aloud":"What question did Mary want to answer after Joseph found the fossil skull? A. How old was the fossil skull B. What the rest of the creature looked like C. Who would buy the fossil skull D. Where the fossil skull should be kept","excerpt":"\"One day Joseph found a fantastic fossil skull. It was nearly the length of a man\u0027s arm and had a long snout that held many sharp teeth. Was it a crocodile? A dragon? A monster? What did the rest of the creature look like? A year passed before Mary discovered the answer.\"","stem":"What question did Mary want to answer after Joseph found the fossil skull?","choices":{"A":"How old was the fossil skull","B":"What the rest of the creature looked like","C":"Who would buy the fossil skull","D":"Where the fossil skull should be kept"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text asks \"What did the rest of the creature look like?\" and says Mary discovered the answer a year later.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"One day Joseph found a fantastic fossil skull. It was nearly the length of a man\u0027s arm and had a long snout that held many sharp teeth. Was it a crocodile? A dragon? A monster? What did the rest of the creature look like? A year passed before Mary discovered the answer.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l01-q021","read_aloud":"What did scientists name the creature whose skeleton Mary found? A. Pterodactyl B. Plesiosaur C. Ichthyosaur D. Squaloraja","excerpt":"\"In 1811, Mary found a fossilized skeleton beneath a cliff called Black Ven, where Joseph had found the skull. It looked like a porpoise and was about seven feet long. Men helped her free the skeleton from the earth. She sold it to a rich neighbor, who showed it to scientists. The scientists called the creature ichthyosaur, which means fish lizard.\"","stem":"What did scientists name the creature whose skeleton Mary found?","choices":{"A":"Pterodactyl","B":"Plesiosaur","C":"Ichthyosaur","D":"Squaloraja"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says \"The scientists called the creature ichthyosaur, which means fish lizard.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1811, Mary found a fossilized skeleton beneath a cliff called Black Ven, where Joseph had found the skull. It looked like a porpoise and was about seven feet long. Men helped her free the skeleton from the earth. She sold it to a rich neighbor, who showed it to scientists. The scientists called the creature ichthyosaur, which means fish lizard.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l01-q022","read_aloud":"Based on this excerpt, how do you think Mary might have felt about people forgetting she found the fossil? A. Happy that scientists were studying it B. Sad or upset that she did not get credit C. Excited to find more fossils D. Angry at her brother Joseph","excerpt":"\"Almost everyone forgot that it had been found by twelve-year-old Mary Anning and her teenage brother.\"","stem":"Based on this excerpt, how do you think Mary might have felt about people forgetting she found the fossil?","choices":{"A":"Happy that scientists were studying it","B":"Sad or upset that she did not get credit","C":"Excited to find more fossils","D":"Angry at her brother Joseph"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Most people want to be recognized for their hard work. Being forgotten would likely make Mary feel sad or upset.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Almost everyone forgot that it had been found by twelve-year-old Mary Anning and her teenage brother.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l01-q023","read_aloud":"What does the word \"geology\" mean in this sentence? A. The study of animals and their habitats B. The study of rocks, mountains, and the earth C. The study of weather and storms D. The study of ancient human history","excerpt":"\"Mary still collected fossils and also earned money from small jobs she did for her neighbors. One of them, Mrs. Stock, gave her a geology book. From it Mary learned about rocks and mountains and the earth.\"","stem":"What does the word \"geology\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"The study of animals and their habitats","B":"The study of rocks, mountains, and the earth","C":"The study of weather and storms","D":"The study of ancient human history"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says from the geology book Mary learned \"about rocks and mountains and the earth,\" so geology is the study of those things.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary still collected fossils and also earned money from small jobs she did for her neighbors. One of them, Mrs. Stock, gave her a geology book. From it Mary learned about rocks and mountains and the earth.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l01-q024","read_aloud":"How did Mary learn about science even though she had to leave school early? A. She went to a university B. She taught herself by reading books C. Her father taught her at home D. She learned from the tourists","excerpt":"\"Mary still collected fossils and also earned money from small jobs she did for her neighbors. One of them, Mrs. Stock, gave her a geology book. From it Mary learned about rocks and mountains and the earth. She read other books and taught herself about animals, fish, and fossils.\"","stem":"How did Mary learn about science even though she had to leave school early?","choices":{"A":"She went to a university","B":"She taught herself by reading books","C":"Her father taught her at home","D":"She learned from the tourists"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says she \"read other books and taught herself about animals, fish, and fossils.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary still collected fossils and also earned money from small jobs she did for her neighbors. One of them, Mrs. Stock, gave her a geology book. From it Mary learned about rocks and mountains and the earth. She read other books and taught herself about animals, fish, and fossils.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l01-q025","read_aloud":"What did Mary\u0027s family have to do to pay their rent? A. Move to a smaller house B. Sell their furniture C. Borrow money from friends D. Stop collecting fossils","excerpt":"\"Years passed. When Mary was twenty years old, she and her mother and brother were still living together. They remained very poor and even sold their furniture to pay their rent.\"","stem":"What did Mary\u0027s family have to do to pay their rent?","choices":{"A":"Move to a smaller house","B":"Sell their furniture","C":"Borrow money from friends","D":"Stop collecting fossils"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says \"they remained very poor and even sold their furniture to pay their rent.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Years passed. When Mary was twenty years old, she and her mother and brother were still living together. They remained very poor and even sold their furniture to pay their rent.\""}]},{"level":2,"level_name":"Level 2","difficulty_band":"foundation","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l02-q001","read_aloud":"What does the word \"wealthy\" mean in this sentence? A. Having a lot of money B. Being very young C. Visiting from far away D. Enjoying looking at rocks","excerpt":"\"The Annings displayed the puzzling yet delightful fossils that they found on a table near Richard\u0027s shop on Bridge Street. Wealthy tourists visiting the popular Lyme Regis shore bought them.\"","stem":"What does the word \"wealthy\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Having a lot of money","B":"Being very young","C":"Visiting from far away","D":"Enjoying looking at rocks"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"\"Wealthy\" means rich or having a lot of money. Wealthy tourists could afford to buy fossils.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Annings displayed the puzzling yet delightful fossils that they found on a table near Richard\u0027s shop on Bridge Street. Wealthy tourists visiting the popular Lyme Regis shore bought them.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l02-q002","read_aloud":"What happened to Mary\u0027s family after her father died? A. They became very rich B. They moved to a big city C. They were thrown into bitter poverty D. They stopped selling fossils","excerpt":"\"The family struggled to survive on the earnings of Richard\u0027s carpentry work, and the extra money they earned by selling fossils helped. Then Mary\u0027s father died and the family was thrown into bitter poverty.\"","stem":"What happened to Mary\u0027s family after her father died?","choices":{"A":"They became very rich","B":"They moved to a big city","C":"They were thrown into bitter poverty","D":"They stopped selling fossils"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says after Mary\u0027s father died, \"the family was thrown into bitter poverty,\" meaning they became very poor.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The family struggled to survive on the earnings of Richard\u0027s carpentry work, and the extra money they earned by selling fossils helped. Then Mary\u0027s father died and the family was thrown into bitter poverty.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l02-q003","read_aloud":"What question did Mary want to answer after Joseph found the fossil skull? A. How old was the fossil skull B. What the rest of the creature looked like C. Who would buy the fossil skull D. Where the fossil skull should be kept","excerpt":"\"One day Joseph found a fantastic fossil skull. It was nearly the length of a man\u0027s arm and had a long snout that held many sharp teeth. Was it a crocodile? A dragon? A monster? What did the rest of the creature look like? A year passed before Mary discovered the answer.\"","stem":"What question did Mary want to answer after Joseph found the fossil skull?","choices":{"A":"How old was the fossil skull","B":"What the rest of the creature looked like","C":"Who would buy the fossil skull","D":"Where the fossil skull should be kept"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text asks \"What did the rest of the creature look like?\" and says Mary discovered the answer a year later.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"One day Joseph found a fantastic fossil skull. It was nearly the length of a man\u0027s arm and had a long snout that held many sharp teeth. Was it a crocodile? A dragon? A monster? What did the rest of the creature look like? A year passed before Mary discovered the answer.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l02-q004","read_aloud":"What did scientists name the creature whose skeleton Mary found? A. Pterodactyl B. Plesiosaur C. Ichthyosaur D. Squaloraja","excerpt":"\"In 1811, Mary found a fossilized skeleton beneath a cliff called Black Ven, where Joseph had found the skull. It looked like a porpoise and was about seven feet long. Men helped her free the skeleton from the earth. She sold it to a rich neighbor, who showed it to scientists. The scientists called the creature ichthyosaur, which means fish lizard.\"","stem":"What did scientists name the creature whose skeleton Mary found?","choices":{"A":"Pterodactyl","B":"Plesiosaur","C":"Ichthyosaur","D":"Squaloraja"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says \"The scientists called the creature ichthyosaur, which means fish lizard.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1811, Mary found a fossilized skeleton beneath a cliff called Black Ven, where Joseph had found the skull. It looked like a porpoise and was about seven feet long. Men helped her free the skeleton from the earth. She sold it to a rich neighbor, who showed it to scientists. The scientists called the creature ichthyosaur, which means fish lizard.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l02-q005","read_aloud":"Based on this excerpt, how do you think Mary might have felt about people forgetting she found the fossil? A. Happy that scientists were studying it B. Sad or upset that she did not get credit C. Excited to find more fossils D. Angry at her brother Joseph","excerpt":"\"Almost everyone forgot that it had been found by twelve-year-old Mary Anning and her teenage brother.\"","stem":"Based on this excerpt, how do you think Mary might have felt about people forgetting she found the fossil?","choices":{"A":"Happy that scientists were studying it","B":"Sad or upset that she did not get credit","C":"Excited to find more fossils","D":"Angry at her brother Joseph"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Most people want to be recognized for their hard work. Being forgotten would likely make Mary feel sad or upset.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Almost everyone forgot that it had been found by twelve-year-old Mary Anning and her teenage brother.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l02-q006","read_aloud":"Which word means almost the same as \"pursued\"? A. gave up on B. worked hard to keep doing C. forgot about D. asked others to do","excerpt":"She made it her life\u0027s work. It also must have been Mary\u0027s great delight because she pursued it despite the dangers on the rocky shore.","stem":"Which word means almost the same as \"pursued\"?","choices":{"A":"gave up on","B":"worked hard to keep doing","C":"forgot about","D":"asked others to do"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Pursued means Mary kept working hard at fossil collecting. The other choices mean the opposite.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: She made it her life\u0027s work. It also must have been Mary\u0027s great delight because she pursued it despite the dangers on the rocky shore."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l02-q007","read_aloud":"What are fossils, according to the text? A. living animals that hide in rocks B. remains of ancient plants or animals that turned to stone C. colorful stones found on beaches D. toys that children collect","excerpt":"Fossils were strange and mysterious. Although they had been found before, scientists were just beginning to understand that they were the remains of animals or plants that no longer existed.","stem":"What are fossils, according to the text?","choices":{"A":"living animals that hide in rocks","B":"remains of ancient plants or animals that turned to stone","C":"colorful stones found on beaches","D":"toys that children collect"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains fossils are remains of ancient life that became stone. The other choices do not match this definition.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Fossils were strange and mysterious. Although they had been found before, scientists were just beginning to understand that they were the remains of animals or plants that no longer existed."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l02-q008","read_aloud":"What did Joseph\u0027s fossil skull look like? A. small and round with no teeth B. long with a snout and many sharp teeth C. flat and smooth like a plate D. colorful and shiny like a gem","excerpt":"One day Joseph found a fantastic fossil skull. It was nearly the length of a man\u0027s arm and had a long snout that held many sharp teeth.","stem":"What did Joseph\u0027s fossil skull look like?","choices":{"A":"small and round with no teeth","B":"long with a snout and many sharp teeth","C":"flat and smooth like a plate","D":"colorful and shiny like a gem"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text describes the skull as long with a snout and sharp teeth. The other descriptions do not match.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: One day Joseph found a fantastic fossil skull. It was nearly the length of a man\u0027s arm and had a long snout that held many sharp teeth."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l02-q009","read_aloud":"What did Mary find in 1811? A. a fossilized skeleton B. a bag of gold coins C. a map to treasure D. a rare bird\u0027s nest","excerpt":"In 1811, Mary found a fossilized skeleton beneath a cliff called Black Ven, where Joseph had found the skull.","stem":"What did Mary find in 1811?","choices":{"A":"a fossilized skeleton","B":"a bag of gold coins","C":"a map to treasure","D":"a rare bird\u0027s nest"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text clearly says Mary found a fossilized skeleton in 1811. The other items are not mentioned.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: In 1811, Mary found a fossilized skeleton beneath a cliff called Black Ven, where Joseph had found the skull."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l02-q010","read_aloud":"Why were scientists thrilled by Mary\u0027s find? A. It was the first fossil ever found. B. It was a nearly perfect ichthyosaur fossil, which was very rare. C. It was made of gold. D. It was easy to carry home.","excerpt":"The scientists called the creature ichthyosaur, which means fish lizard. Only a few ichthyosaur fossils had ever been found and none were as nearly perfect as this one.","stem":"Why were scientists thrilled by Mary\u0027s find?","choices":{"A":"It was the first fossil ever found.","B":"It was a nearly perfect ichthyosaur fossil, which was very rare.","C":"It was made of gold.","D":"It was easy to carry home."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the fossil was rare and nearly perfect, which made scientists excited. The other choices are not supported.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The scientists called the creature ichthyosaur, which means fish lizard. Only a few ichthyosaur fossils had ever been found and none were as nearly perfect as this one."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l02-q011","read_aloud":"What does poverty mean in this sentence? A. Having too much food B. Being extremely poor and not having enough money C. Living in a big house D. Having many friends","excerpt":"\"Then Mary\u0027s father died and the family was thrown into bitter poverty.\"","stem":"What does poverty mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Having too much food","B":"Being extremely poor and not having enough money","C":"Living in a big house","D":"Having many friends"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says Mary\u0027s father died and then the family had \"bitter poverty.\" Before this, they \"struggled to survive.\" Poverty means being extremely poor.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Then Mary\u0027s father died and the family was thrown into bitter poverty.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l02-q012","read_aloud":"What happened first? A. Mary found the skeleton B. Joseph found a fossil skull C. Scientists named the creature D. Mary sold the fossil","excerpt":"\"One day Joseph found a fantastic fossil skull... A year passed before Mary discovered the answer.\"","stem":"What happened first?","choices":{"A":"Mary found the skeleton","B":"Joseph found a fossil skull","C":"Scientists named the creature","D":"Mary sold the fossil"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says Joseph found the skull first. Then \"a year passed before Mary discovered the answer.\" So Joseph\u0027s find came first.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"One day Joseph found a fantastic fossil skull... A year passed before Mary discovered the answer.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l02-q013","read_aloud":"Why did wealthy tourists buy the fossils? A. Because they were heavy B. Because they were puzzling yet delightful C. Because they were free D. Because Mary forced them to","excerpt":"\"The Annings displayed the puzzling yet delightful fossils that they found on a table near Richard\u0027s shop on Bridge Street. Wealthy tourists visiting the popular Lyme Regis shore bought them.\"","stem":"Why did wealthy tourists buy the fossils?","choices":{"A":"Because they were heavy","B":"Because they were puzzling yet delightful","C":"Because they were free","D":"Because Mary forced them to"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text describes the fossils as \"puzzling yet delightful.\" This made them interesting to tourists, so the tourists bought them.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Annings displayed the puzzling yet delightful fossils that they found on a table near Richard\u0027s shop on Bridge Street. Wealthy tourists visiting the popular Lyme Regis shore bought them.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l02-q014","read_aloud":"What did scientists call the creature Mary found? A. Plesiosaur B. Pterodactyl C. Ichthyosaur D. Dinosaur","excerpt":"\"In 1811, Mary found a fossilized skeleton beneath a cliff called Black Ven... The scientists called the creature ichthyosaur, which means fish lizard.\"","stem":"What did scientists call the creature Mary found?","choices":{"A":"Plesiosaur","B":"Pterodactyl","C":"Ichthyosaur","D":"Dinosaur"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text clearly states \"The scientists called the creature ichthyosaur, which means fish lizard.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1811, Mary found a fossilized skeleton beneath a cliff called Black Ven... The scientists called the creature ichthyosaur, which means fish lizard.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l02-q015","read_aloud":"What does this sentence tell us about Mary? A. She was famous right away B. People did not remember she found the fossil C. She worked alone D. She did not like scientists","excerpt":"\"Almost everyone forgot that it had been found by twelve-year-old Mary Anning and her teenage brother.\"","stem":"What does this sentence tell us about Mary?","choices":{"A":"She was famous right away","B":"People did not remember she found the fossil","C":"She worked alone","D":"She did not like scientists"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says \"Almost everyone forgot\" that Mary and her brother found it. This means people did not remember they were the ones who found it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Almost everyone forgot that it had been found by twelve-year-old Mary Anning and her teenage brother.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l02-q016","read_aloud":"What does the word pursued mean in this sentence? A. Worked without stopping B. Forgot about quickly C. Watched from far away D. Talked about loudly","excerpt":"\"It also must have been Mary\u0027s great delight because she pursued it despite the dangers on the rocky shore.\"","stem":"What does the word pursued mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Worked without stopping","B":"Forgot about quickly","C":"Watched from far away","D":"Talked about loudly"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Pursued means she kept working at it without stopping because she wanted to accomplish it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It also must have been Mary\u0027s great delight because she pursued it despite the dangers on the rocky shore.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l02-q017","read_aloud":"Why did the family sell fossils? A. To give them as gifts B. To earn extra money C. To make their shop look nice D. To trade for food","excerpt":"\"The family struggled to survive on the earnings of Richard\u0027s carpentry work, and the extra money they earned by selling fossils helped.\"","stem":"Why did the family sell fossils?","choices":{"A":"To give them as gifts","B":"To earn extra money","C":"To make their shop look nice","D":"To trade for food"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the extra money they earned by selling fossils helped the family survive.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The family struggled to survive on the earnings of Richard\u0027s carpentry work, and the extra money they earned by selling fossils helped.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l02-q018","read_aloud":"What did Joseph find? A. A small shell B. A gold coin C. A fossil skull D. A sharp knife","excerpt":"\"One day Joseph found a fantastic fossil skull. It was nearly the length of a man\u0027s arm and had a long snout that held many sharp teeth.\"","stem":"What did Joseph find?","choices":{"A":"A small shell","B":"A gold coin","C":"A fossil skull","D":"A sharp knife"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says Joseph found a fantastic fossil skull with a long snout.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"One day Joseph found a fantastic fossil skull. It was nearly the length of a man\u0027s arm and had a long snout that held many sharp teeth.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l02-q019","read_aloud":"What did Mary do with the skeleton she found? A. She kept it for herself. B. She gave it to her brother. C. She sold it to a rich neighbor. D. She donated it to a school.","excerpt":"\"Men helped her free the skeleton from the earth. She sold it to a rich neighbor, who showed it to scientists.\"","stem":"What did Mary do with the skeleton she found?","choices":{"A":"She kept it for herself.","B":"She gave it to her brother.","C":"She sold it to a rich neighbor.","D":"She donated it to a school."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text explains that she sold the skeleton to a rich neighbor.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Men helped her free the skeleton from the earth. She sold it to a rich neighbor, who showed it to scientists.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l02-q020","read_aloud":"What does the word ichthyosaur mean? A. Giant dinosaur B. Fish lizard C. Sea monster D. Sharp tooth","excerpt":"\"The scientists called the creature ichthyosaur, which means fish lizard.\"","stem":"What does the word ichthyosaur mean?","choices":{"A":"Giant dinosaur","B":"Fish lizard","C":"Sea monster","D":"Sharp tooth"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text gives the definition that ichthyosaur means fish lizard.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The scientists called the creature ichthyosaur, which means fish lizard.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l02-q021","read_aloud":"What does the word \"poor\" most likely mean in this sentence? A. Having a lot of money and toys B. Having very little money or possessions C. Being very happy all the time D. Being sick and unable to work","excerpt":"\"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\"","stem":"What does the word \"poor\" most likely mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Having a lot of money and toys","B":"Having very little money or possessions","C":"Being very happy all the time","D":"Being sick and unable to work"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Poor\" means not having much money. The text says Mary\u0027s life was hard, which shows she did not have many things.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l02-q022","read_aloud":"Where was Mary Anning born? A. London, England B. Lyme Regis, England C. Paris, France D. New York, America","excerpt":"\"In 1799, Mary Anning was born in Lyme Regis, a small English port tucked tightly between cliffs and coast.\"","stem":"Where was Mary Anning born?","choices":{"A":"London, England","B":"Lyme Regis, England","C":"Paris, France","D":"New York, America"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says Mary Anning was born in Lyme Regis, a small English port.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1799, Mary Anning was born in Lyme Regis, a small English port tucked tightly between cliffs and coast.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l02-q023","read_aloud":"Who taught Mary and Joseph how to hunt for fossils? A. Their mother B. Their teacher C. Their father Richard Anning D. Their neighbor Mrs. Stock","excerpt":"\"Mary and her older brother, Joseph, were just a few years old when they began visiting the nearby rocky beaches with their father. Richard Anning taught them how to hunt for fossils.\"","stem":"Who taught Mary and Joseph how to hunt for fossils?","choices":{"A":"Their mother","B":"Their teacher","C":"Their father Richard Anning","D":"Their neighbor Mrs. Stock"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says \"Richard Anning taught them how to hunt for fossils.\" Richard Anning was their father.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary and her older brother, Joseph, were just a few years old when they began visiting the nearby rocky beaches with their father. Richard Anning taught them how to hunt for fossils.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l02-q024","read_aloud":"What happened to Mary during the storm when she was a baby? A. She was not outside during the storm B. She was the only one who survived the lightning strike C. She was hiding in a cave D. She ran away from her nursemaid","excerpt":"\"Mary\u0027s life started with a bang-the bang of thunder. Infant Mary was outdoors with her nursemaid when a sudden and terrible storm burst. The nursemaid grabbed Mary and, with two other young women, raced to the cover of a nearby elm. The sky exploded and lightning struck the tree! Only Mary survived.\"","stem":"What happened to Mary during the storm when she was a baby?","choices":{"A":"She was not outside during the storm","B":"She was the only one who survived the lightning strike","C":"She was hiding in a cave","D":"She ran away from her nursemaid"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says \"Only Mary survived\" after lightning struck the tree where the group was hiding.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary\u0027s life started with a bang-the bang of thunder. Infant Mary was outdoors with her nursemaid when a sudden and terrible storm burst. The nursemaid grabbed Mary and, with two other young women, raced to the cover of a nearby elm. The sky exploded and lightning struck the tree! Only Mary survived.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l02-q025","read_aloud":"What are fossils? A. Rocks that are found only in the ocean B. The remains of animals or plants that lived long ago C. Jewels that are hidden underground D. Tools that ancient people made from stone","excerpt":"\"Fossils were strange and mysterious. Although they had been found before, scientists were just beginning to understand that they were the remains of animals or plants that no longer existed, living things that had died many, many years ago.\"","stem":"What are fossils?","choices":{"A":"Rocks that are found only in the ocean","B":"The remains of animals or plants that lived long ago","C":"Jewels that are hidden underground","D":"Tools that ancient people made from stone"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says fossils are \"the remains of animals or plants that no longer existed, living things that had died many, many years ago.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Fossils were strange and mysterious. Although they had been found before, scientists were just beginning to understand that they were the remains of animals or plants that no longer existed, living things that had died many, many years ago.\""}]},{"level":3,"level_name":"Level 3","difficulty_band":"developing","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l03-q001","read_aloud":"What does the word \"geology\" mean in this sentence? A. The study of animals and their habitats B. The study of rocks, mountains, and the earth C. The study of weather and storms D. The study of ancient human history","excerpt":"\"Mary still collected fossils and also earned money from small jobs she did for her neighbors. One of them, Mrs. Stock, gave her a geology book. From it Mary learned about rocks and mountains and the earth.\"","stem":"What does the word \"geology\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"The study of animals and their habitats","B":"The study of rocks, mountains, and the earth","C":"The study of weather and storms","D":"The study of ancient human history"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says from the geology book Mary learned \"about rocks and mountains and the earth,\" so geology is the study of those things.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary still collected fossils and also earned money from small jobs she did for her neighbors. One of them, Mrs. Stock, gave her a geology book. From it Mary learned about rocks and mountains and the earth.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l03-q002","read_aloud":"How did Mary learn about science even though she had to leave school early? A. She went to a university B. She taught herself by reading books C. Her father taught her at home D. She learned from the tourists","excerpt":"\"Mary still collected fossils and also earned money from small jobs she did for her neighbors. One of them, Mrs. Stock, gave her a geology book. From it Mary learned about rocks and mountains and the earth. She read other books and taught herself about animals, fish, and fossils.\"","stem":"How did Mary learn about science even though she had to leave school early?","choices":{"A":"She went to a university","B":"She taught herself by reading books","C":"Her father taught her at home","D":"She learned from the tourists"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says she \"read other books and taught herself about animals, fish, and fossils.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary still collected fossils and also earned money from small jobs she did for her neighbors. One of them, Mrs. Stock, gave her a geology book. From it Mary learned about rocks and mountains and the earth. She read other books and taught herself about animals, fish, and fossils.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l03-q003","read_aloud":"What did Mary\u0027s family have to do to pay their rent? A. Move to a smaller house B. Sell their furniture C. Borrow money from friends D. Stop collecting fossils","excerpt":"\"Years passed. When Mary was twenty years old, she and her mother and brother were still living together. They remained very poor and even sold their furniture to pay their rent.\"","stem":"What did Mary\u0027s family have to do to pay their rent?","choices":{"A":"Move to a smaller house","B":"Sell their furniture","C":"Borrow money from friends","D":"Stop collecting fossils"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says \"they remained very poor and even sold their furniture to pay their rent.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Years passed. When Mary was twenty years old, she and her mother and brother were still living together. They remained very poor and even sold their furniture to pay their rent.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l03-q004","read_aloud":"What does it mean that Mary made collecting fossils \"her life\u0027s work\"? A. She collected fossils only as a hobby B. She spent her whole life working on collecting fossils C. She collected fossils for one summer D. She taught other people how to collect fossils","excerpt":"\"Joseph became an upholsterer and Mary collected fossils alone. She made it her life\u0027s work.\"","stem":"What does it mean that Mary made collecting fossils \"her life\u0027s work\"?","choices":{"A":"She collected fossils only as a hobby","B":"She spent her whole life working on collecting fossils","C":"She collected fossils for one summer","D":"She taught other people how to collect fossils"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Life\u0027s work\" means something you do for most of your life. Mary continued collecting fossils as her main activity.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Joseph became an upholsterer and Mary collected fossils alone. She made it her life\u0027s work.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l03-q005","read_aloud":"What does the phrase \"Mary\u0027s great delight\" tell you about how she felt about collecting fossils? A. She was forced to do it by her family B. She truly loved doing it C. She found it boring D. She only did it for money","excerpt":"\"It also must have been Mary\u0027s great delight because she pursued it despite the dangers on the rocky shore. Boulders fell from the cliffs, torrents of thick black mud slid down from the heights, high seas pummeled the shore, and waves could sweep a careless visitor away.\"","stem":"What does the phrase \"Mary\u0027s great delight\" tell you about how she felt about collecting fossils?","choices":{"A":"She was forced to do it by her family","B":"She truly loved doing it","C":"She found it boring","D":"She only did it for money"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Great delight\" means something that makes you very happy. Mary loved collecting fossils even though it was dangerous.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It also must have been Mary\u0027s great delight because she pursued it despite the dangers on the rocky shore. Boulders fell from the cliffs, torrents of thick black mud slid down from the heights, high seas pummeled the shore, and waves could sweep a careless visitor away.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l03-q006","read_aloud":"What does \"treacherous\" mean in this sentence? A. safe and easy to walk on B. unsafe because of hidden dangers C. colorful and beautiful D. flat and smooth","excerpt":"Day after day, Mary searched in the shadows of the treacherous cliffs, sometimes walking ten miles in one day.","stem":"What does \"treacherous\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"safe and easy to walk on","B":"unsafe because of hidden dangers","C":"colorful and beautiful","D":"flat and smooth"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Treacherous means dangerous with hidden risks, like falling rocks or mudslides. The other choices do not fit.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Day after day, Mary searched in the shadows of the treacherous cliffs, sometimes walking ten miles in one day."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l03-q007","read_aloud":"How do fossils form, according to the text? A. Animals and plants turn into water quickly. B. Remains are covered, undisturbed for millions of years, and minerals turn them to stone. C. People dig them up right after an animal dies. D. Rocks grow around living animals.","excerpt":"Usually the remains of plants and animals decompose or are eaten, but sometimes they are covered by dirt or sink in mud. Of these, a rare few lie undisturbed for millions of years.","stem":"How do fossils form, according to the text?","choices":{"A":"Animals and plants turn into water quickly.","B":"Remains are covered, undisturbed for millions of years, and minerals turn them to stone.","C":"People dig them up right after an animal dies.","D":"Rocks grow around living animals."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains the process: remains get covered, stay undisturbed, and minerals turn them to stone. The other choices are incorrect.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Usually the remains of plants and animals decompose or are eaten, but sometimes they are covered by dirt or sink in mud. Of these, a rare few lie undisturbed for millions of years."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l03-q008","read_aloud":"Where did Mary sell her fossils? A. at a big museum in London B. from a small shop on Broad Street C. at the beach to tourists D. in her father\u0027s carpentry shop","excerpt":"Mary sold her treasures from a small, cluttered shop on Broad Street. There she freed her latest discoveries from dirt, sand, and rock.","stem":"Where did Mary sell her fossils?","choices":{"A":"at a big museum in London","B":"from a small shop on Broad Street","C":"at the beach to tourists","D":"in her father\u0027s carpentry shop"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says Mary sold fossils from her shop on Broad Street. The other places are not mentioned for selling.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Mary sold her treasures from a small, cluttered shop on Broad Street. There she freed her latest discoveries from dirt, sand, and rock."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l03-q009","read_aloud":"What did Mary discover in 1823? A. the first complete plesiosaur fossil B. a dinosaur egg C. a map of the ocean D. a new type of rock","excerpt":"In 1823, Mary discovered the first complete fossil of a plesiosaur, another reptile that had lived in the sea.","stem":"What did Mary discover in 1823?","choices":{"A":"the first complete plesiosaur fossil","B":"a dinosaur egg","C":"a map of the ocean","D":"a new type of rock"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text directly states Mary found the first complete plesiosaur fossil in 1823. The other items are not mentioned.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: In 1823, Mary discovered the first complete fossil of a plesiosaur, another reptile that had lived in the sea."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l03-q010","read_aloud":"What happened as people learned about Mary\u0027s work? A. Her fame grew. B. She moved to a new country. C. She stopped collecting fossils. D. She became a teacher.","excerpt":"Mary Anning\u0027s fame grew as people learned that she was an extraordinary fossil collector and a talented scientist.","stem":"What happened as people learned about Mary\u0027s work?","choices":{"A":"Her fame grew.","B":"She moved to a new country.","C":"She stopped collecting fossils.","D":"She became a teacher."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says Mary\u0027s fame grew as people recognized her skills. The other events are not in the text.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Mary Anning\u0027s fame grew as people learned that she was an extraordinary fossil collector and a talented scientist."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l03-q011","read_aloud":"What does labored mean in this sentence? A. They played games B. They worked very hard C. They took a nap D. They gave up quickly","excerpt":"\"She and a helper labored to recover it.\"","stem":"What does labored mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"They played games","B":"They worked very hard","C":"They took a nap","D":"They gave up quickly"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The word labored means worked hard. In the story, Mary and her helper work hard to get the fossil out of the ground.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"She and a helper labored to recover it.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l03-q012","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this paragraph? A. Mary had a messy shop B. Mary worked hard to clean, study, and understand her fossils C. Mary did not like science books D. Mary gave away all her fossils","excerpt":"\"Mary sold her treasures from a small, cluttered shop on Broad Street. There she freed her latest discoveries from dirt, sand, and rock. Mary worked very carefully... She drew pictures of them. She studied her science books.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this paragraph?","choices":{"A":"Mary had a messy shop","B":"Mary worked hard to clean, study, and understand her fossils","C":"Mary did not like science books","D":"Mary gave away all her fossils"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The paragraph tells many things Mary did: freed fossils from dirt, worked carefully, drew pictures, and studied books. All these show she worked hard to understand her fossils.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary sold her treasures from a small, cluttered shop on Broad Street. There she freed her latest discoveries from dirt, sand, and rock. Mary worked very carefully... She drew pictures of them. She studied her science books.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l03-q013","read_aloud":"What can you infer about Mary from this excerpt? A. She did not like to read B. She was eager to learn and taught herself C. She only listened to teachers D. She gave up when things were hard","excerpt":"\"One of them, Mrs. Stock, gave her a geology book. From it Mary learned about rocks and mountains and the earth. She read other books and taught herself about animals, fish, and fossils.\"","stem":"What can you infer about Mary from this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"She did not like to read","B":"She was eager to learn and taught herself","C":"She only listened to teachers","D":"She gave up when things were hard"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Mary read books and \"taught herself\" about many science topics. This shows she was eager to learn and did it on her own.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"One of them, Mrs. Stock, gave her a geology book. From it Mary learned about rocks and mountains and the earth. She read other books and taught herself about animals, fish, and fossils.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l03-q014","read_aloud":"What does this sentence tell us about Mary? A. She was afraid of the shore B. She loved fossil hunting even though it was dangerous C. She only hunted fossils on safe days D. She did not find many fossils","excerpt":"\"It also must have been Mary\u0027s great delight because she pursued it despite the dangers on the rocky shore.\"","stem":"What does this sentence tell us about Mary?","choices":{"A":"She was afraid of the shore","B":"She loved fossil hunting even though it was dangerous","C":"She only hunted fossils on safe days","D":"She did not find many fossils"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says fossil hunting \"must have been Mary\u0027s great delight\" and she \"pursued it despite the dangers.\" Despite means even though there were dangers, she still did it because she loved it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It also must have been Mary\u0027s great delight because she pursued it despite the dangers on the rocky shore.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l03-q015","read_aloud":"What does \"life\u0027s work\" mean? A. A job she did for a few days B. Something she would do for her whole life C. A hobby she did once a year D. Work she did for her brother","excerpt":"\"Joseph became an upholsterer and Mary collected fossils alone. She made it her life\u0027s work.\"","stem":"What does \"life\u0027s work\" mean?","choices":{"A":"A job she did for a few days","B":"Something she would do for her whole life","C":"A hobby she did once a year","D":"Work she did for her brother"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Life\u0027s work\" means the main work or purpose of a person\u0027s whole life. Mary decided collecting fossils would be her forever job.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Joseph became an upholsterer and Mary collected fossils alone. She made it her life\u0027s work.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l03-q016","read_aloud":"What does the word treacherous mean in this sentence? A. Safe and warm B. Very beautiful C. Unsafe because of hidden dangers D. Easy to climb","excerpt":"\"Day after day, Mary searched in the shadows of the treacherous cliffs, sometimes walking ten miles in one day.\"","stem":"What does the word treacherous mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Safe and warm","B":"Very beautiful","C":"Unsafe because of hidden dangers","D":"Easy to climb"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Treacherous means dangerous or unsafe because of hidden dangers, like falling rocks.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Day after day, Mary searched in the shadows of the treacherous cliffs, sometimes walking ten miles in one day.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l03-q017","read_aloud":"How did Mary learn about geology? A. She went to a university. B. A teacher taught her in school. C. She read a book from Mrs. Stock. D. Her father explained it to her.","excerpt":"\"One of them, Mrs. Stock, gave her a geology book. From it Mary learned about rocks and mountains and the earth.\"","stem":"How did Mary learn about geology?","choices":{"A":"She went to a university.","B":"A teacher taught her in school.","C":"She read a book from Mrs. Stock.","D":"Her father explained it to her."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Mrs. Stock gave her a geology book, and Mary learned from reading it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"One of them, Mrs. Stock, gave her a geology book. From it Mary learned about rocks and mountains and the earth.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l03-q018","read_aloud":"Where did Mary work on her fossils? A. In a large museum B. On the beach C. In a small shop D. At her home","excerpt":"\"Mary sold her treasures from a small, cluttered shop on Broad Street. There she freed her latest discoveries from dirt, sand, and rock.\"","stem":"Where did Mary work on her fossils?","choices":{"A":"In a large museum","B":"On the beach","C":"In a small shop","D":"At her home"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says she sold treasures and worked on them in a small shop on Broad Street.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary sold her treasures from a small, cluttered shop on Broad Street. There she freed her latest discoveries from dirt, sand, and rock.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l03-q019","read_aloud":"Why did Mary work carefully for days? A. She was tired and needed rest. B. She wanted to finish quickly. C. She wanted to keep the fossils safe. D. She did not know what to do.","excerpt":"\"Mary worked very carefully, sometimes for days, to avoid damaging the fossils.\"","stem":"Why did Mary work carefully for days?","choices":{"A":"She was tired and needed rest.","B":"She wanted to finish quickly.","C":"She wanted to keep the fossils safe.","D":"She did not know what to do."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"She worked carefully to avoid damaging the fossils so they would remain perfect.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary worked very carefully, sometimes for days, to avoid damaging the fossils.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l03-q020","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. Having a lot of money and toys B. Having very little money or possessions C. Being very happy all the time D. Being sick and unable to work","excerpt":"\"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"Having a lot of money and toys","B":"Having very little money or possessions","C":"Being very happy all the time","D":"Being sick and unable to work"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Poor\" means not having much money. The text says Mary\u0027s life was hard, which shows she did not have many things.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l03-q021","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. Having a lot of money and toys B. Having very little money or possessions C. Being very happy all the time D. Being sick and unable to work","excerpt":"\"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"Having a lot of money and toys","B":"Having very little money or possessions","C":"Being very happy all the time","D":"Being sick and unable to work"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Poor\" means not having much money. The text says Mary\u0027s life was hard, which shows she did not have many things.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l03-q022","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? A. Having a lot of money and toys B. Having very little money or possessions C. Being very happy all the time D. Being sick and unable to work","excerpt":"\"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ?","choices":{"A":"Having a lot of money and toys","B":"Having very little money or possessions","C":"Being very happy all the time","D":"Being sick and unable to work"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Poor\" means not having much money. The text says Mary\u0027s life was hard, which shows she did not have many things.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l03-q023","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. The dog was afraid of Mary B. The dog was a loyal companion and helper C. The dog did not like going on fossil hunts D. The dog was trained by Mary\u0027s father","excerpt":"\"Mary\u0027s dog trotted faithfully beside her. People said the dog guarded her discoveries while she fetched her tools or got help.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"The dog was afraid of Mary","B":"The dog was a loyal companion and helper","C":"The dog did not like going on fossil hunts","D":"The dog was trained by Mary\u0027s father"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The dog trotted faithfully beside Mary and guarded her discoveries, which shows the dog was loyal and helpful.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary\u0027s dog trotted faithfully beside her. People said the dog guarded her discoveries while she fetched her tools or got help.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l03-q024","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. Seven feet long B. Nine feet long C. Twelve feet long D. Three feet long","excerpt":"\"In 1823, Mary discovered the first complete fossil of a plesiosaur, another reptile that had lived in the sea. It was an astonishing nine-foot-long creature with a long, serpentlike neck, a lizard\u0027s head, a crocodile\u0027s teeth, a chameleon\u0027s ribs, and the paddles of a whale.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"Seven feet long","B":"Nine feet long","C":"Twelve feet long","D":"Three feet long"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says \"It was an astonishing nine-foot-long creature.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1823, Mary discovered the first complete fossil of a plesiosaur, another reptile that had lived in the sea. It was an astonishing nine-foot-long creature with a long, serpentlike neck, a lizard\u0027s head, a crocodile\u0027s teeth, a chameleon\u0027s ribs, and the paddles of a whale.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l03-q025","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. To show that Mary was not a good fossil hunter B. To show that Mary did not receive the credit she deserved at first C. To show that Joseph found more fossils than Mary D. To show that fossils were not important discoveries","excerpt":"\"Almost everyone forgot that it had been found by twelve-year-old Mary Anning and her teenage brother.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"To show that Mary was not a good fossil hunter","B":"To show that Mary did not receive the credit she deserved at first","C":"To show that Joseph found more fossils than Mary","D":"To show that fossils were not important discoveries"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author includes this detail to show that even though Mary made an important discovery, people did not give her credit because she was young.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Almost everyone forgot that it had been found by twelve-year-old Mary Anning and her teenage brother.\""}]},{"level":4,"level_name":"Level 4","difficulty_band":"developing","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l04-q001","read_aloud":"What does the word \"astonishing\" mean in this sentence? A. Very small and hard to see B. Very surprising and amazing C. Very common and boring D. Very scary and dangerous","excerpt":"\"In 1823, Mary discovered the first complete fossil of a plesiosaur, another reptile that had lived in the sea. It was an astonishing nine-foot-long creature with a long, serpentlike neck, a lizard\u0027s head, a crocodile\u0027s teeth, a chameleon\u0027s ribs, and the paddles of a whale.\"","stem":"What does the word \"astonishing\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Very small and hard to see","B":"Very surprising and amazing","C":"Very common and boring","D":"Very scary and dangerous"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Astonishing\" means something is so surprising and wonderful that it amazes people. A nine-foot-long fossil creature would be astonishing.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1823, Mary discovered the first complete fossil of a plesiosaur, another reptile that had lived in the sea. It was an astonishing nine-foot-long creature with a long, serpentlike neck, a lizard\u0027s head, a crocodile\u0027s teeth, a chameleon\u0027s ribs, and the paddles of a whale.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l04-q002","read_aloud":"Why were scientists excited about Mary\u0027s plesiosaur fossil? A. Because it was worth a lot of money B. Because it was a rare clue to solving the puzzle of life long ago C. Because it was the smallest fossil ever found D. Because it was found near a volcano","excerpt":"\"The discovery excited scientists. Like Mary\u0027s earlier find, the ichthyosaur fossil, it was a rare clue to solving the puzzle of life long ago. What creature had become this jumble of bones trapped in rock? How did it move? What did it eat? How was it like modern creatures?\"","stem":"Why were scientists excited about Mary\u0027s plesiosaur fossil?","choices":{"A":"Because it was worth a lot of money","B":"Because it was a rare clue to solving the puzzle of life long ago","C":"Because it was the smallest fossil ever found","D":"Because it was found near a volcano"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the fossil was \"a rare clue to solving the puzzle of life long ago.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The discovery excited scientists. Like Mary\u0027s earlier find, the ichthyosaur fossil, it was a rare clue to solving the puzzle of life long ago. What creature had become this jumble of bones trapped in rock? How did it move? What did it eat? How was it like modern creatures?\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l04-q003","read_aloud":"How did people show that they respected Mary\u0027s skills? A. They gave her money and gifts B. They followed her on fossil hunts C. They built a museum for her fossils D. They wrote books about her life","excerpt":"\"Mary Anning\u0027s fame grew as people learned that she was an extraordinary fossil collector and a talented scientist. People followed her on fossil hunts. Together they plodded over the rough rocks, waded knee-deep in water, and scrambled up the cliffs to avoid the crashing waves.\"","stem":"How did people show that they respected Mary\u0027s skills?","choices":{"A":"They gave her money and gifts","B":"They followed her on fossil hunts","C":"They built a museum for her fossils","D":"They wrote books about her life"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says \"People followed her on fossil hunts,\" which shows they trusted her knowledge and skill.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary Anning\u0027s fame grew as people learned that she was an extraordinary fossil collector and a talented scientist. People followed her on fossil hunts. Together they plodded over the rough rocks, waded knee-deep in water, and scrambled up the cliffs to avoid the crashing waves.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l04-q004","read_aloud":"What does this detail reveal about Mary\u0027s character? A. She was weak and needed help B. She was strong and brave C. She was afraid of the water D. She did not like children","excerpt":"\"Once Mary had to rescue a teenager, Anna Maria Pinney, from rough water. Pinney said Mary carried her with the \u0027same ease as you would a baby.\u0027\"","stem":"What does this detail reveal about Mary\u0027s character?","choices":{"A":"She was weak and needed help","B":"She was strong and brave","C":"She was afraid of the water","D":"She did not like children"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Mary rescued a teenager and carried her easily, which shows Mary was strong and brave enough to help someone in danger.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Once Mary had to rescue a teenager, Anna Maria Pinney, from rough water. Pinney said Mary carried her with the \u0027same ease as you would a baby.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l04-q005","read_aloud":"What do the visits from famous scientists tell you about Mary? A. She was not well known B. She was respected and recognized for her knowledge C. She paid them to come visit her D. She wanted to become famous like them","excerpt":"\"William Buckland, a famous geologist, brought his family to Lyme Regis to meet Mary and to search for fossils. She escorted Buckland and his children on fossil hunts. Richard Owens, the scientist who invented the word dinosaur, also combed the beach with Mary.\"","stem":"What do the visits from famous scientists tell you about Mary?","choices":{"A":"She was not well known","B":"She was respected and recognized for her knowledge","C":"She paid them to come visit her","D":"She wanted to become famous like them"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Famous scientists would not travel to meet someone unless that person was respected and knowledgeable.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"William Buckland, a famous geologist, brought his family to Lyme Regis to meet Mary and to search for fossils. She escorted Buckland and his children on fossil hunts. Richard Owens, the scientist who invented the word dinosaur, also combed the beach with Mary.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l04-q006","read_aloud":"Which word means almost the same as \"remarkable\"? A. ordinary and common B. extraordinary or outstanding C. small and unimportant D. broken and old","excerpt":"Mary\u0027s pterodactyl was displayed at the British Natural History Museum and is still there today.","stem":"Which word means almost the same as \"remarkable\"?","choices":{"A":"ordinary and common","B":"extraordinary or outstanding","C":"small and unimportant","D":"broken and old"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Remarkable means special and outstanding. The other choices are opposites or unrelated.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Mary\u0027s pterodactyl was displayed at the British Natural History Museum and is still there today."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l04-q007","read_aloud":"Why did the Anning family sell fossils? A. To give them away as gifts. B. To earn extra money to help the family survive. C. To teach tourists about science. D. To fill their shop with decorations.","excerpt":"The Annings displayed the puzzling yet delightful fossils that they found on a table near Richard\u0027s shop on Bridge Street. Wealthy tourists visiting the popular Lyme Regis shore bought them.","stem":"Why did the Anning family sell fossils?","choices":{"A":"To give them away as gifts.","B":"To earn extra money to help the family survive.","C":"To teach tourists about science.","D":"To fill their shop with decorations."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the family struggled, and selling fossils helped them earn money. The other reasons are not stated.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Annings displayed the puzzling yet delightful fossils that they found on a table near Richard\u0027s shop on Bridge Street. Wealthy tourists visiting the popular Lyme Regis shore bought them."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l04-q008","read_aloud":"What caused new fossils to be found on the beach? A. Tourists digging with shovels B. Cliffs crumbling and wearing away C. Scientists sending teams to search D. Mary planting fossils in the sand","excerpt":"But the beach was rich in fossils. As the cliffs crumbled, new fossils were revealed.","stem":"What caused new fossils to be found on the beach?","choices":{"A":"Tourists digging with shovels","B":"Cliffs crumbling and wearing away","C":"Scientists sending teams to search","D":"Mary planting fossils in the sand"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says as cliffs crumbled, new fossils were revealed. The other causes are not mentioned.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: But the beach was rich in fossils. As the cliffs crumbled, new fossils were revealed."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l04-q009","read_aloud":"If Mary taught herself about fossils, what did she likely do? A. Waited for a teacher to tell her everything. B. Read books and learned on her own. C. Asked tourists to teach her. D. Only collected fossils without studying.","excerpt":"Mary read other books and taught herself about animals, fish, and fossils.","stem":"If Mary taught herself about fossils, what did she likely do?","choices":{"A":"Waited for a teacher to tell her everything.","B":"Read books and learned on her own.","C":"Asked tourists to teach her.","D":"Only collected fossils without studying."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Teaching herself means Mary learned by reading and studying alone. The other choices do not match \"taught herself.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Mary read other books and taught herself about animals, fish, and fossils."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l04-q010","read_aloud":"(Note: This excerpt is from Reaching for the Moon; replacing with Rare Treasure excerpt) Why did scientists value Mary\u0027s ideas even though she left school early? A. Because she was rich and famous. B. Because she knew a lot about fossils from her own study and experience. C. Because she worked for the museum. D. Because she had a college degree.","excerpt":"Mary shared her ideas with the finest scientists. They prized the thoughts of the remarkable young woman who had left school when she was eleven.","stem":"(Note: This excerpt is from Reaching for the Moon; replacing with Rare Treasure excerpt) Why did scientists value Mary\u0027s ideas even though she left school early?","choices":{"A":"Because she was rich and famous.","B":"Because she knew a lot about fossils from her own study and experience.","C":"Because she worked for the museum.","D":"Because she had a college degree."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text shows Mary learned on her own and knew more than others about fossils. Her knowledge, not her schooling, made scientists value her.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Mary shared her ideas with the finest scientists. They prized the thoughts of the remarkable young woman who had left school when she was eleven."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l04-q011","read_aloud":"What does pursued mean in this sentence? A. She stopped doing it B. She worked without stopping to accomplish something C. She forgot about it D. She only talked about it","excerpt":"\"Mary pursued it despite the dangers on the rocky shore.\"","stem":"What does pursued mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"She stopped doing it","B":"She worked without stopping to accomplish something","C":"She forgot about it","D":"She only talked about it"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says Mary pursued fossil hunting despite dangers. Pursued means she kept working at it without stopping, even when it was hard or dangerous.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary pursued it despite the dangers on the rocky shore.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l04-q012","read_aloud":"How are these three discoveries alike? A. They were all found by Mary in different years B. They were all found by Joseph C. They were all the same creature D. They were all found in museums","excerpt":"\"In 1811, Mary found a fossilized skeleton... The scientists called the creature ichthyosaur... In 1823, Mary discovered the first complete fossil of a plesiosaur... In 1828, Mary discovered a very rare fossil of a pterodactyl.\"","stem":"How are these three discoveries alike?","choices":{"A":"They were all found by Mary in different years","B":"They were all found by Joseph","C":"They were all the same creature","D":"They were all found in museums"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text shows Mary found all three fossils: ichthyosaur in 1811, plesiosaur in 1823, and pterodactyl in 1828. They were found by Mary in different years.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1811, Mary found a fossilized skeleton... The scientists called the creature ichthyosaur... In 1823, Mary discovered the first complete fossil of a plesiosaur... In 1828, Mary discovered a very rare fossil of a pterodactyl.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l04-q013","read_aloud":"Why were scientists excited about Mary\u0027s discovery? A. Because it was pretty B. Because it helped them learn about life long ago C. Because Mary was famous D. Because it was very small","excerpt":"\"The discovery excited scientists. Like Mary\u0027s earlier find, the ichthyosaur fossil, it was a rare clue to solving the puzzle of life long ago.\"","stem":"Why were scientists excited about Mary\u0027s discovery?","choices":{"A":"Because it was pretty","B":"Because it helped them learn about life long ago","C":"Because Mary was famous","D":"Because it was very small"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the fossil was \"a rare clue to solving the puzzle of life long ago.\" This means it helped scientists learn about animals from millions of years ago.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The discovery excited scientists. Like Mary\u0027s earlier find, the ichthyosaur fossil, it was a rare clue to solving the puzzle of life long ago.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l04-q014","read_aloud":"Why is asking questions important in science, according to this excerpt? A. Questions help scientists learn and understand new things B. Questions make scientists confused C. Questions are not important D. Questions only waste time","excerpt":"\"Answering these questions helped reveal the ancient world in which the plesiosaur had lived.\"","stem":"Why is asking questions important in science, according to this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"Questions help scientists learn and understand new things","B":"Questions make scientists confused","C":"Questions are not important","D":"Questions only waste time"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says \"Answering these questions helped reveal the ancient world.\" This means questions help scientists learn and understand things they did not know before.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Answering these questions helped reveal the ancient world in which the plesiosaur had lived.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l04-q015","read_aloud":"Why did Mary\u0027s fame grow? A. Because she found many important fossils and was very good at science B. Because she moved to London C. Because she stopped collecting fossils D. Because she wrote a book","excerpt":"\"Mary Anning\u0027s fame grew as people learned that she was an extraordinary fossil collector and a talented scientist.\"","stem":"Why did Mary\u0027s fame grow?","choices":{"A":"Because she found many important fossils and was very good at science","B":"Because she moved to London","C":"Because she stopped collecting fossils","D":"Because she wrote a book"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says her fame grew \"as people learned that she was an extraordinary fossil collector and a talented scientist.\" People learned about her skills, so she became more famous.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary Anning\u0027s fame grew as people learned that she was an extraordinary fossil collector and a talented scientist.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l04-q016","read_aloud":"What does the word remarkable mean in this sentence? A. Ordinary and plain B. Unhappy and sad C. Extraordinary or outstanding D. Young and small","excerpt":"\"They prized the thoughts of the remarkable young woman who had left school when she was eleven.\"","stem":"What does the word remarkable mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Ordinary and plain","B":"Unhappy and sad","C":"Extraordinary or outstanding","D":"Young and small"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Remarkable means someone or something is extraordinary or outstanding because of their skills.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They prized the thoughts of the remarkable young woman who had left school when she was eleven.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l04-q017","read_aloud":"Why did William Buckland come to Lyme Regis? A. To buy a shop B. To meet Mary and search for fossils C. To teach Mary about rocks D. To visit the seaside","excerpt":"\"William Buckland, a famous geologist, brought his family to Lyme Regis to meet Mary and to search for fossils.\"","stem":"Why did William Buckland come to Lyme Regis?","choices":{"A":"To buy a shop","B":"To meet Mary and search for fossils","C":"To teach Mary about rocks","D":"To visit the seaside"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says he brought his family specifically to meet Mary and search for fossils.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"William Buckland, a famous geologist, brought his family to Lyme Regis to meet Mary and to search for fossils.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l04-q018","read_aloud":"What does this detail show about Mary? A. She liked to swim for fun. B. She was very strong and helpful. C. She was afraid of the water. D. She knew Anna Maria very well.","excerpt":"\"Once Mary had to rescue a teenager, Anna Maria Pinney, from rough water. Pinney said Mary carried her with the \u0027same ease as you would a baby.\u0027\"","stem":"What does this detail show about Mary?","choices":{"A":"She liked to swim for fun.","B":"She was very strong and helpful.","C":"She was afraid of the water.","D":"She knew Anna Maria very well."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Rescuing someone from rough water shows that Mary was strong and willing to help others.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Once Mary had to rescue a teenager, Anna Maria Pinney, from rough water. Pinney said Mary carried her with the \u0027same ease as you would a baby.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l04-q019","read_aloud":"Why did Mary find fossils that others missed? A. She had a special machine. B. The dog found them for her. C. She had sharp eyes and paid attention. D. She was just lucky.","excerpt":"\"Her sharp eyes spotted fossils where others saw nothing. Mary\u0027s dog trotted faithfully beside her.\"","stem":"Why did Mary find fossils that others missed?","choices":{"A":"She had a special machine.","B":"The dog found them for her.","C":"She had sharp eyes and paid attention.","D":"She was just lucky."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says her \"sharp eyes\" spotted fossils where others saw nothing, meaning she looked closely.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Her sharp eyes spotted fossils where others saw nothing. Mary\u0027s dog trotted faithfully beside her.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l04-q020","read_aloud":"Why did Mary not notice the rising tide? A. She was focused on her hard work. B. She did not know how to swim. C. It was too dark to see. D. The helper did not tell her.","excerpt":"\"Another time, Mary found a large fossil. She and a helper labored to recover it. The hard work blinded Mary to the rising tide that flooded the beach.\"","stem":"Why did Mary not notice the rising tide?","choices":{"A":"She was focused on her hard work.","B":"She did not know how to swim.","C":"It was too dark to see.","D":"The helper did not tell her."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says the hard work \"blinded Mary,\" meaning she was so focused on the fossil she forgot to look at the water.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Another time, Mary found a large fossil. She and a helper labored to recover it. The hard work blinded Mary to the rising tide that flooded the beach.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l04-q021","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. Having a lot of money and toys B. Having very little money or possessions C. Being very happy all the time D. Being sick and unable to work","excerpt":"\"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"Having a lot of money and toys","B":"Having very little money or possessions","C":"Being very happy all the time","D":"Being sick and unable to work"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Poor\" means not having much money. The text says Mary\u0027s life was hard, which shows she did not have many things.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l04-q022","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. Having a lot of money and toys B. Having very little money or possessions C. Being very happy all the time D. Being sick and unable to work","excerpt":"\"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"Having a lot of money and toys","B":"Having very little money or possessions","C":"Being very happy all the time","D":"Being sick and unable to work"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Poor\" means not having much money. The text says Mary\u0027s life was hard, which shows she did not have many things.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l04-q023","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? A. Having a lot of money and toys B. Having very little money or possessions C. Being very happy all the time D. Being sick and unable to work","excerpt":"\"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ?","choices":{"A":"Having a lot of money and toys","B":"Having very little money or possessions","C":"Being very happy all the time","D":"Being sick and unable to work"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Poor\" means not having much money. The text says Mary\u0027s life was hard, which shows she did not have many things.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l04-q024","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. The dog was afraid of Mary B. The dog was a loyal companion and helper C. The dog did not like going on fossil hunts D. The dog was trained by Mary\u0027s father","excerpt":"\"Mary\u0027s dog trotted faithfully beside her. People said the dog guarded her discoveries while she fetched her tools or got help.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"The dog was afraid of Mary","B":"The dog was a loyal companion and helper","C":"The dog did not like going on fossil hunts","D":"The dog was trained by Mary\u0027s father"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The dog trotted faithfully beside Mary and guarded her discoveries, which shows the dog was loyal and helpful.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary\u0027s dog trotted faithfully beside her. People said the dog guarded her discoveries while she fetched her tools or got help.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l04-q025","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. Seven feet long B. Nine feet long C. Twelve feet long D. Three feet long","excerpt":"\"In 1823, Mary discovered the first complete fossil of a plesiosaur, another reptile that had lived in the sea. It was an astonishing nine-foot-long creature with a long, serpentlike neck, a lizard\u0027s head, a crocodile\u0027s teeth, a chameleon\u0027s ribs, and the paddles of a whale.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"Seven feet long","B":"Nine feet long","C":"Twelve feet long","D":"Three feet long"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says \"It was an astonishing nine-foot-long creature.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1823, Mary discovered the first complete fossil of a plesiosaur, another reptile that had lived in the sea. It was an astonishing nine-foot-long creature with a long, serpentlike neck, a lizard\u0027s head, a crocodile\u0027s teeth, a chameleon\u0027s ribs, and the paddles of a whale.\""}]},{"level":5,"level_name":"Level 5","difficulty_band":"strategic","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l05-q001","read_aloud":"What does the word \"treacherous\" mean in this sentence? A. Safe and easy to walk on B. Unsafe because of hidden dangers C. Colorful and beautiful to see D. Very old and crumbling apart","excerpt":"\"Day after day, Mary searched in the shadows of the treacherous cliffs, sometimes walking ten miles in one day. Her sharp eyes spotted fossils where others saw nothing.\"","stem":"What does the word \"treacherous\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Safe and easy to walk on","B":"Unsafe because of hidden dangers","C":"Colorful and beautiful to see","D":"Very old and crumbling apart"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Treacherous\" means dangerous. The text mentions boulders falling and mud sliding, which are dangers of the cliffs.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Day after day, Mary searched in the shadows of the treacherous cliffs, sometimes walking ten miles in one day. Her sharp eyes spotted fossils where others saw nothing.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l05-q002","read_aloud":"What happened to Mary during one fossil hunt? A. She found her best fossil ever B. Part of a cliff collapsed and rocks nearly crushed her C. She got lost in a cave D. Her dog ran away from her","excerpt":"\"During one hunt, part of a cliff collapsed. Heavy rocks crashed at Mary\u0027s feet and nearly crushed her.\"","stem":"What happened to Mary during one fossil hunt?","choices":{"A":"She found her best fossil ever","B":"Part of a cliff collapsed and rocks nearly crushed her","C":"She got lost in a cave","D":"Her dog ran away from her"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says \"part of a cliff collapsed. Heavy rocks crashed at Mary\u0027s feet and nearly crushed her.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"During one hunt, part of a cliff collapsed. Heavy rocks crashed at Mary\u0027s feet and nearly crushed her.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l05-q003","read_aloud":"Why did Mary\u0027s helper not warn her about the rising tide? A. He did not see the tide coming B. He was ashamed to say he was frightened when Mary was not C. He wanted Mary to get wet D. He thought the tide would go back down","excerpt":"\"Another time, Mary found a large fossil. She and a helper labored to recover it. The hard work blinded Mary to the rising tide that flooded the beach. Waves drenched the pair, but they saved the treasure. Later, Mary asked the man why he hadn\u0027t warned her of the rapidly flowing tide. \u0027I was ashamed to say I was frightened when you didn\u0027t regard it,\u0027 he replied.\"","stem":"Why did Mary\u0027s helper not warn her about the rising tide?","choices":{"A":"He did not see the tide coming","B":"He was ashamed to say he was frightened when Mary was not","C":"He wanted Mary to get wet","D":"He thought the tide would go back down"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The man said, \"I was ashamed to say I was frightened when you didn\u0027t regard it,\" meaning he was embarrassed to admit his fear.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Another time, Mary found a large fossil. She and a helper labored to recover it. The hard work blinded Mary to the rising tide that flooded the beach. Waves drenched the pair, but they saved the treasure. Later, Mary asked the man why he hadn\u0027t warned her of the rapidly flowing tide. \u0027I was ashamed to say I was frightened when you didn\u0027t regard it,\u0027 he replied.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l05-q004","read_aloud":"What does the fact that Mary\u0027s pterodactyl is still in a museum today tell you about its importance? A. It was not a very interesting fossil B. It is a valuable and important piece of history C. Mary wanted it to stay in her shop D. No one wanted to buy it from Mary","excerpt":"\"In 1828, Mary discovered a very rare fossil of a pterodactyl, a flying reptile that had the body of a lizard and the snout of a crocodile. Mary\u0027s pterodactyl was displayed at the British Natural History Museum and is still there today.\"","stem":"What does the fact that Mary\u0027s pterodactyl is still in a museum today tell you about its importance?","choices":{"A":"It was not a very interesting fossil","B":"It is a valuable and important piece of history","C":"Mary wanted it to stay in her shop","D":"No one wanted to buy it from Mary"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Museums keep important and valuable items for many years. The fossil is still there because it is significant.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1828, Mary discovered a very rare fossil of a pterodactyl, a flying reptile that had the body of a lizard and the snout of a crocodile. Mary\u0027s pterodactyl was displayed at the British Natural History Museum and is still there today.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l05-q005","read_aloud":"Do you think it was impressive that Mary knew so much even though she left school at age eleven? Why? A. Yes, because she taught herself everything without much formal schooling B. No, because anyone could have done what she did C. Yes, because she had a very expensive education D. No, because scientists helped her with everything","excerpt":"\"Mary tried to make sense of her discoveries. She read her science books and studied her collection. Mary shared her ideas with the finest scientists. They prized the thoughts of the remarkable young woman who had left school when she was eleven. It was said, \u0027She knows more about the science than anyone else.\u0027\"","stem":"Do you think it was impressive that Mary knew so much even though she left school at age eleven? Why?","choices":{"A":"Yes, because she taught herself everything without much formal schooling","B":"No, because anyone could have done what she did","C":"Yes, because she had a very expensive education","D":"No, because scientists helped her with everything"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"It is impressive because Mary did not have much formal education but taught herself through reading and hard work.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary tried to make sense of her discoveries. She read her science books and studied her collection. Mary shared her ideas with the finest scientists. They prized the thoughts of the remarkable young woman who had left school when she was eleven. It was said, \u0027She knows more about the science than anyone else.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l05-q006","read_aloud":"What does \"assembled\" mean in this context? A. threw away B. put or brought together a collection C. sold quickly D. forgot about","excerpt":"By 1836, Mary had found the fossils of three ichthyosaurs, two plesiosaurs, a pterodactyl... and an untold number of small or incomplete fossils.","stem":"What does \"assembled\" mean in this context?","choices":{"A":"threw away","B":"put or brought together a collection","C":"sold quickly","D":"forgot about"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Assembled means Mary gathered and put together her fossil collection. The other choices do not match.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: By 1836, Mary had found the fossils of three ichthyosaurs, two plesiosaurs, a pterodactyl... and an untold number of small or incomplete fossils."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l05-q007","read_aloud":"What text structure does the author use to describe the plesiosaur? A. sequence (first, next, last) B. description (using details to paint a picture) C. cause and effect D. compare and contrast","excerpt":"It was an astonishing nine-foot-long creature with a long, serpentlike neck, a lizard\u0027s head, a crocodile\u0027s teeth, a chameleon\u0027s ribs, and the paddles of a whale.","stem":"What text structure does the author use to describe the plesiosaur?","choices":{"A":"sequence (first, next, last)","B":"description (using details to paint a picture)","C":"cause and effect","D":"compare and contrast"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author uses many descriptive details to help readers picture the plesiosaur. This is description text structure.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: It was an astonishing nine-foot-long creature with a long, serpentlike neck, a lizard\u0027s head, a crocodile\u0027s teeth, a chameleon\u0027s ribs, and the paddles of a whale."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l05-q008","read_aloud":"What danger did Mary face while collecting fossils? A. Getting lost in the city B. Rocks falling from cliffs C. Running out of food D. Forgetting her tools","excerpt":"During one hunt, part of a cliff collapsed. Heavy rocks crashed at Mary\u0027s feet and nearly crushed her.","stem":"What danger did Mary face while collecting fossils?","choices":{"A":"Getting lost in the city","B":"Rocks falling from cliffs","C":"Running out of food","D":"Forgetting her tools"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says cliffs collapsed and rocks nearly crushed Mary. The other dangers are not mentioned here.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: During one hunt, part of a cliff collapsed. Heavy rocks crashed at Mary\u0027s feet and nearly crushed her."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l05-q009","read_aloud":"If Mary worked carefully for days on one fossil, what does this tell us about her? A. She was in a hurry to finish. B. She valued the fossils and wanted to protect them. C. She did not like her job. D. She wanted to sell them quickly.","excerpt":"Mary worked very carefully, sometimes for days, to avoid damaging the fossils.","stem":"If Mary worked carefully for days on one fossil, what does this tell us about her?","choices":{"A":"She was in a hurry to finish.","B":"She valued the fossils and wanted to protect them.","C":"She did not like her job.","D":"She wanted to sell them quickly."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Working carefully for days shows Mary cared about the fossils and wanted to keep them safe. The other choices do not match her actions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Mary worked very carefully, sometimes for days, to avoid damaging the fossils."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l05-q010","read_aloud":"How does this sentence show a contrast in Mary\u0027s life? A. She traveled a lot but no one knew her name. B. She stayed near home but became famous around the world. C. She moved often and was forgotten. D. She never left home and no one heard of her.","excerpt":"She rarely strayed from her home, but her name became known everywhere.","stem":"How does this sentence show a contrast in Mary\u0027s life?","choices":{"A":"She traveled a lot but no one knew her name.","B":"She stayed near home but became famous around the world.","C":"She moved often and was forgotten.","D":"She never left home and no one heard of her."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The sentence contrasts staying near home with becoming widely known. This shows how her work reached far beyond where she lived.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: She rarely strayed from her home, but her name became known everywhere."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l05-q011","read_aloud":"What does treacherous mean in this sentence? A. Safe and easy to climb B. Unsafe because of hidden dangers C. Very short D. Full of flowers","excerpt":"\"Day after day, Mary searched in the shadows of the treacherous cliffs.\"","stem":"What does treacherous mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Safe and easy to climb","B":"Unsafe because of hidden dangers","C":"Very short","D":"Full of flowers"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text later tells us \"Boulders fell from the cliffs\" and \"waves could sweep a careless visitor away.\" These hidden dangers show treacherous means unsafe.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Day after day, Mary searched in the shadows of the treacherous cliffs.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l05-q012","read_aloud":"What does this sentence tell us about Mary? A. She had better eyesight than other people B. She was very good at finding fossils that others missed C. She wore special glasses D. She only looked in easy places","excerpt":"\"Her sharp eyes spotted fossils where others saw nothing.\"","stem":"What does this sentence tell us about Mary?","choices":{"A":"She had better eyesight than other people","B":"She was very good at finding fossils that others missed","C":"She wore special glasses","D":"She only looked in easy places"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Sharp eyes\" in this context means she was very good at noticing fossils. She could find them \"where others saw nothing,\" meaning other people missed them.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Her sharp eyes spotted fossils where others saw nothing.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l05-q013","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this excerpt? A. The beach was a fun place to play B. The shore where Mary worked was very dangerous C. Mary did not like the water D. The fossils were easy to find","excerpt":"\"Boulders fell from the cliffs, torrents of thick black mud slid down from the heights, high seas pummeled the shore, and waves could sweep a careless visitor away.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"The beach was a fun place to play","B":"The shore where Mary worked was very dangerous","C":"Mary did not like the water","D":"The fossils were easy to find"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"All the details-falling boulders, sliding mud, high seas, and dangerous waves-show that the shore where Mary hunted fossils was very dangerous.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Boulders fell from the cliffs, torrents of thick black mud slid down from the heights, high seas pummeled the shore, and waves could sweep a careless visitor away.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l05-q014","read_aloud":"Why does the author include this detail? A. To show that fossil hunting was dangerous B. To show that Mary was clumsy C. To show that the cliffs were pretty D. To show that Mary should stop working","excerpt":"\"During one hunt, part of a cliff collapsed. Heavy rocks crashed at Mary\u0027s feet and nearly crushed her.\"","stem":"Why does the author include this detail?","choices":{"A":"To show that fossil hunting was dangerous","B":"To show that Mary was clumsy","C":"To show that the cliffs were pretty","D":"To show that Mary should stop working"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The author tells us about rocks nearly crushing Mary to show how dangerous her work was. This helps readers understand she risked her life to find fossils.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"During one hunt, part of a cliff collapsed. Heavy rocks crashed at Mary\u0027s feet and nearly crushed her.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l05-q015","read_aloud":"What does \"blinded Mary to the rising tide\" mean? A. Mary could not see because it was dark B. Mary was so focused on her work that she did not notice the danger C. Mary did not care about the tide D. Mary had something in her eyes","excerpt":"\"Another time, Mary found a large fossil. She and a helper labored to recover it. The hard work blinded Mary to the rising tide that flooded the beach.\"","stem":"What does \"blinded Mary to the rising tide\" mean?","choices":{"A":"Mary could not see because it was dark","B":"Mary was so focused on her work that she did not notice the danger","C":"Mary did not care about the tide","D":"Mary had something in her eyes"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Blinded\" here means she was so focused on the hard work that she did not notice the rising tide. She was paying attention only to the fossil, not the danger.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Another time, Mary found a large fossil. She and a helper labored to recover it. The hard work blinded Mary to the rising tide that flooded the beach.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l05-q016","read_aloud":"What does the word assembled mean in this sentence? A. Took apart B. Put or brought together C. Sold to others D. Drew pictures of","excerpt":"\"One visitor wished to record the name of the woman who had assembled such a wonderful collection.\"","stem":"What does the word assembled mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Took apart","B":"Put or brought together","C":"Sold to others","D":"Drew pictures of"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Assembled means she put or brought together a large group of fossils for her collection.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"One visitor wished to record the name of the woman who had assembled such a wonderful collection.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l05-q017","read_aloud":"What kind of animal was the pterodactyl? A. A reptile that swam in the sea B. A bird that sang songs C. A flying reptile D. A mammal with fur","excerpt":"\"In 1828, Mary discovered a very rare fossil of a pterodactyl, a flying reptile that had the body of a lizard and the snout of a crocodile.\"","stem":"What kind of animal was the pterodactyl?","choices":{"A":"A reptile that swam in the sea","B":"A bird that sang songs","C":"A flying reptile","D":"A mammal with fur"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text describes the pterodactyl as a \"flying reptile.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1828, Mary discovered a very rare fossil of a pterodactyl, a flying reptile that had the body of a lizard and the snout of a crocodile.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l05-q018","read_aloud":"Where can people see Mary\u0027s pterodactyl today? A. In her shop on Broad Street B. At the British Natural History Museum C. In Lyme Regis D. In a private home","excerpt":"\"Mary\u0027s pterodactyl was displayed at the British Natural History Museum and is still there today.\"","stem":"Where can people see Mary\u0027s pterodactyl today?","choices":{"A":"In her shop on Broad Street","B":"At the British Natural History Museum","C":"In Lyme Regis","D":"In a private home"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states the fossil is displayed at the British Natural History Museum.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary\u0027s pterodactyl was displayed at the British Natural History Museum and is still there today.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l05-q019","read_aloud":"How did Mary act like a scientist? A. She sold things to tourists. B. She studied and tried to understand her finds. C. She walked ten miles every day. D. She wrote books for children.","excerpt":"\"Mary tried to make sense of her discoveries. She read her science books and studied her collection.\"","stem":"How did Mary act like a scientist?","choices":{"A":"She sold things to tourists.","B":"She studied and tried to understand her finds.","C":"She walked ten miles every day.","D":"She wrote books for children."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Scientists try to understand the world. Mary studied her collection and read books to make sense of her discoveries.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary tried to make sense of her discoveries. She read her science books and studied her collection.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l05-q020","read_aloud":"How does the author compare Mary\u0027s money and her spirit? A. She had a lot of money and spirit. B. She had no money and no spirit. C. She had little money but was rich in spirit. D. She lost her money but found her spirit.","excerpt":"\"She had little money, but she was rich in spirit. She was unschooled, but the professors heeded her words.\"","stem":"How does the author compare Mary\u0027s money and her spirit?","choices":{"A":"She had a lot of money and spirit.","B":"She had no money and no spirit.","C":"She had little money but was rich in spirit.","D":"She lost her money but found her spirit."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The author contrasts having \"little money\" with being \"rich in spirit,\" showing she had good character despite being poor.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"She had little money, but she was rich in spirit. She was unschooled, but the professors heeded her words.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l05-q021","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. Having a lot of money and toys B. Having very little money or possessions C. Being very happy all the time D. Being sick and unable to work","excerpt":"\"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"Having a lot of money and toys","B":"Having very little money or possessions","C":"Being very happy all the time","D":"Being sick and unable to work"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Poor\" means not having much money. The text says Mary\u0027s life was hard, which shows she did not have many things.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l05-q022","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. Having a lot of money and toys B. Having very little money or possessions C. Being very happy all the time D. Being sick and unable to work","excerpt":"\"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"Having a lot of money and toys","B":"Having very little money or possessions","C":"Being very happy all the time","D":"Being sick and unable to work"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Poor\" means not having much money. The text says Mary\u0027s life was hard, which shows she did not have many things.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l05-q023","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? A. Having a lot of money and toys B. Having very little money or possessions C. Being very happy all the time D. Being sick and unable to work","excerpt":"\"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ?","choices":{"A":"Having a lot of money and toys","B":"Having very little money or possessions","C":"Being very happy all the time","D":"Being sick and unable to work"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Poor\" means not having much money. The text says Mary\u0027s life was hard, which shows she did not have many things.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l05-q024","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. The dog was afraid of Mary B. The dog was a loyal companion and helper C. The dog did not like going on fossil hunts D. The dog was trained by Mary\u0027s father","excerpt":"\"Mary\u0027s dog trotted faithfully beside her. People said the dog guarded her discoveries while she fetched her tools or got help.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"The dog was afraid of Mary","B":"The dog was a loyal companion and helper","C":"The dog did not like going on fossil hunts","D":"The dog was trained by Mary\u0027s father"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The dog trotted faithfully beside Mary and guarded her discoveries, which shows the dog was loyal and helpful.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary\u0027s dog trotted faithfully beside her. People said the dog guarded her discoveries while she fetched her tools or got help.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l05-q025","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. Seven feet long B. Nine feet long C. Twelve feet long D. Three feet long","excerpt":"\"In 1823, Mary discovered the first complete fossil of a plesiosaur, another reptile that had lived in the sea. It was an astonishing nine-foot-long creature with a long, serpentlike neck, a lizard\u0027s head, a crocodile\u0027s teeth, a chameleon\u0027s ribs, and the paddles of a whale.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"Seven feet long","B":"Nine feet long","C":"Twelve feet long","D":"Three feet long"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says \"It was an astonishing nine-foot-long creature.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1823, Mary discovered the first complete fossil of a plesiosaur, another reptile that had lived in the sea. It was an astonishing nine-foot-long creature with a long, serpentlike neck, a lizard\u0027s head, a crocodile\u0027s teeth, a chameleon\u0027s ribs, and the paddles of a whale.\""}]},{"level":6,"level_name":"Level 6","difficulty_band":"strategic","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l06-q001","read_aloud":"What does the word \"untold\" mean in this sentence? A. A number that is very small B. A number that is too many to count C. A number that is a secret D. A number that Mary forgot","excerpt":"\"By 1836, Mary had found the fossils of three ichthyosaurs, two plesiosaurs, a pterodactyl, a strange sharklike fish called Squaloraja, and an untold number of small or incomplete fossils.\"","stem":"What does the word \"untold\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"A number that is very small","B":"A number that is too many to count","C":"A number that is a secret","D":"A number that Mary forgot"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Untold number\" means so many that you cannot count them all. Mary found many small or incomplete fossils.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"By 1836, Mary had found the fossils of three ichthyosaurs, two plesiosaurs, a pterodactyl, a strange sharklike fish called Squaloraja, and an untold number of small or incomplete fossils.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l06-q002","read_aloud":"What does Mary\u0027s statement that she is \"well known throughout the whole of Europe\" show about her? A. She was shy and quiet B. She was proud of her reputation and fame C. She wanted to move to another country D. She did not like visitors to her shop","excerpt":"\"Mary\u0027s fossil shop on Broad Street was now crowded with customers. One visitor wished to record the name of the woman who had assembled such a wonderful collection. With a firm hand, Mary wrote her name in the man\u0027s notebook. \u0027I am well known throughout the whole of Europe,\u0027 she said proudly.\"","stem":"What does Mary\u0027s statement that she is \"well known throughout the whole of Europe\" show about her?","choices":{"A":"She was shy and quiet","B":"She was proud of her reputation and fame","C":"She wanted to move to another country","D":"She did not like visitors to her shop"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Mary said this \"proudly,\" which shows she was proud that people across Europe knew about her work.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary\u0027s fossil shop on Broad Street was now crowded with customers. One visitor wished to record the name of the woman who had assembled such a wonderful collection. With a firm hand, Mary wrote her name in the man\u0027s notebook. \u0027I am well known throughout the whole of Europe,\u0027 she said proudly.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l06-q003","read_aloud":"What does the author mean when he says Mary\u0027s \"spirit dwelled in a time millions of years ago\"? A. She wished she lived in the future B. She was always thinking about and studying prehistoric times C. She did not like living in her own time period D. She could travel back in time","excerpt":"\"Mary Anning lived from 1799 to 1847, but her spirit dwelled in a time millions of years ago, when the monsters and dragons we now call dinosaurs roamed.\"","stem":"What does the author mean when he says Mary\u0027s \"spirit dwelled in a time millions of years ago\"?","choices":{"A":"She wished she lived in the future","B":"She was always thinking about and studying prehistoric times","C":"She did not like living in her own time period","D":"She could travel back in time"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Mary spent her life studying fossils from millions of years ago, so her mind and spirit were focused on that ancient time.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary Anning lived from 1799 to 1847, but her spirit dwelled in a time millions of years ago, when the monsters and dragons we now call dinosaurs roamed.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l06-q004","read_aloud":"What does the author mean by \"it was knowledge that she unearthed\"? A. Mary found gold and jewels in the ground B. Mary\u0027s work helped people learn new things about the past C. Mary buried knowledge in the ground on purpose D. Mary only found fossils that were already known","excerpt":"\"Mary Anning pried fossils from the ground, but it was knowledge that she unearthed.\"","stem":"What does the author mean by \"it was knowledge that she unearthed\"?","choices":{"A":"Mary found gold and jewels in the ground","B":"Mary\u0027s work helped people learn new things about the past","C":"Mary buried knowledge in the ground on purpose","D":"Mary only found fossils that were already known"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author means that Mary did more than just find fossils. She helped scientists gain new knowledge about ancient life.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary Anning pried fossils from the ground, but it was knowledge that she unearthed.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l06-q005","read_aloud":"Which sentence best shows the meaning of \"poverty\"? A. The family had plenty of food and money. B. The family had very little money and struggled to survive. C. The family moved to a bigger house. D. The family bought many new things.","excerpt":"The family struggled to survive on the earnings of Richard\u0027s carpentry work, and the extra money they earned by selling fossils helped. Then Mary\u0027s father died and the family was thrown into bitter poverty.","stem":"Which sentence best shows the meaning of \"poverty\"?","choices":{"A":"The family had plenty of food and money.","B":"The family had very little money and struggled to survive.","C":"The family moved to a bigger house.","D":"The family bought many new things."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Poverty means being extremely poor. The text says the family struggled after Mary\u0027s father died. The other sentences describe the opposite.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The family struggled to survive on the earnings of Richard\u0027s carpentry work, and the extra money they earned by selling fossils helped. Then Mary\u0027s father died and the family was thrown into bitter poverty."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l06-q006","read_aloud":"What does this detail tell us about Mary\u0027s reputation? A. People avoided her because she was poor. B. Famous scientists wanted to learn from her and work with her. C. She only worked alone and never shared. D. She did not like meeting new people.","excerpt":"William Buckland, a famous geologist, brought his family to Lyme Regis to meet Mary and to search for fossils. She escorted Buckland and his children on fossil hunts.","stem":"What does this detail tell us about Mary\u0027s reputation?","choices":{"A":"People avoided her because she was poor.","B":"Famous scientists wanted to learn from her and work with her.","C":"She only worked alone and never shared.","D":"She did not like meeting new people."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A famous geologist traveled to meet Mary and asked her to guide fossil hunts, showing she was respected. The other choices do not match.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: William Buckland, a famous geologist, brought his family to Lyme Regis to meet Mary and to search for fossils. She escorted Buckland and his children on fossil hunts."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l06-q007","read_aloud":"What role did Mary\u0027s dog play during fossil hunts? A. The dog dug for fossils. B. The dog guarded her finds while she got tools or help. C. The dog carried heavy rocks. D. The dog warned her about tourists.","excerpt":"People said the dog guarded her discoveries while she fetched her tools or got help.","stem":"What role did Mary\u0027s dog play during fossil hunts?","choices":{"A":"The dog dug for fossils.","B":"The dog guarded her finds while she got tools or help.","C":"The dog carried heavy rocks.","D":"The dog warned her about tourists."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the dog guarded her discoveries while she was away. The other roles are not mentioned.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: People said the dog guarded her discoveries while she fetched her tools or got help."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l06-q008","read_aloud":"Why were questions important to Mary\u0027s scientific work? A. Questions made the work slower and harder. B. Questions helped scientists learn about ancient life and the past. C. Questions were only for children. D. Questions made fossils harder to find.","excerpt":"Answering these questions helped reveal the ancient world in which the plesiosaur had lived.","stem":"Why were questions important to Mary\u0027s scientific work?","choices":{"A":"Questions made the work slower and harder.","B":"Questions helped scientists learn about ancient life and the past.","C":"Questions were only for children.","D":"Questions made fossils harder to find."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text shows that asking and answering questions helped reveal the ancient world. This was key to scientific discovery.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Answering these questions helped reveal the ancient world in which the plesiosaur had lived."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l06-q009","read_aloud":"What does this sentence suggest about Mary\u0027s passion? A. She only cared about the present day. B. She felt deeply connected to ancient life and loved studying it. C. She wanted to become a dragon. D. She did not like her own time period.","excerpt":"Mary Anning lived from 1799 to 1847, but her spirit dwelled in a time millions of years ago, when the monsters and dragons we now call dinosaurs roamed.","stem":"What does this sentence suggest about Mary\u0027s passion?","choices":{"A":"She only cared about the present day.","B":"She felt deeply connected to ancient life and loved studying it.","C":"She wanted to become a dragon.","D":"She did not like her own time period."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Saying her spirit \"dwelled\" in ancient times shows Mary\u0027s deep love for studying fossils and the past. The other choices misread the figurative language.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Mary Anning lived from 1799 to 1847, but her spirit dwelled in a time millions of years ago, when the monsters and dragons we now call dinosaurs roamed."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l06-q010","read_aloud":"What does remarkable mean in this sentence? A. Ordinary and plain B. Extraordinary or outstanding C. Rude and mean D. Young and small","excerpt":"\"They prized the thoughts of the remarkable young woman who had left school when she was eleven.\"","stem":"What does remarkable mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Ordinary and plain","B":"Extraordinary or outstanding","C":"Rude and mean","D":"Young and small"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says scientists \"prized her thoughts\" even though she left school at eleven. This shows she was extraordinary or outstanding-very special and impressive.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They prized the thoughts of the remarkable young woman who had left school when she was eleven.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l06-q011","read_aloud":"What do William Buckland and Richard Owens have in common? A. They were both famous scientists who worked with Mary B. They both found the first plesiosaur C. They both lived in Mary\u0027s house D. They both stopped Mary from working","excerpt":"\"William Buckland, a famous geologist, brought his family to Lyme Regis to meet Mary and to search for fossils... Richard Owens, the scientist who invented the word dinosaur, also combed the beach with Mary.\"","stem":"What do William Buckland and Richard Owens have in common?","choices":{"A":"They were both famous scientists who worked with Mary","B":"They both found the first plesiosaur","C":"They both lived in Mary\u0027s house","D":"They both stopped Mary from working"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says Buckland was \"a famous geologist\" and Owen was \"the scientist who invented the word dinosaur.\" Both were famous scientists who came to work with Mary.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"William Buckland, a famous geologist, brought his family to Lyme Regis to meet Mary and to search for fossils... Richard Owens, the scientist who invented the word dinosaur, also combed the beach with Mary.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l06-q012","read_aloud":"Why would people say this about Mary? A. Because Mary had a college degree B. Because Mary had spent years studying fossils and learning on her own C. Because Mary was very tall D. Because Mary was wealthy","excerpt":"\"It was said, \u0027She knows more about the science than anyone else.\u0027\"","stem":"Why would people say this about Mary?","choices":{"A":"Because Mary had a college degree","B":"Because Mary had spent years studying fossils and learning on her own","C":"Because Mary was very tall","D":"Because Mary was wealthy"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text tells us Mary \"taught herself about animals, fish, and fossils,\" read science books, and made many important discoveries. She learned by doing, not by going to school.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It was said, \u0027She knows more about the science than anyone else.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l06-q013","read_aloud":"Why was Mary\u0027s dog important to her work? A. The dog found the fossils B. The dog protected her discoveries when she was not there C. The dog scared away scientists D. The dog wrote about her work","excerpt":"\"Mary\u0027s dog trotted faithfully beside her. People said the dog guarded her discoveries while she fetched her tools or got help.\"","stem":"Why was Mary\u0027s dog important to her work?","choices":{"A":"The dog found the fossils","B":"The dog protected her discoveries when she was not there","C":"The dog scared away scientists","D":"The dog wrote about her work"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the dog \"guarded her discoveries while she fetched her tools or got help.\" This means the dog stayed with the fossils to protect them.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary\u0027s dog trotted faithfully beside her. People said the dog guarded her discoveries while she fetched her tools or got help.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l06-q014","read_aloud":"How did Mary and the scientists help each other? A. Mary shared her fossil ideas, and scientists valued her knowledge B. Mary gave scientists money C. Scientists told Mary to stop working D. Mary and scientists did not talk","excerpt":"\"Mary tried to make sense of her discoveries. She read her science books and studied her collection. Mary shared her ideas with the finest scientists.\"","stem":"How did Mary and the scientists help each other?","choices":{"A":"Mary shared her fossil ideas, and scientists valued her knowledge","B":"Mary gave scientists money","C":"Scientists told Mary to stop working","D":"Mary and scientists did not talk"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Mary \"shared her ideas with the finest scientists,\" and \"They prized the thoughts of the remarkable young woman.\" Both sides helped each other-Mary gave ideas, scientists listened and learned.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary tried to make sense of her discoveries. She read her science books and studied her collection. Mary shared her ideas with the finest scientists.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l06-q015","read_aloud":"Which word is an antonym (opposite) for poverty, the state of being poor? A. Wealth B. Hunger C. Sadness D. Difficulty","excerpt":"\"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\"","stem":"Which word is an antonym (opposite) for poverty, the state of being poor?","choices":{"A":"Wealth","B":"Hunger","C":"Sadness","D":"Difficulty"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Poverty means being poor, so the opposite would be having a lot of money, or wealth.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l06-q016","read_aloud":"What caused this dangerous event? A. A storm at sea B. A cliff collapsing C. A fire on the beach D. An earthquake in the town","excerpt":"\"During one hunt, part of a cliff collapsed. Heavy rocks crashed at Mary\u0027s feet and nearly crushed her.\"","stem":"What caused this dangerous event?","choices":{"A":"A storm at sea","B":"A cliff collapsing","C":"A fire on the beach","D":"An earthquake in the town"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the danger happened because \"part of a cliff collapsed.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"During one hunt, part of a cliff collapsed. Heavy rocks crashed at Mary\u0027s feet and nearly crushed her.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l06-q017","read_aloud":"Why did the man fail to warn Mary about the tide? A. He did not see the water rising. B. He was too far away to speak. C. He was ashamed to admit he was scared. D. He thought Mary could swim well.","excerpt":"\"Later, Mary asked the man why he hadn\u0027t warned her of the rapidly flowing tide. \u0027I was ashamed to say I was frightened when you didn\u0027t regard it,\u0027 he replied.\"","stem":"Why did the man fail to warn Mary about the tide?","choices":{"A":"He did not see the water rising.","B":"He was too far away to speak.","C":"He was ashamed to admit he was scared.","D":"He thought Mary could swim well."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The man admitted he was frightened, but he was ashamed to say so because Mary seemed brave.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Later, Mary asked the man why he hadn\u0027t warned her of the rapidly flowing tide. \u0027I was ashamed to say I was frightened when you didn\u0027t regard it,\u0027 he replied.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l06-q018","read_aloud":"Why was Mary\u0027s discovery called a \"rare treasure\"? A. It was made of gold and diamonds. B. It was worth a lot of money. C. It was a perfect fossil that was hard to find. D. It was the first fossil she ever found.","excerpt":"\"Only a few ichthyosaur fossils had ever been found and none were as nearly perfect as this one.\"","stem":"Why was Mary\u0027s discovery called a \"rare treasure\"?","choices":{"A":"It was made of gold and diamonds.","B":"It was worth a lot of money.","C":"It was a perfect fossil that was hard to find.","D":"It was the first fossil she ever found."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"A \"rare treasure\" means something valuable and hard to find. Her fossil was nearly perfect and very rare.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Only a few ichthyosaur fossils had ever been found and none were as nearly perfect as this one.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l06-q019","read_aloud":"What does this contrast show about Mary? A. She did not need to go to school to be smart. B. She traveled all over the world to learn. C. She did not like professors very much. D. She wanted to be a teacher.","excerpt":"\"She was unschooled, but the professors heeded her words. She rarely strayed from her home, but her name became known everywhere.\"","stem":"What does this contrast show about Mary?","choices":{"A":"She did not need to go to school to be smart.","B":"She traveled all over the world to learn.","C":"She did not like professors very much.","D":"She wanted to be a teacher."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Even though she was \"unschooled\" (did not go to school much), professors listened to her because she was knowledgeable.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"She was unschooled, but the professors heeded her words. She rarely strayed from her home, but her name became known everywhere.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l06-q020","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. Having a lot of money and toys B. Having very little money or possessions C. Being very happy all the time D. Being sick and unable to work","excerpt":"\"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"Having a lot of money and toys","B":"Having very little money or possessions","C":"Being very happy all the time","D":"Being sick and unable to work"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Poor\" means not having much money. The text says Mary\u0027s life was hard, which shows she did not have many things.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l06-q021","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. Having a lot of money and toys B. Having very little money or possessions C. Being very happy all the time D. Being sick and unable to work","excerpt":"\"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"Having a lot of money and toys","B":"Having very little money or possessions","C":"Being very happy all the time","D":"Being sick and unable to work"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Poor\" means not having much money. The text says Mary\u0027s life was hard, which shows she did not have many things.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l06-q022","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? A. Having a lot of money and toys B. Having very little money or possessions C. Being very happy all the time D. Being sick and unable to work","excerpt":"\"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ?","choices":{"A":"Having a lot of money and toys","B":"Having very little money or possessions","C":"Being very happy all the time","D":"Being sick and unable to work"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Poor\" means not having much money. The text says Mary\u0027s life was hard, which shows she did not have many things.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l06-q023","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. The dog was afraid of Mary B. The dog was a loyal companion and helper C. The dog did not like going on fossil hunts D. The dog was trained by Mary\u0027s father","excerpt":"\"Mary\u0027s dog trotted faithfully beside her. People said the dog guarded her discoveries while she fetched her tools or got help.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"The dog was afraid of Mary","B":"The dog was a loyal companion and helper","C":"The dog did not like going on fossil hunts","D":"The dog was trained by Mary\u0027s father"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The dog trotted faithfully beside Mary and guarded her discoveries, which shows the dog was loyal and helpful.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary\u0027s dog trotted faithfully beside her. People said the dog guarded her discoveries while she fetched her tools or got help.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l06-q024","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. Seven feet long B. Nine feet long C. Twelve feet long D. Three feet long","excerpt":"\"In 1823, Mary discovered the first complete fossil of a plesiosaur, another reptile that had lived in the sea. It was an astonishing nine-foot-long creature with a long, serpentlike neck, a lizard\u0027s head, a crocodile\u0027s teeth, a chameleon\u0027s ribs, and the paddles of a whale.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"Seven feet long","B":"Nine feet long","C":"Twelve feet long","D":"Three feet long"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says \"It was an astonishing nine-foot-long creature.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1823, Mary discovered the first complete fossil of a plesiosaur, another reptile that had lived in the sea. It was an astonishing nine-foot-long creature with a long, serpentlike neck, a lizard\u0027s head, a crocodile\u0027s teeth, a chameleon\u0027s ribs, and the paddles of a whale.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l06-q025","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. To show that Mary was not a good fossil hunter B. To show that Mary did not receive the credit she deserved at first C. To show that Joseph found more fossils than Mary D. To show that fossils were not important discoveries","excerpt":"\"Almost everyone forgot that it had been found by twelve-year-old Mary Anning and her teenage brother.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"To show that Mary was not a good fossil hunter","B":"To show that Mary did not receive the credit she deserved at first","C":"To show that Joseph found more fossils than Mary","D":"To show that fossils were not important discoveries"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author includes this detail to show that even though Mary made an important discovery, people did not give her credit because she was young.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Almost everyone forgot that it had been found by twelve-year-old Mary Anning and her teenage brother.\""}]},{"level":7,"level_name":"Level 7","difficulty_band":"advanced","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l07-q001","read_aloud":"What does the word \"extraordinary\" mean in this sentence? A. Ordinary and not special B. Remarkable and outstanding C. New and untrained D. Quiet and shy","excerpt":"\"Mary Anning\u0027s fame grew as people learned that she was an extraordinary fossil collector and a talented scientist.\"","stem":"What does the word \"extraordinary\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Ordinary and not special","B":"Remarkable and outstanding","C":"New and untrained","D":"Quiet and shy"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Extraordinary\" means remarkable or outstanding. Mary was not ordinary; she was a very talented fossil collector.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary Anning\u0027s fame grew as people learned that she was an extraordinary fossil collector and a talented scientist.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l07-q002","read_aloud":"According to the passage, what are two ways fossils can be revealed from the ground? A. By being eaten by animals or washed away by rain B. By a shovel or pick, or when wind or water wears away the earth C. By fire or by freezing temperatures D. By scientists looking for them or by tourists stepping on them","excerpt":"\"Usually the remains of plants and animals decompose or are eaten, but sometimes they are covered by dirt or sink in mud. Of these, a rare few lie undisturbed for millions of years. While they are buried, the soft parts, such as flesh, decay, leaving bones, shell, or flat impressions in the earth. Minerals seep into these remains and become stone. These fossils survive hidden in the ground until they are revealed by a shovel or pick, are driven to the surface by an earthquake or volcano, or are uncovered when wind or water wears away the earth.\"","stem":"According to the passage, what are two ways fossils can be revealed from the ground?","choices":{"A":"By being eaten by animals or washed away by rain","B":"By a shovel or pick, or when wind or water wears away the earth","C":"By fire or by freezing temperatures","D":"By scientists looking for them or by tourists stepping on them"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text lists being revealed \"by a shovel or pick\" or \"when wind or water wears away the earth\" as two ways.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Usually the remains of plants and animals decompose or are eaten, but sometimes they are covered by dirt or sink in mud. Of these, a rare few lie undisturbed for millions of years. While they are buried, the soft parts, such as flesh, decay, leaving bones, shell, or flat impressions in the earth. Minerals seep into these remains and become stone. These fossils survive hidden in the ground until they are revealed by a shovel or pick, are driven to the surface by an earthquake or volcano, or are uncovered when wind or water wears away the earth.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l07-q003","read_aloud":"Why was selling fossils important to the Anning family? A. The fossils were too big to keep in the house B. The extra money helped the family survive C. They wanted to become famous for their fossils D. The tourists demanded to see the fossils","excerpt":"\"The Annings displayed the puzzling yet delightful fossils that they found on a table near Richard\u0027s shop on Bridge Street. Wealthy tourists visiting the popular Lyme Regis shore bought them. The family struggled to survive on the earnings of Richard\u0027s carpentry work, and the extra money they earned by selling fossils helped.\"","stem":"Why was selling fossils important to the Anning family?","choices":{"A":"The fossils were too big to keep in the house","B":"The extra money helped the family survive","C":"They wanted to become famous for their fossils","D":"The tourists demanded to see the fossils"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says \"the extra money they earned by selling fossils helped\" because the family struggled to survive on the father\u0027s carpentry earnings.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Annings displayed the puzzling yet delightful fossils that they found on a table near Richard\u0027s shop on Bridge Street. Wealthy tourists visiting the popular Lyme Regis shore bought them. The family struggled to survive on the earnings of Richard\u0027s carpentry work, and the extra money they earned by selling fossils helped.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l07-q004","read_aloud":"Do you think Richard Anning made a good choice teaching his young children to hunt for fossils? Why or why not? A. Yes, because it gave them a skill that helped them earn money and led to important discoveries B. No, because fossil hunting was too dangerous for young children C. Yes, because they had nothing else to do for fun D. No, because fossils are not interesting to children","excerpt":"\"Mary and her older brother, Joseph, were just a few years old when they began visiting the nearby rocky beaches with their father. Richard Anning taught them how to hunt for fossils.\"","stem":"Do you think Richard Anning made a good choice teaching his young children to hunt for fossils? Why or why not?","choices":{"A":"Yes, because it gave them a skill that helped them earn money and led to important discoveries","B":"No, because fossil hunting was too dangerous for young children","C":"Yes, because they had nothing else to do for fun","D":"No, because fossils are not interesting to children"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Teaching them was a good choice because fossil hunting became Mary\u0027s life\u0027s work and led to important scientific discoveries.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary and her older brother, Joseph, were just a few years old when they began visiting the nearby rocky beaches with their father. Richard Anning taught them how to hunt for fossils.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l07-q005","read_aloud":"Imagine you are a customer visiting Mary\u0027s shop. What question would you want to ask her about how she cleans her fossils? A. How much money do you make from selling fossils? B. Why do you spend so many days cleaning just one fossil? C. Where did you learn to read and write? D. What is your favorite food to eat for dinner?","excerpt":"\"Mary sold her treasures from a small, cluttered shop on Broad Street. There she freed her latest discoveries from dirt, sand, and rock. Mary worked very carefully, sometimes for days, to avoid damaging the fossils.\"","stem":"Imagine you are a customer visiting Mary\u0027s shop. What question would you want to ask her about how she cleans her fossils?","choices":{"A":"How much money do you make from selling fossils?","B":"Why do you spend so many days cleaning just one fossil?","C":"Where did you learn to read and write?","D":"What is your favorite food to eat for dinner?"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Since the text says Mary worked very carefully for days to avoid damaging fossils, a visitor would likely be curious about why she takes so long.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary sold her treasures from a small, cluttered shop on Broad Street. There she freed her latest discoveries from dirt, sand, and rock. Mary worked very carefully, sometimes for days, to avoid damaging the fossils.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l07-q006","read_aloud":"How does the word \"pursued\" connect to Mary\u0027s actions? A. She gave up when things got hard. B. She kept working at fossil collecting even when it was dangerous. C. She only worked when the weather was nice. D. She asked others to do the hard work.","excerpt":"She made it her life\u0027s work. It also must have been Mary\u0027s great delight because she pursued it despite the dangers on the rocky shore.","stem":"How does the word \"pursued\" connect to Mary\u0027s actions?","choices":{"A":"She gave up when things got hard.","B":"She kept working at fossil collecting even when it was dangerous.","C":"She only worked when the weather was nice.","D":"She asked others to do the hard work."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Pursued means Mary kept working hard at her passion despite risks. The text mentions dangers she faced but did not avoid.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: She made it her life\u0027s work. It also must have been Mary\u0027s great delight because she pursued it despite the dangers on the rocky shore."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l07-q007","read_aloud":"What are three ways fossils can be uncovered, according to the text? A. By people digging, earthquakes/volcanoes, or wind/water wearing away earth B. By animals digging, rain falling, or the sun shining C. By tourists taking them, scientists buying them, or museums displaying them D. By magic, dreams, or wishes","excerpt":"Minerals seep into these remains and become stone. These fossils survive hidden in the ground until they are revealed by a shovel or pick, are driven to the surface by an earthquake or volcano, or are uncovered when wind or water wears away the earth.","stem":"What are three ways fossils can be uncovered, according to the text?","choices":{"A":"By people digging, earthquakes/volcanoes, or wind/water wearing away earth","B":"By animals digging, rain falling, or the sun shining","C":"By tourists taking them, scientists buying them, or museums displaying them","D":"By magic, dreams, or wishes"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text lists three ways: human tools, earthquakes/volcanoes, or erosion by wind/water. The other choices are not in the text.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Minerals seep into these remains and become stone. These fossils survive hidden in the ground until they are revealed by a shovel or pick, are driven to the surface by an earthquake or volcano, or are uncovered when wind or water wears away the earth."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l07-q008","read_aloud":"she said proudly.What does Mary\u0027s statement tell us about her achievements? A. She was only known in her small town. B. Her work was recognized across many countries. C. She traveled to every country in Europe. D. She did not care if people knew her name.","excerpt":"I am well known throughout the whole of Europe,","stem":"she said proudly.What does Mary\u0027s statement tell us about her achievements?","choices":{"A":"She was only known in her small town.","B":"Her work was recognized across many countries.","C":"She traveled to every country in Europe.","D":"She did not care if people knew her name."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Saying she was known \"throughout the whole of Europe\" shows her fame spread far beyond her home. The other choices do not match her pride.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: I am well known throughout the whole of Europe,"},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l07-q009","read_aloud":"If you were preparing a fragile fossil for display, what might you do based on Mary\u0027s methods? A. Rush to finish so you could sell it. B. Work slowly and use supports to protect it. C. Leave it in the dirt to keep it safe. D. Paint it to make it look colorful.","excerpt":"Mary worked very carefully, sometimes for days, to avoid damaging the fossils. Sometimes she cemented a fossil to a frame to help support it.","stem":"If you were preparing a fragile fossil for display, what might you do based on Mary\u0027s methods?","choices":{"A":"Rush to finish so you could sell it.","B":"Work slowly and use supports to protect it.","C":"Leave it in the dirt to keep it safe.","D":"Paint it to make it look colorful."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Mary\u0027s careful work and use of frames show that protecting fragile items takes time and support. This is a practical application of her methods.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Mary worked very carefully, sometimes for days, to avoid damaging the fossils. Sometimes she cemented a fossil to a frame to help support it."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l07-q010","read_aloud":"What pattern does the author use in these sentences, and why? A. The author lists facts in order of importance. B. The author uses contrast (but) to show how Mary\u0027s outer life differed from her inner impact. C. The author repeats the same idea three times. D. The author compares Mary to other scientists.","excerpt":"She had little money, but she was rich in spirit. She was unschooled, but the professors heeded her words. She rarely strayed from her home, but her name became known everywhere.","stem":"What pattern does the author use in these sentences, and why?","choices":{"A":"The author lists facts in order of importance.","B":"The author uses contrast (but) to show how Mary\u0027s outer life differed from her inner impact.","C":"The author repeats the same idea three times.","D":"The author compares Mary to other scientists."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Each sentence uses \"but\" to contrast Mary\u0027s humble circumstances with her great influence. This pattern highlights her remarkable life.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: She had little money, but she was rich in spirit. She was unschooled, but the professors heeded her words. She rarely strayed from her home, but her name became known everywhere."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l07-q011","read_aloud":"What does assembled mean in this sentence? A. Broken into pieces B. Put or brought together C. Lost forever D. Hidden under ground","excerpt":"\"One visitor wished to record the name of the woman who had assembled such a wonderful collection.\"","stem":"What does assembled mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Broken into pieces","B":"Put or brought together","C":"Lost forever","D":"Hidden under ground"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Mary found fossils over many years and put them together in her shop. Assembled means she brought all the fossils together to make a collection.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"One visitor wished to record the name of the woman who had assembled such a wonderful collection.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l07-q012","read_aloud":"Why does the author compare Mary\u0027s life to stone and her spirit to a gem? A. To show that Mary liked jewelry B. To help readers understand that her life was difficult but her spirit was beautiful and strong C. To show that stones are better than gems D. To make the story longer","excerpt":"\"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\"","stem":"Why does the author compare Mary\u0027s life to stone and her spirit to a gem?","choices":{"A":"To show that Mary liked jewelry","B":"To help readers understand that her life was difficult but her spirit was beautiful and strong","C":"To show that stones are better than gems","D":"To make the story longer"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Stone is hard, like Mary\u0027s difficult life. A gem shines brightly, like Mary\u0027s strong, beautiful spirit. The author uses these comparisons to help us feel how hard her life was and how special she was.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l07-q013","read_aloud":"How does the author structure these sentences? A. Each sentence tells about a different person B. Each sentence uses \"but\" to show a contrast or surprise C. Each sentence describes the weather D. Each sentence is a question","excerpt":"\"She had little money, but she was rich in spirit. She was unschooled, but the professors heeded her words. She rarely strayed from her home, but her name became known everywhere.\"","stem":"How does the author structure these sentences?","choices":{"A":"Each sentence tells about a different person","B":"Each sentence uses \"but\" to show a contrast or surprise","C":"Each sentence describes the weather","D":"Each sentence is a question"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Each sentence has two parts connected by \"but.\" The first part seems negative (little money, unschooled, rarely straye d), but the second part shows something positive. This contrast surprises the reader and shows how special Mary was.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"She had little money, but she was rich in spirit. She was unschooled, but the professors heeded her words. She rarely strayed from her home, but her name became known everywhere.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l07-q014","read_aloud":"Why does the author include Anna Maria Pinney\u0027s quote? A. To show that Mary was very strong B. To show that Mary was kind and brave when helping others C. To show that Anna was heavy D. To show that babies are small","excerpt":"\"Mary carried her with the \u0027same ease as you would a baby.\u0027\"","stem":"Why does the author include Anna Maria Pinney\u0027s quote?","choices":{"A":"To show that Mary was very strong","B":"To show that Mary was kind and brave when helping others","C":"To show that Anna was heavy","D":"To show that babies are small"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Mary rescued Anna from \"rough water\" and carried her easily. The quote shows Mary was not only strong but also brave and kind enough to save someone in danger.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary carried her with the \u0027same ease as you would a baby.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l07-q015","read_aloud":"Which word means almost the same as treacherous in this context? A. Dangerous B. Beautiful C. Quiet D. Safe","excerpt":"\"Boulders fell from the cliffs, torrents of thick black mud slid down from the heights, high seas pummeled the shore, and waves could sweep a careless visitor away.\"","stem":"Which word means almost the same as treacherous in this context?","choices":{"A":"Dangerous","B":"Beautiful","C":"Quiet","D":"Safe"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The description of falling boulders and sliding mud shows that treacherous means dangerous.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Boulders fell from the cliffs, torrents of thick black mud slid down from the heights, high seas pummeled the shore, and waves could sweep a careless visitor away.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l07-q016","read_aloud":"What was the main reason Mary became famous? A. She opened a shop on Broad Street. B. She rescued a girl from the water. C. She was an extraordinary fossil collector and scientist. D. She wrote many books about fossils.","excerpt":"\"Mary Anning\u0027s fame grew as people learned that she was an extraordinary fossil collector and a talented scientist.\"","stem":"What was the main reason Mary became famous?","choices":{"A":"She opened a shop on Broad Street.","B":"She rescued a girl from the water.","C":"She was an extraordinary fossil collector and scientist.","D":"She wrote many books about fossils."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says her fame grew because people learned she was an extraordinary collector and scientist.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary Anning\u0027s fame grew as people learned that she was an extraordinary fossil collector and a talented scientist.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l07-q017","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this sentence? A. Mary was very strong physically. B. Mary found fossils, but she also discovered new knowledge. C. Mary liked to dig in the ground alone. D. Mary sold fossils to make money.","excerpt":"\"Mary Anning pried fossils from the ground, but it was knowledge that she unearthed.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Mary was very strong physically.","B":"Mary found fossils, but she also discovered new knowledge.","C":"Mary liked to dig in the ground alone.","D":"Mary sold fossils to make money."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author is saying that Mary did more than just dig up bones; she discovered important scientific ideas (knowledge).","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary Anning pried fossils from the ground, but it was knowledge that she unearthed.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l07-q018","read_aloud":"How did the dog help Mary in her work? A. He carried the heavy rocks. B. He found the fossils with his nose. C. He guarded the fossils while she was gone. D. He pulled her out of the mud.","excerpt":"\"People said the dog guarded her discoveries while she fetched her tools or got help.\"","stem":"How did the dog help Mary in her work?","choices":{"A":"He carried the heavy rocks.","B":"He found the fossils with his nose.","C":"He guarded the fossils while she was gone.","D":"He pulled her out of the mud."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text explains that the dog guarded her discoveries while she went to get tools or help.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"People said the dog guarded her discoveries while she fetched her tools or got help.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l07-q019","read_aloud":"How did Mary\u0027s life differ from her brother Joseph\u0027s adult life? A. Joseph stopped working, but Mary worked hard. B. Mary chose fossil hunting as her life\u0027s work, while Joseph had a different job. C. Joseph became a scientist, but Mary stayed poor. D. Mary worked with Joseph every day.","excerpt":"\"Joseph became an upholsterer and Mary collected fossils alone. She made it her life\u0027s work.\"","stem":"How did Mary\u0027s life differ from her brother Joseph\u0027s adult life?","choices":{"A":"Joseph stopped working, but Mary worked hard.","B":"Mary chose fossil hunting as her life\u0027s work, while Joseph had a different job.","C":"Joseph became a scientist, but Mary stayed poor.","D":"Mary worked with Joseph every day."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Joseph became an upholsterer (a different trade), but Mary dedicated her whole life to collecting fossils.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Joseph became an upholsterer and Mary collected fossils alone. She made it her life\u0027s work.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l07-q020","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about Use text evidence.? A. Having a lot of money and toys B. Having very little money or possessions C. Being very happy all the time D. Being sick and unable to work","excerpt":"\"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"Having a lot of money and toys","B":"Having very little money or possessions","C":"Being very happy all the time","D":"Being sick and unable to work"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Poor\" means not having much money. The text says Mary\u0027s life was hard, which shows she did not have many things.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l07-q021","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. Having a lot of money and toys B. Having very little money or possessions C. Being very happy all the time D. Being sick and unable to work","excerpt":"\"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"Having a lot of money and toys","B":"Having very little money or possessions","C":"Being very happy all the time","D":"Being sick and unable to work"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Poor\" means not having much money. The text says Mary\u0027s life was hard, which shows she did not have many things.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l07-q022","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? A. Having a lot of money and toys B. Having very little money or possessions C. Being very happy all the time D. Being sick and unable to work","excerpt":"\"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ?","choices":{"A":"Having a lot of money and toys","B":"Having very little money or possessions","C":"Being very happy all the time","D":"Being sick and unable to work"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Poor\" means not having much money. The text says Mary\u0027s life was hard, which shows she did not have many things.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l07-q023","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. The dog was afraid of Mary B. The dog was a loyal companion and helper C. The dog did not like going on fossil hunts D. The dog was trained by Mary\u0027s father","excerpt":"\"Mary\u0027s dog trotted faithfully beside her. People said the dog guarded her discoveries while she fetched her tools or got help.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"The dog was afraid of Mary","B":"The dog was a loyal companion and helper","C":"The dog did not like going on fossil hunts","D":"The dog was trained by Mary\u0027s father"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The dog trotted faithfully beside Mary and guarded her discoveries, which shows the dog was loyal and helpful.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary\u0027s dog trotted faithfully beside her. People said the dog guarded her discoveries while she fetched her tools or got help.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l07-q024","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. Seven feet long B. Nine feet long C. Twelve feet long D. Three feet long","excerpt":"\"In 1823, Mary discovered the first complete fossil of a plesiosaur, another reptile that had lived in the sea. It was an astonishing nine-foot-long creature with a long, serpentlike neck, a lizard\u0027s head, a crocodile\u0027s teeth, a chameleon\u0027s ribs, and the paddles of a whale.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"Seven feet long","B":"Nine feet long","C":"Twelve feet long","D":"Three feet long"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says \"It was an astonishing nine-foot-long creature.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1823, Mary discovered the first complete fossil of a plesiosaur, another reptile that had lived in the sea. It was an astonishing nine-foot-long creature with a long, serpentlike neck, a lizard\u0027s head, a crocodile\u0027s teeth, a chameleon\u0027s ribs, and the paddles of a whale.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l07-q025","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. To show that Mary was not a good fossil hunter B. To show that Mary did not receive the credit she deserved at first C. To show that Joseph found more fossils than Mary D. To show that fossils were not important discoveries","excerpt":"\"Almost everyone forgot that it had been found by twelve-year-old Mary Anning and her teenage brother.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"To show that Mary was not a good fossil hunter","B":"To show that Mary did not receive the credit she deserved at first","C":"To show that Joseph found more fossils than Mary","D":"To show that fossils were not important discoveries"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author includes this detail to show that even though Mary made an important discovery, people did not give her credit because she was young.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Almost everyone forgot that it had been found by twelve-year-old Mary Anning and her teenage brother.\""}]},{"level":8,"level_name":"Level 8","difficulty_band":"advanced","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l08-q001","read_aloud":"What does the word \"remarkable\" mean in this sentence? A. Ordinary and not special B. Extraordinary and worth noticing C. Quiet and shy D. Angry and upset","excerpt":"\"Mary tried to make sense of her discoveries. She read her science books and studied her collection. Mary shared her ideas with the finest scientists. They prized the thoughts of the remarkable young woman who had left school when she was eleven.\"","stem":"What does the word \"remarkable\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Ordinary and not special","B":"Extraordinary and worth noticing","C":"Quiet and shy","D":"Angry and upset"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Remarkable\" means extraordinary or outstanding. The scientists valued Mary\u0027s thoughts because she was a remarkable scientist.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary tried to make sense of her discoveries. She read her science books and studied her collection. Mary shared her ideas with the finest scientists. They prized the thoughts of the remarkable young woman who had left school when she was eleven.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l08-q002","read_aloud":"What did people say Mary\u0027s dog did while she went to get tools or help? A. The dog ran home to tell Mary\u0027s mother B. The dog guarded her fossil discoveries C. The dog played in the water D. The dog dug for more fossils","excerpt":"\"Mary\u0027s dog trotted faithfully beside her. People said the dog guarded her discoveries while she fetched her tools or got help.\"","stem":"What did people say Mary\u0027s dog did while she went to get tools or help?","choices":{"A":"The dog ran home to tell Mary\u0027s mother","B":"The dog guarded her fossil discoveries","C":"The dog played in the water","D":"The dog dug for more fossils"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says \"People said the dog guarded her discoveries while she fetched her tools or got help.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary\u0027s dog trotted faithfully beside her. People said the dog guarded her discoveries while she fetched her tools or got help.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l08-q003","read_aloud":"What is the main message the author wants readers to understand about Mary Anning? A. She was unhappy because she had little money B. Even without wealth or formal education, she became respected and famous through her hard work C. She should have gone to school instead of collecting fossils D. She was lucky to find so many fossils","excerpt":"\"Mary Anning lived from 1799 to 1847, but her spirit dwelled in a time millions of years ago, when the monsters and dragons we now call dinosaurs roamed. She had little money, but she was rich in spirit. She was unschooled, but the professors heeded her words. She rarely strayed from her home, but her name became known everywhere.\"","stem":"What is the main message the author wants readers to understand about Mary Anning?","choices":{"A":"She was unhappy because she had little money","B":"Even without wealth or formal education, she became respected and famous through her hard work","C":"She should have gone to school instead of collecting fossils","D":"She was lucky to find so many fossils"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author contrasts Mary\u0027s lack of money and schooling with her rich spirit and respected reputation to show her achievements.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary Anning lived from 1799 to 1847, but her spirit dwelled in a time millions of years ago, when the monsters and dragons we now call dinosaurs roamed. She had little money, but she was rich in spirit. She was unschooled, but the professors heeded her words. She rarely strayed from her home, but her name became known everywhere.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l08-q004","read_aloud":"Do you agree with the author\u0027s statement that Mary unearthed knowledge, not just fossils? Why? A. Yes, because the fossils she found helped scientists learn new things about ancient life B. No, because fossils are just rocks and have no value C. Yes, because she became rich from selling fossils D. No, because she did not write any books","excerpt":"\"Mary Anning pried fossils from the ground, but it was knowledge that she unearthed.\"","stem":"Do you agree with the author\u0027s statement that Mary unearthed knowledge, not just fossils? Why?","choices":{"A":"Yes, because the fossils she found helped scientists learn new things about ancient life","B":"No, because fossils are just rocks and have no value","C":"Yes, because she became rich from selling fossils","D":"No, because she did not write any books"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Mary\u0027s fossils were clues that helped scientists understand what life was like millions of years ago, so she helped unearth knowledge.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary Anning pried fossils from the ground, but it was knowledge that she unearthed.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l08-q005","read_aloud":"If you could write a letter to the scientists who studied Mary\u0027s ichthyosaur fossil, what would you want to tell them about giving her credit? A. You should ignore Mary because she is just a child B. You should remember that Mary was the one who found this important fossil C. You should buy more fossils from Mary\u0027s shop D. You should stop studying fossils altogether","excerpt":"\"Almost everyone forgot that it had been found by twelve-year-old Mary Anning and her teenage brother.\"","stem":"If you could write a letter to the scientists who studied Mary\u0027s ichthyosaur fossil, what would you want to tell them about giving her credit?","choices":{"A":"You should ignore Mary because she is just a child","B":"You should remember that Mary was the one who found this important fossil","C":"You should buy more fossils from Mary\u0027s shop","D":"You should stop studying fossils altogether"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Mary deserved credit for her discovery, so a fair letter would ask scientists to remember that she found the fossil.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Almost everyone forgot that it had been found by twelve-year-old Mary Anning and her teenage brother.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l08-q006","read_aloud":"How does the word \"remarkable\" in the title connect to Mary\u0027s life? A. It suggests her discoveries were ordinary and forgettable. B. It suggests her finds were extraordinary and changed science. C. It suggests she was famous for her art, not fossils. D. It suggests she worked only for money.","excerpt":"Mary Anning and Her Remarkable Discoveries","stem":"How does the word \"remarkable\" in the title connect to Mary\u0027s life?","choices":{"A":"It suggests her discoveries were ordinary and forgettable.","B":"It suggests her finds were extraordinary and changed science.","C":"It suggests she was famous for her art, not fossils.","D":"It suggests she worked only for money."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Remarkable means outstanding. The title signals that Mary\u0027s fossil discoveries were special and important to science.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Mary Anning and Her Remarkable Discoveries"},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l08-q007","read_aloud":"(Note: Replacing with Rare Treasure excerpt) (Still wrong-using correct excerpt) What was new about scientists\u0027 understanding of fossils in Mary\u0027s time? A. They knew fossils were just pretty rocks. B. They were starting to see fossils as remains of ancient, extinct life. C. They thought fossils were made by magic. D. They believed fossils could come back to life.","excerpt":"Scientists were just beginning to understand that they were the remains of animals or plants that no longer existed, living things that had died many, many years ago.","stem":"(Note: Replacing with Rare Treasure excerpt) (Still wrong-using correct excerpt) What was new about scientists\u0027 understanding of fossils in Mary\u0027s time?","choices":{"A":"They knew fossils were just pretty rocks.","B":"They were starting to see fossils as remains of ancient, extinct life.","C":"They thought fossils were made by magic.","D":"They believed fossils could come back to life."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says scientists were \"just beginning to understand\" fossils were remains of extinct life. This was a new scientific idea then.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Scientists were just beginning to understand that they were the remains of animals or plants that no longer existed, living things that had died many, many years ago."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l08-q008","read_aloud":"(Replacing with Rare Treasure) (Wrong text-correcting) (Still wrong-final correction) What text structure helps the reader picture the Moon\u0027s surface? (Replacing with Rare Treasure question) What text structure does the author use to describe the plesiosaur? A. Problem and solution B. Description using sensory and comparative details C. Sequence of events D. Cause and effect","excerpt":"It was an astonishing nine-foot-long creature with a long, serpentlike neck, a lizard\u0027s head, a crocodile\u0027s teeth, a chameleon\u0027s ribs, and the paddles of a whale.","stem":"(Replacing with Rare Treasure) (Wrong text-correcting) (Still wrong-final correction) What text structure helps the reader picture the Moon\u0027s surface? (Replacing with Rare Treasure question) What text structure does the author use to describe the plesiosaur?","choices":{"A":"Problem and solution","B":"Description using sensory and comparative details","C":"Sequence of events","D":"Cause and effect"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author uses vivid descriptive details and comparisons (serpentlike, lizard\u0027s hea d) to help readers visualize the creature. This is description structure.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: It was an astonishing nine-foot-long creature with a long, serpentlike neck, a lizard\u0027s head, a crocodile\u0027s teeth, a chameleon\u0027s ribs, and the paddles of a whale."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l08-q009","read_aloud":"Do you think it was fair that Mary was often forgotten when her fossils were presented to scientists? Use clues from the text. A. Yes, because scientists did all the important work. B. No, because Mary found and prepared the fossils, and scientists valued her ideas. C. Yes, because she was not formally educated. D. No, but only because she was a woman.","excerpt":"Mary shared her ideas with the finest scientists. They prized the thoughts of the remarkable young woman who had left school when she was eleven.","stem":"Do you think it was fair that Mary was often forgotten when her fossils were presented to scientists? Use clues from the text.","choices":{"A":"Yes, because scientists did all the important work.","B":"No, because Mary found and prepared the fossils, and scientists valued her ideas.","C":"Yes, because she was not formally educated.","D":"No, but only because she was a woman."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text shows Mary did the hard work of finding fossils and that scientists prized her thoughts. Forgetting her contributions was not fair.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Mary shared her ideas with the finest scientists. They prized the thoughts of the remarkable young woman who had left school when she was eleven."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l08-q010","read_aloud":"Why do you think the author ends the biography with this idea-that Mary \"unearthed knowledge\"? A. To show that digging for fossils was her only skill. B. To highlight that Mary\u0027s greatest discovery was advancing human understanding of ancient life. C. To suggest that knowledge is buried like treasure. D. To complain that Mary did not travel enough.","excerpt":"She rarely strayed from her home, but her name became known everywhere. Mary Anning pried fossils from the ground, but it was knowledge that she unearthed.","stem":"Why do you think the author ends the biography with this idea-that Mary \"unearthed knowledge\"?","choices":{"A":"To show that digging for fossils was her only skill.","B":"To highlight that Mary\u0027s greatest discovery was advancing human understanding of ancient life.","C":"To suggest that knowledge is buried like treasure.","D":"To complain that Mary did not travel enough."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The phrase \"it was knowledge that she unearthed\" connects her fossil finds to bigger scientific discoveries. This ending celebrates her lasting impact.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: She rarely strayed from her home, but her name became known everywhere. Mary Anning pried fossils from the ground, but it was knowledge that she unearthed."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l08-q011","read_aloud":"What does remarkable mean when describing Mary as \"the remarkable young woman\"? (Use context from the whole text.) A. Very ordinary and easy to forget B. Extraordinary and worthy of attention because she achieved so much C. Very young and inexperienced D. Very quiet and shy","excerpt":"\"The discovery excited scientists. Like Mary\u0027s earlier find, the ichthyosaur fossil, it was a rare clue to solving the puzzle of life long ago.\"","stem":"What does remarkable mean when describing Mary as \"the remarkable young woman\"? (Use context from the whole text.)","choices":{"A":"Very ordinary and easy to forget","B":"Extraordinary and worthy of attention because she achieved so much","C":"Very young and inexperienced","D":"Very quiet and shy"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text shows Mary made many important discoveries, taught herself science, and impressed famous professors. Remarkable means she was extraordinary and worthy of attention because she achieved so much despite difficulties.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The discovery excited scientists. Like Mary\u0027s earlier find, the ichthyosaur fossil, it was a rare clue to solving the puzzle of life long ago.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l08-q012","read_aloud":"Why does the author end the story with this sentence? A. To show that fossils were not important B. To show that Mary\u0027s real gift was discovering new knowledge, not just finding old bones C. To show that Mary stopped working D. To show that the ground was soft","excerpt":"\"Mary Anning pried fossils from the ground, but it was knowledge that she unearthed.\"","stem":"Why does the author end the story with this sentence?","choices":{"A":"To show that fossils were not important","B":"To show that Mary\u0027s real gift was discovering new knowledge, not just finding old bones","C":"To show that Mary stopped working","D":"To show that the ground was soft"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author uses a metaphor. \"Pried fossils from the ground\" means she dug them up. \"Unearthed knowledge\" means she discovered new understanding. The ending shows her true importance was the knowledge she shared, not just the fossils.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary Anning pried fossils from the ground, but it was knowledge that she unearthed.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l08-q013","read_aloud":"Why do you think the author includes this sad detail? A. To show that Mary was not important B. To show that people often did not give credit to young people and women in those days C. To show that Joseph found the fossil alone D. To show that scientists were mean","excerpt":"\"Almost everyone forgot that it had been found by twelve-year-old Mary Anning and her teenage brother.\"","stem":"Why do you think the author includes this sad detail?","choices":{"A":"To show that Mary was not important","B":"To show that people often did not give credit to young people and women in those days","C":"To show that Joseph found the fossil alone","D":"To show that scientists were mean"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author wants readers to understand that Mary did not get credit at first. In her time, young people and women were often not respected for their work. This detail helps us see the unfairness Mary faced.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Almost everyone forgot that it had been found by twelve-year-old Mary Anning and her teenage brother.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l08-q014","read_aloud":"she said proudly. Do you think Mary had good reasons to be proud? Use clues from the text. A. No, because she did not go to school B. Yes, because she taught herself, made important discoveries, and became famous despite many hardships C. No, because she was poor D. Yes, because she found only one fossil","excerpt":"I am well known throughout the whole of Europe,","stem":"she said proudly. Do you think Mary had good reasons to be proud? Use clues from the text.","choices":{"A":"No, because she did not go to school","B":"Yes, because she taught herself, made important discoveries, and became famous despite many hardships","C":"No, because she was poor","D":"Yes, because she found only one fossil"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text shows Mary faced poverty, danger, and lack of schooling. Yet she taught herself, found rare fossils, and impressed famous scientists. She worked very hard, so she had good reasons to be proud.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: I am well known throughout the whole of Europe,"},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l08-q015","read_aloud":"Why were Mary\u0027s thoughts considered remarkable? A. She learned everything from school. B. She had very unusual ideas. C. She knew a lot even though she was self-taught. D. She was the only woman in the town.","excerpt":"\"They prized the thoughts of the remarkable young woman who had left school when she was eleven.\"","stem":"Why were Mary\u0027s thoughts considered remarkable?","choices":{"A":"She learned everything from school.","B":"She had very unusual ideas.","C":"She knew a lot even though she was self-taught.","D":"She was the only woman in the town."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Her thoughts were outstanding because she taught herself and knew more than people who went to school.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They prized the thoughts of the remarkable young woman who had left school when she was eleven.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l08-q016","read_aloud":"What does the author mean by \"her spirit dwelled in a time millions of years ago\"? A. She was an old woman who acted young. B. She was very interested in the past and dinosaurs. C. She wished she lived in the future. D. She was afraid of the modern world.","excerpt":"\"Mary Anning lived from 1799 to 1847, but her spirit dwelled in a time millions of years ago, when the monsters and dragons we now call dinosaurs roamed.\"","stem":"What does the author mean by \"her spirit dwelled in a time millions of years ago\"?","choices":{"A":"She was an old woman who acted young.","B":"She was very interested in the past and dinosaurs.","C":"She wished she lived in the future.","D":"She was afraid of the modern world."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"This phrase means she spent her time thinking about and studying ancient history, like the time of dinosaurs.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary Anning lived from 1799 to 1847, but her spirit dwelled in a time millions of years ago, when the monsters and dragons we now call dinosaurs roamed.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l08-q017","read_aloud":"What conclusion can you draw about scientists in the 1800s? A. They did not want to share their ideas. B. They only listened to people who went to college. C. They respected Mary\u0027s knowledge and ideas. D. They thought Mary was not smart enough.","excerpt":"\"Mary shared her ideas with the finest scientists. They prized the thoughts of the remarkable young woman who had left school when she was eleven.\"","stem":"What conclusion can you draw about scientists in the 1800s?","choices":{"A":"They did not want to share their ideas.","B":"They only listened to people who went to college.","C":"They respected Mary\u0027s knowledge and ideas.","D":"They thought Mary was not smart enough."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Since they \"prized\" her thoughts, it shows they respected and valued what she had to say.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary shared her ideas with the finest scientists. They prized the thoughts of the remarkable young woman who had left school when she was eleven.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l08-q018","read_aloud":"Do you think Mary deserved this praise? A. No, because she did not go to school long enough. B. Yes, because she studied hard and found many important fossils. C. No, because other scientists were older than her. D. Yes, because she had a lot of money to buy books.","excerpt":"\"It was said, \u0027She knows more about the science than anyone else.\u0027\"","stem":"Do you think Mary deserved this praise?","choices":{"A":"No, because she did not go to school long enough.","B":"Yes, because she studied hard and found many important fossils.","C":"No, because other scientists were older than her.","D":"Yes, because she had a lot of money to buy books."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"She deserved the praise because she taught herself and made major discoveries that others could not make.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It was said, \u0027She knows more about the science than anyone else.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l08-q019","read_aloud":"How would the meaning change if the author said \"knowledge that she read in books\"? A. It would show she was a fast reader. B. It would show she did not do the hard work herself. C. It would take away from the idea that she discovered new things. D. It would make the story more exciting.","excerpt":"\"Mary Anning pried fossils from the ground, but it was knowledge that she unearthed.\"","stem":"How would the meaning change if the author said \"knowledge that she read in books\"?","choices":{"A":"It would show she was a fast reader.","B":"It would show she did not do the hard work herself.","C":"It would take away from the idea that she discovered new things.","D":"It would make the story more exciting."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"\"Unearthed knowledge\" implies she discovered new ideas through her digging. Reading books would not show her active discovery.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary Anning pried fossils from the ground, but it was knowledge that she unearthed.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l08-q020","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about Use text evidence.? A. Having a lot of money and toys B. Having very little money or possessions C. Being very happy all the time D. Being sick and unable to work","excerpt":"\"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"Having a lot of money and toys","B":"Having very little money or possessions","C":"Being very happy all the time","D":"Being sick and unable to work"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Poor\" means not having much money. The text says Mary\u0027s life was hard, which shows she did not have many things.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l08-q021","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. Having a lot of money and toys B. Having very little money or possessions C. Being very happy all the time D. Being sick and unable to work","excerpt":"\"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"Having a lot of money and toys","B":"Having very little money or possessions","C":"Being very happy all the time","D":"Being sick and unable to work"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Poor\" means not having much money. The text says Mary\u0027s life was hard, which shows she did not have many things.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l08-q022","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? A. Having a lot of money and toys B. Having very little money or possessions C. Being very happy all the time D. Being sick and unable to work","excerpt":"\"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ?","choices":{"A":"Having a lot of money and toys","B":"Having very little money or possessions","C":"Being very happy all the time","D":"Being sick and unable to work"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Poor\" means not having much money. The text says Mary\u0027s life was hard, which shows she did not have many things.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l08-q023","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. The dog was afraid of Mary B. The dog was a loyal companion and helper C. The dog did not like going on fossil hunts D. The dog was trained by Mary\u0027s father","excerpt":"\"Mary\u0027s dog trotted faithfully beside her. People said the dog guarded her discoveries while she fetched her tools or got help.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"The dog was afraid of Mary","B":"The dog was a loyal companion and helper","C":"The dog did not like going on fossil hunts","D":"The dog was trained by Mary\u0027s father"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The dog trotted faithfully beside Mary and guarded her discoveries, which shows the dog was loyal and helpful.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary\u0027s dog trotted faithfully beside her. People said the dog guarded her discoveries while she fetched her tools or got help.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l08-q024","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. Seven feet long B. Nine feet long C. Twelve feet long D. Three feet long","excerpt":"\"In 1823, Mary discovered the first complete fossil of a plesiosaur, another reptile that had lived in the sea. It was an astonishing nine-foot-long creature with a long, serpentlike neck, a lizard\u0027s head, a crocodile\u0027s teeth, a chameleon\u0027s ribs, and the paddles of a whale.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"Seven feet long","B":"Nine feet long","C":"Twelve feet long","D":"Three feet long"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says \"It was an astonishing nine-foot-long creature.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1823, Mary discovered the first complete fossil of a plesiosaur, another reptile that had lived in the sea. It was an astonishing nine-foot-long creature with a long, serpentlike neck, a lizard\u0027s head, a crocodile\u0027s teeth, a chameleon\u0027s ribs, and the paddles of a whale.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l08-q025","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. To show that Mary was not a good fossil hunter B. To show that Mary did not receive the credit she deserved at first C. To show that Joseph found more fossils than Mary D. To show that fossils were not important discoveries","excerpt":"\"Almost everyone forgot that it had been found by twelve-year-old Mary Anning and her teenage brother.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"To show that Mary was not a good fossil hunter","B":"To show that Mary did not receive the credit she deserved at first","C":"To show that Joseph found more fossils than Mary","D":"To show that fossils were not important discoveries"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author includes this detail to show that even though Mary made an important discovery, people did not give her credit because she was young.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Almost everyone forgot that it had been found by twelve-year-old Mary Anning and her teenage brother.\""}]},{"level":9,"level_name":"Level 9","difficulty_band":"mastery","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l09-q001","read_aloud":"What does the word \"assembled\" mean in this sentence? A. Lost or misplaced B. Put or brought together C. Sold to customers D. Hidden from view","excerpt":"\"Mary assembled a wonderful collection of fossils in her shop on Broad Street. One visitor wished to record the name of the woman who had assembled such a wonderful collection.\"","stem":"What does the word \"assembled\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Lost or misplaced","B":"Put or brought together","C":"Sold to customers","D":"Hidden from view"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Assembled\" means gathered or brought together. Mary collected and brought together many fossils in her shop.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary assembled a wonderful collection of fossils in her shop on Broad Street. One visitor wished to record the name of the woman who had assembled such a wonderful collection.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l09-q002","read_aloud":"What does Mary\u0027s pride in being known throughout Europe reveal about her character? A. She was boastful and unkind B. She was proud of her hard-earned reputation and accomplishments C. She wanted to move to Europe to be more famous D. She did not care about what others thought","excerpt":"\"I am well known throughout the whole of Europe,\u0027 she said proudly.\"","stem":"What does Mary\u0027s pride in being known throughout Europe reveal about her character?","choices":{"A":"She was boastful and unkind","B":"She was proud of her hard-earned reputation and accomplishments","C":"She wanted to move to Europe to be more famous","D":"She did not care about what others thought"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Mary worked very hard her whole life. Being known across Europe was a great achievement, and she had earned the right to be proud.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I am well known throughout the whole of Europe,\u0027 she said proudly.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l09-q003","read_aloud":"How does the author\u0027s word choice of \"monsters and dragons\" help readers understand how people might have viewed fossils in Mary\u0027s time? A. It shows that people knew exactly what dinosaurs were B. It shows that people did not understand fossils and thought they might be from monsters C. It shows that Mary was afraid of the fossils she found D. It shows that dinosaurs were still alive when Mary was born","excerpt":"\"Mary Anning lived from 1799 to 1847, but her spirit dwelled in a time millions of years ago, when the monsters and dragons we now call dinosaurs roamed.\"","stem":"How does the author\u0027s word choice of \"monsters and dragons\" help readers understand how people might have viewed fossils in Mary\u0027s time?","choices":{"A":"It shows that people knew exactly what dinosaurs were","B":"It shows that people did not understand fossils and thought they might be from monsters","C":"It shows that Mary was afraid of the fossils she found","D":"It shows that dinosaurs were still alive when Mary was born"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In Mary\u0027s time, people did not fully understand fossils. Words like \"monsters and dragons\" suggest they imagined strange creatures.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary Anning lived from 1799 to 1847, but her spirit dwelled in a time millions of years ago, when the monsters and dragons we now call dinosaurs roamed.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l09-q004","read_aloud":"Do you think Mary\u0027s success as a fossil hunter came mostly from natural talent or from hard work? Use details from the text. A. Mostly from talent alone, because she was born with good eyesight B. Mostly from hard work, because she spent years practicing and learning to see what others missed C. Only from luck, because she happened to live near cliffs D. Only from help, because others always showed her where to look","excerpt":"\"Mary\u0027s sharp eyes spotted fossils where others saw nothing.\"","stem":"Do you think Mary\u0027s success as a fossil hunter came mostly from natural talent or from hard work? Use details from the text.","choices":{"A":"Mostly from talent alone, because she was born with good eyesight","B":"Mostly from hard work, because she spent years practicing and learning to see what others missed","C":"Only from luck, because she happened to live near cliffs","D":"Only from help, because others always showed her where to look"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Mary worked hard from childhood, taught herself from books, and spent long days searching. Her skill came from dedication and practice.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary\u0027s sharp eyes spotted fossils where others saw nothing.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l09-q005","read_aloud":"How might Mary\u0027s life have been different if she had traveled to other countries to share her knowledge? A. She would have found fewer fossils by traveling B. She might have become even more famous and met more scientists around the world C. She would have stopped collecting fossils completely D. No one would have listened to her in other countries","excerpt":"\"She rarely strayed from her home, but her name became known everywhere.\"","stem":"How might Mary\u0027s life have been different if she had traveled to other countries to share her knowledge?","choices":{"A":"She would have found fewer fossils by traveling","B":"She might have become even more famous and met more scientists around the world","C":"She would have stopped collecting fossils completely","D":"No one would have listened to her in other countries"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Traveling would have allowed Mary to share her knowledge with more people and possibly become even more well-known.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"She rarely strayed from her home, but her name became known everywhere.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l09-q006","read_aloud":"Which sentence best shows the meaning of \"poverty\" using context clues? A. The family had extra money from selling fossils. B. After her father died, the family had very little money and struggled to survive. C. The family moved to a bigger house. D. The family bought many new things.","excerpt":"The family struggled to survive on the earnings of Richard\u0027s carpentry work, and the extra money they earned by selling fossils helped. Then Mary\u0027s father died and the family was thrown into bitter poverty.","stem":"Which sentence best shows the meaning of \"poverty\" using context clues?","choices":{"A":"The family had extra money from selling fossils.","B":"After her father died, the family had very little money and struggled to survive.","C":"The family moved to a bigger house.","D":"The family bought many new things."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text contrasts earning extra money with being \"thrown into bitter poverty\" after the father died, showing poverty means extreme lack of money.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The family struggled to survive on the earnings of Richard\u0027s carpentry work, and the extra money they earned by selling fossils helped. Then Mary\u0027s father died and the family was thrown into bitter poverty."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l09-q007","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this paragraph? A. Fossils are easy to find on any beach. B. Fossils form through a rare, slow process where remains are buried and turned to stone. C. All plants and animals become fossils when they die. D. Minerals destroy fossils over time.","excerpt":"Usually the remains of plants and animals decompose or are eaten, but sometimes they are covered by dirt or sink in mud. Of these, a rare few lie undisturbed for millions of years. While they are buried, the soft parts, such as flesh, decay, leaving bones, shell, or flat impressions in the earth. Minerals seep into these remains and become stone.","stem":"What is the main idea of this paragraph?","choices":{"A":"Fossils are easy to find on any beach.","B":"Fossils form through a rare, slow process where remains are buried and turned to stone.","C":"All plants and animals become fossils when they die.","D":"Minerals destroy fossils over time."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The paragraph explains the specific, rare conditions needed for fossils to form. The other choices misstate or oversimplify the process.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Usually the remains of plants and animals decompose or are eaten, but sometimes they are covered by dirt or sink in mud. Of these, a rare few lie undisturbed for millions of years. While they are buried, the soft parts, such as flesh, decay, leaving bones, shell, or flat impressions in the earth. Minerals seep into these remains and become stone."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l09-q008","read_aloud":"What do these details help the reader understand about fossil collecting? A. It was always safe and easy. B. It was exciting but also dangerous and required courage. C. It was only done by men. D. It was boring and slow.","excerpt":"During one hunt, part of a cliff collapsed. Heavy rocks crashed at Mary\u0027s feet and nearly crushed her. Another time, Mary found a large fossil. She and a helper labored to recover it. The hard work blinded Mary to the rising tide that flooded the beach. Waves drenched the pair, but they saved the treasure.","stem":"What do these details help the reader understand about fossil collecting?","choices":{"A":"It was always safe and easy.","B":"It was exciting but also dangerous and required courage.","C":"It was only done by men.","D":"It was boring and slow."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text describes real dangers like falling rocks and rising tides, showing fossil hunting was risky but rewarding. This adds depth to Mary\u0027s story.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: During one hunt, part of a cliff collapsed. Heavy rocks crashed at Mary\u0027s feet and nearly crushed her. Another time, Mary found a large fossil. She and a helper labored to recover it. The hard work blinded Mary to the rising tide that flooded the beach. Waves drenched the pair, but they saved the treasure."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l09-q009","read_aloud":"Do you think Mary\u0027s habit of studying and sharing her ideas was important to her success? Why or why not? A. No, because finding fossils was all that mattered. B. Yes, because studying and sharing helped her learn more and earn scientists\u0027 respect. C. No, because scientists did not listen to her. D. Yes, but only because she had a college degree.","excerpt":"Mary tried to make sense of her discoveries. She read her science books and studied her collection. Mary shared her ideas with the finest scientists.","stem":"Do you think Mary\u0027s habit of studying and sharing her ideas was important to her success? Why or why not?","choices":{"A":"No, because finding fossils was all that mattered.","B":"Yes, because studying and sharing helped her learn more and earn scientists\u0027 respect.","C":"No, because scientists did not listen to her.","D":"Yes, but only because she had a college degree."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text shows Mary\u0027s self-education and collaboration with scientists helped her grow and be valued. This supports the idea that her habits contributed to her success.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Mary tried to make sense of her discoveries. She read her science books and studied her collection. Mary shared her ideas with the finest scientists."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l09-q010","read_aloud":"Imagine you are writing a short tribute to Mary Anning for a museum plaque. What is one sentence you might write to honor her legacy? A. \"Mary Anning found pretty rocks on the beach.\" B. \"Mary Anning\u0027s careful work and sharp mind helped unlock the secrets of ancient life for all of us.\" C. \"Mary Anning was lucky to find fossils.\" D. \"Mary Anning liked to walk on the beach.\"","excerpt":"Mary Anning pried fossils from the ground, but it was knowledge that she unearthed.","stem":"Imagine you are writing a short tribute to Mary Anning for a museum plaque. What is one sentence you might write to honor her legacy?","choices":{"A":"\"Mary Anning found pretty rocks on the beach.\"","B":"\"Mary Anning\u0027s careful work and sharp mind helped unlock the secrets of ancient life for all of us.\"","C":"\"Mary Anning was lucky to find fossils.\"","D":"\"Mary Anning liked to walk on the beach.\""},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"This tribute captures Mary\u0027s skill, intelligence, and lasting impact on science, matching the biography\u0027s message. The other sentences are too simple or miss her contributions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Mary Anning pried fossils from the ground, but it was knowledge that she unearthed."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l09-q011","read_aloud":"What type of figurative language is \"rugged ribbon of shore,\" and what does it mean? A. It is a simile comparing the shore to a ribbon B. It is a metaphor comparing the shore to a ribbon-long, thin, and rough C. It is a question about the shore D. It is a fact stating the shore was made of ribbon","excerpt":"\"Mary and Joseph still collected and sold fossils they found on the rugged ribbon of shore that separated the sea and the cliffs.\"","stem":"What type of figurative language is \"rugged ribbon of shore,\" and what does it mean?","choices":{"A":"It is a simile comparing the shore to a ribbon","B":"It is a metaphor comparing the shore to a ribbon-long, thin, and rough","C":"It is a question about the shore","D":"It is a fact stating the shore was made of ribbon"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author uses a metaphor (compares without using \"like\" or \"as\") to compare the shore to a ribbon. \"Rugged\" means rough, and a ribbon is long and thin. This helps us picture the narrow, rough strip of beach.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary and Joseph still collected and sold fossils they found on the rugged ribbon of shore that separated the sea and the cliffs.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l09-q012","read_aloud":"Why does the author use both a simile and a metaphor in these sentences? A. To confuse the reader B. To help readers feel and understand Mary\u0027s difficult life and bright spirit through vivid comparisons C. To make the sentences longer D. To show that Mary liked rocks","excerpt":"\"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\"","stem":"Why does the author use both a simile and a metaphor in these sentences?","choices":{"A":"To confuse the reader","B":"To help readers feel and understand Mary\u0027s difficult life and bright spirit through vivid comparisons","C":"To make the sentences longer","D":"To show that Mary liked rocks"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Hard as stone\" (simile) helps us feel how difficult her life was. \"Shone like a gem\" (simile) helps us see how bright and valuable her spirit was. The figurative language makes the description vivid and emotional.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l09-q013","read_aloud":"Why does the author list so many fossils? A. To make the paragraph boring B. To show the amazing variety and large number of Mary\u0027s discoveries C. To show that Mary was confused D. To list fossils that were not important","excerpt":"\"By 1836, Mary had found the fossils of three ichthyosaurs, two plesiosaurs, a pterodactyl, a strange sharklike fish called Squaloraja, and an untold number of small or incomplete fossils.\"","stem":"Why does the author list so many fossils?","choices":{"A":"To make the paragraph boring","B":"To show the amazing variety and large number of Mary\u0027s discoveries","C":"To show that Mary was confused","D":"To list fossils that were not important"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The long list shows readers that Mary found many different kinds of fossils over her lifetime. This proves she was an extraordinary and dedicated fossil collector.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"By 1836, Mary had found the fossils of three ichthyosaurs, two plesiosaurs, a pterodactyl, a strange sharklike fish called Squaloraja, and an untold number of small or incomplete fossils.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l09-q014","read_aloud":"How had Mary\u0027s life changed from the beginning of the story to this point? A. She went from being unknown and poor to being famous and successful B. She stayed poor and unknown C. She stopped collecting fossils D. She moved away from Lyme Regis","excerpt":"\"Mary\u0027s fossil shop on Broad Street was now crowded with customers.\"","stem":"How had Mary\u0027s life changed from the beginning of the story to this point?","choices":{"A":"She went from being unknown and poor to being famous and successful","B":"She stayed poor and unknown","C":"She stopped collecting fossils","D":"She moved away from Lyme Regis"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"At the start, Mary was poor, her father had died, and \"almost everyone forgot\" her discoveries. Later, her shop was \"crowded with customers\" and she was \"well known throughout the whole of Europe.\" Her life changed greatly.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary\u0027s fossil shop on Broad Street was now crowded with customers.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l09-q015","read_aloud":"Which word is an antonym (opposite) for assembled? A. Collected B. Separated C. Gathered D. Organized","excerpt":"\"One visitor wished to record the name of the woman who had assembled such a wonderful collection.\"","stem":"Which word is an antonym (opposite) for assembled?","choices":{"A":"Collected","B":"Separated","C":"Gathered","D":"Organized"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Assembled means to bring things together. Separated means to take things apart.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"One visitor wished to record the name of the woman who had assembled such a wonderful collection.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l09-q016","read_aloud":"Why were scientists excited about the plesiosaur? A. It was worth a lot of money. B. It was a clue to understanding the past. C. It was found in a new location. D. It was the first fossil Mary found.","excerpt":"\"The discovery excited scientists. Like Mary\u0027s earlier find, the ichthyosaur fossil, it was a rare clue to solving the puzzle of life long ago.\"","stem":"Why were scientists excited about the plesiosaur?","choices":{"A":"It was worth a lot of money.","B":"It was a clue to understanding the past.","C":"It was found in a new location.","D":"It was the first fossil Mary found."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the fossil was a \"rare clue to solving the puzzle of life long ago.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The discovery excited scientists. Like Mary\u0027s earlier find, the ichthyosaur fossil, it was a rare clue to solving the puzzle of life long ago.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l09-q017","read_aloud":"What needs to happen for a fossil to form? A. The remains must be eaten by animals. B. The remains must decompose quickly. C. The remains must be covered by dirt or mud. D. The remains must be left on the surface.","excerpt":"\"Usually the remains of plants and animals decompose or are eaten, but sometimes they are covered by dirt or sink in mud.\"","stem":"What needs to happen for a fossil to form?","choices":{"A":"The remains must be eaten by animals.","B":"The remains must decompose quickly.","C":"The remains must be covered by dirt or mud.","D":"The remains must be left on the surface."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text explains that for fossils to form, the remains must be covered by dirt or sink in mud.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Usually the remains of plants and animals decompose or are eaten, but sometimes they are covered by dirt or sink in mud.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l09-q018","read_aloud":"What is the author\u0027s purpose for including the phrase \"rich in spirit\"? A. To show that Mary had a lot of money in the bank. B. To show Mary was greedy with her money. C. To show Mary was happy and strong inside despite being poor. D. To show Mary wanted to be rich one day.","excerpt":"\"Mary Anning lived from 1799 to 1847... She had little money, but she was rich in spirit.\"","stem":"What is the author\u0027s purpose for including the phrase \"rich in spirit\"?","choices":{"A":"To show that Mary had a lot of money in the bank.","B":"To show Mary was greedy with her money.","C":"To show Mary was happy and strong inside despite being poor.","D":"To show Mary wanted to be rich one day."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Being \"rich in spirit\" is a way to say she had a good character and inner strength, even though she was poor.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary Anning lived from 1799 to 1847... She had little money, but she was rich in spirit.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l09-q019","read_aloud":"How does this list support the title \"Rare Treasure\"? A. It shows she found a lot of junk on the beach. B. It proves she was the only person looking for fossils. C. It shows she found many valuable and rare things. D. It explains why she was poor for so long.","excerpt":"\"By 1836, Mary had found the fossils of three ichthyosaurs, two plesiosaurs, a pterodactyl, a strange sharklike fish called Squaloraja, and an untold number of small or incomplete fossils.\"","stem":"How does this list support the title \"Rare Treasure\"?","choices":{"A":"It shows she found a lot of junk on the beach.","B":"It proves she was the only person looking for fossils.","C":"It shows she found many valuable and rare things.","D":"It explains why she was poor for so long."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The list shows she found many different types of rare fossils, which supports the idea that she found \"rare treasures.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"By 1836, Mary had found the fossils of three ichthyosaurs, two plesiosaurs, a pterodactyl, a strange sharklike fish called Squaloraja, and an untold number of small or incomplete fossils.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l09-q020","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about Use text evidence.? A. Having a lot of money and toys B. Having very little money or possessions C. Being very happy all the time D. Being sick and unable to work","excerpt":"\"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"Having a lot of money and toys","B":"Having very little money or possessions","C":"Being very happy all the time","D":"Being sick and unable to work"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Poor\" means not having much money. The text says Mary\u0027s life was hard, which shows she did not have many things.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l09-q021","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. Having a lot of money and toys B. Having very little money or possessions C. Being very happy all the time D. Being sick and unable to work","excerpt":"\"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"Having a lot of money and toys","B":"Having very little money or possessions","C":"Being very happy all the time","D":"Being sick and unable to work"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Poor\" means not having much money. The text says Mary\u0027s life was hard, which shows she did not have many things.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l09-q022","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? A. Having a lot of money and toys B. Having very little money or possessions C. Being very happy all the time D. Being sick and unable to work","excerpt":"\"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ?","choices":{"A":"Having a lot of money and toys","B":"Having very little money or possessions","C":"Being very happy all the time","D":"Being sick and unable to work"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Poor\" means not having much money. The text says Mary\u0027s life was hard, which shows she did not have many things.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l09-q023","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. The dog was afraid of Mary B. The dog was a loyal companion and helper C. The dog did not like going on fossil hunts D. The dog was trained by Mary\u0027s father","excerpt":"\"Mary\u0027s dog trotted faithfully beside her. People said the dog guarded her discoveries while she fetched her tools or got help.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"The dog was afraid of Mary","B":"The dog was a loyal companion and helper","C":"The dog did not like going on fossil hunts","D":"The dog was trained by Mary\u0027s father"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The dog trotted faithfully beside Mary and guarded her discoveries, which shows the dog was loyal and helpful.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary\u0027s dog trotted faithfully beside her. People said the dog guarded her discoveries while she fetched her tools or got help.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l09-q024","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. Seven feet long B. Nine feet long C. Twelve feet long D. Three feet long","excerpt":"\"In 1823, Mary discovered the first complete fossil of a plesiosaur, another reptile that had lived in the sea. It was an astonishing nine-foot-long creature with a long, serpentlike neck, a lizard\u0027s head, a crocodile\u0027s teeth, a chameleon\u0027s ribs, and the paddles of a whale.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"Seven feet long","B":"Nine feet long","C":"Twelve feet long","D":"Three feet long"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says \"It was an astonishing nine-foot-long creature.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1823, Mary discovered the first complete fossil of a plesiosaur, another reptile that had lived in the sea. It was an astonishing nine-foot-long creature with a long, serpentlike neck, a lizard\u0027s head, a crocodile\u0027s teeth, a chameleon\u0027s ribs, and the paddles of a whale.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l09-q025","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. To show that Mary was not a good fossil hunter B. To show that Mary did not receive the credit she deserved at first C. To show that Joseph found more fossils than Mary D. To show that fossils were not important discoveries","excerpt":"\"Almost everyone forgot that it had been found by twelve-year-old Mary Anning and her teenage brother.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"To show that Mary was not a good fossil hunter","B":"To show that Mary did not receive the credit she deserved at first","C":"To show that Joseph found more fossils than Mary","D":"To show that fossils were not important discoveries"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author includes this detail to show that even though Mary made an important discovery, people did not give her credit because she was young.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Almost everyone forgot that it had been found by twelve-year-old Mary Anning and her teenage brother.\""}]},{"level":10,"level_name":"Level 10","difficulty_band":"mastery","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l10-q001","read_aloud":"Why does the author use the metaphor \"her spirit shone-it shone like a gem\" to describe Mary? A. To show that Mary collected and sold gems B. To show that Mary\u0027s inner strength and brightness sparkled even when her life was hard C. To show that Mary was rich and owned many jewels D. To show that Mary\u0027s spirit was weak and dull","excerpt":"\"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\"","stem":"Why does the author use the metaphor \"her spirit shone-it shone like a gem\" to describe Mary?","choices":{"A":"To show that Mary collected and sold gems","B":"To show that Mary\u0027s inner strength and brightness sparkled even when her life was hard","C":"To show that Mary was rich and owned many jewels","D":"To show that Mary\u0027s spirit was weak and dull"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A gem shines brightly. The author compares Mary\u0027s spirit to a gem to show that she was strong and bright despite her hard life.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l10-q002","read_aloud":"How does the author help readers understand why fossils were considered \"strange and mysterious\" during Mary\u0027s childhood? A. By explaining that scientists did not yet fully understand what fossils were B. By saying that fossils were worth a lot of money C. By describing how Mary cleaned her fossils D. By listing all the places where fossils could be found","excerpt":"\"Richard Anning taught them how to hunt for fossils. Fossils were strange and mysterious. Although they had been found before, scientists were just beginning to understand that they were the remains of animals or plants that no longer existed.\"","stem":"How does the author help readers understand why fossils were considered \"strange and mysterious\" during Mary\u0027s childhood?","choices":{"A":"By explaining that scientists did not yet fully understand what fossils were","B":"By saying that fossils were worth a lot of money","C":"By describing how Mary cleaned her fossils","D":"By listing all the places where fossils could be found"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The author explains that scientists were \"just beginning to understand\" that fossils were remains of animals that no longer existed, which is why they seemed mysterious.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Richard Anning taught them how to hunt for fossils. Fossils were strange and mysterious. Although they had been found before, scientists were just beginning to understand that they were the remains of animals or plants that no longer existed.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l10-q003","read_aloud":"What do the details about Mary working carefully, drawing pictures, and studying books reveal about her approach to fossils? A. She treated fossil collecting as a serious scientific practice, not just a way to make money B. She wanted to make her fossils look more beautiful than they really were C. She was slow and did not know what she was doing D. She copied what other fossil collectors did without thinking","excerpt":"\"Mary worked very carefully, sometimes for days, to avoid damaging the fossils. Sometimes she cemented a fossil to a frame to help support it. She drew pictures of them. She studied her science books.\"","stem":"What do the details about Mary working carefully, drawing pictures, and studying books reveal about her approach to fossils?","choices":{"A":"She treated fossil collecting as a serious scientific practice, not just a way to make money","B":"She wanted to make her fossils look more beautiful than they really were","C":"She was slow and did not know what she was doing","D":"She copied what other fossil collectors did without thinking"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Mary\u0027s careful work, drawing, and studying show that she was a true scientist who respected the fossils and wanted to learn from them.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary worked very carefully, sometimes for days, to avoid damaging the fossils. Sometimes she cemented a fossil to a frame to help support it. She drew pictures of them. She studied her science books.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l10-q004","read_aloud":"Why do you think it was significant that Mary, a woman in the 1800s, was called a \"talented scientist\" when most scientists at that time were men? A. It was not significant because women were always treated equally B. It was significant because it showed that Mary broke through barriers and earned respect despite the challenges women faced C. It was significant because Mary wanted to become a doctor instead D. It was not significant because Mary did not care about science","excerpt":"\"Mary Anning\u0027s fame grew as people learned that she was an extraordinary fossil collector and a talented scientist.\"","stem":"Why do you think it was significant that Mary, a woman in the 1800s, was called a \"talented scientist\" when most scientists at that time were men?","choices":{"A":"It was not significant because women were always treated equally","B":"It was significant because it showed that Mary broke through barriers and earned respect despite the challenges women faced","C":"It was significant because Mary wanted to become a doctor instead","D":"It was not significant because Mary did not care about science"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In the 1800s, women were often not taken seriously as scientists. Mary earned that title through her remarkable work, which was a great achievement.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary Anning\u0027s fame grew as people learned that she was an extraordinary fossil collector and a talented scientist.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l10-q005","read_aloud":"If Mary were alive today, what award or recognition do you think she should receive for her work, and why? A. An award for cooking, because she had to make her own meals B. A science award for her contributions to paleontology and our understanding of prehistoric life C. An award for farming, because she spent time outdoors D. A music award, because she liked to sing","excerpt":"\"Mary Anning pried fossils from the ground, but it was knowledge that she unearthed.\"","stem":"If Mary were alive today, what award or recognition do you think she should receive for her work, and why?","choices":{"A":"An award for cooking, because she had to make her own meals","B":"A science award for her contributions to paleontology and our understanding of prehistoric life","C":"An award for farming, because she spent time outdoors","D":"A music award, because she liked to sing"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Mary\u0027s work helped scientists understand ancient life. Today, she would likely receive recognition for her contributions to the field of paleontology.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary Anning pried fossils from the ground, but it was knowledge that she unearthed.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l10-q006","read_aloud":"How does the word \"treacherous\" deepen our understanding of Mary\u0027s work? A. It shows the cliffs were safe and easy to climb. B. It shows Mary faced hidden dangers but kept working with courage. C. It shows Mary only worked on sunny days. D. It shows fossils were easy to find.","excerpt":"Day after day, Mary searched in the shadows of the treacherous cliffs, sometimes walking ten miles in one day. Her sharp eyes spotted fossils where others saw nothing.","stem":"How does the word \"treacherous\" deepen our understanding of Mary\u0027s work?","choices":{"A":"It shows the cliffs were safe and easy to climb.","B":"It shows Mary faced hidden dangers but kept working with courage.","C":"It shows Mary only worked on sunny days.","D":"It shows fossils were easy to find."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Treacherous means dangerously unpredictable. Using this word highlights Mary\u0027s bravery and dedication in risky conditions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Day after day, Mary searched in the shadows of the treacherous cliffs, sometimes walking ten miles in one day. Her sharp eyes spotted fossils where others saw nothing."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l10-q007","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this final paragraph? A. Mary was poor and uneducated, so her work did not matter. B. Despite humble circumstances, Mary\u0027s passion and skill led to great scientific impact. C. Mary traveled the world to share her fossils. D. Mary only cared about collecting, not science.","excerpt":"She had little money, but she was rich in spirit. She was unschooled, but the professors heeded her words. She rarely strayed from her home, but her name became known everywhere. Mary Anning pried fossils from the ground, but it was knowledge that she unearthed.","stem":"What is the main idea of this final paragraph?","choices":{"A":"Mary was poor and uneducated, so her work did not matter.","B":"Despite humble circumstances, Mary\u0027s passion and skill led to great scientific impact.","C":"Mary traveled the world to share her fossils.","D":"Mary only cared about collecting, not science."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The paragraph uses contrasts to show how Mary\u0027s inner qualities and work led to worldwide recognition and scientific contribution. This is the central message.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: She had little money, but she was rich in spirit. She was unschooled, but the professors heeded her words. She rarely strayed from her home, but her name became known everywhere. Mary Anning pried fossils from the ground, but it was knowledge that she unearthed."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l10-q008","read_aloud":"How does the author\u0027s use of comparisons (serpentlike, lizard\u0027s head, etc.) help the reader? A. It makes the creature sound scary and fictional. B. It helps readers picture a strange, real animal by connecting it to familiar creatures. C. It confuses readers with too many details. D. It suggests the fossil was not real.","excerpt":"It was an astonishing nine-foot-long creature with a long, serpentlike neck, a lizard\u0027s head, a crocodile\u0027s teeth, a chameleon\u0027s ribs, and the paddles of a whale.","stem":"How does the author\u0027s use of comparisons (serpentlike, lizard\u0027s head, etc.) help the reader?","choices":{"A":"It makes the creature sound scary and fictional.","B":"It helps readers picture a strange, real animal by connecting it to familiar creatures.","C":"It confuses readers with too many details.","D":"It suggests the fossil was not real."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Comparing parts of the plesiosaur to known animals helps readers visualize this extinct creature. This technique makes scientific description vivid and clear.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: It was an astonishing nine-foot-long creature with a long, serpentlike neck, a lizard\u0027s head, a crocodile\u0027s teeth, a chameleon\u0027s ribs, and the paddles of a whale."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l10-q009","read_aloud":"Do you think it matters that Mary\u0027s early discoveries were not credited to her? Why or why not? A. No, because the fossils were what mattered, not who found them. B. Yes, because recognizing her contributions honors her hard work and encourages others. C. No, because she was just a child. D. Yes, but only because she became famous later.","excerpt":"Almost everyone forgot that it had been found by twelve-year-old Mary Anning and her teenage brother.","stem":"Do you think it matters that Mary\u0027s early discoveries were not credited to her? Why or why not?","choices":{"A":"No, because the fossils were what mattered, not who found them.","B":"Yes, because recognizing her contributions honors her hard work and encourages others.","C":"No, because she was just a child.","D":"Yes, but only because she became famous later."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Crediting discoverers respects their effort and inspires future scientists. The text shows Mary\u0027s later recognition was important, suggesting early credit would have been fair.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Almost everyone forgot that it had been found by twelve-year-old Mary Anning and her teenage brother."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l10-q010","read_aloud":"If Mary could send one message to young scientists today, what might she say based on her life story? A. \"Only study if you have money and formal schooling.\" B. \"Stay curious, work hard, and share what you learn-your passion can change the world.\" C. \"Collect pretty rocks and keep them to yourself.\" D. \"Wait for others to tell you what to discover.\"","excerpt":"Mary Anning pried fossils from the ground, but it was knowledge that she unearthed.","stem":"If Mary could send one message to young scientists today, what might she say based on her life story?","choices":{"A":"\"Only study if you have money and formal schooling.\"","B":"\"Stay curious, work hard, and share what you learn-your passion can change the world.\"","C":"\"Collect pretty rocks and keep them to yourself.\"","D":"\"Wait for others to tell you what to discover.\""},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Mary\u0027s life shows that curiosity, self-education, perseverance, and sharing knowledge led to great impact. This message reflects her journey and values.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Mary Anning pried fossils from the ground, but it was knowledge that she unearthed."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l10-q011","read_aloud":"Which word is an antonym (opposite) of rugged as used here? A. Rough B. Smooth C. Long D. Narrow","excerpt":"\"Mary and Joseph still collected and sold fossils they found on the rugged ribbon of shore that separated the sea and the cliffs.\"","stem":"Which word is an antonym (opposite) of rugged as used here?","choices":{"A":"Rough","B":"Smooth","C":"Long","D":"Narrow"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Rugged means rough and uneven. The opposite of rough is smooth. The other words (long, narrow) describe shape, not texture.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary and Joseph still collected and sold fossils they found on the rugged ribbon of shore that separated the sea and the cliffs.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l10-q012","read_aloud":"What is the main theme or message of these sentences? A. Money is the most important thing in life B. Inner strength, hard work, and passion can overcome obstacles like poverty and lack of schooling C. Traveling far is necessary to become famous D. Professors are smarter than everyone else","excerpt":"\"She had little money, but she was rich in spirit. She was unschooled, but the professors heeded her words. She rarely strayed from her home, but her name became known everywhere.\"","stem":"What is the main theme or message of these sentences?","choices":{"A":"Money is the most important thing in life","B":"Inner strength, hard work, and passion can overcome obstacles like poverty and lack of schooling","C":"Traveling far is necessary to become famous","D":"Professors are smarter than everyone else"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Each sentence shows Mary had a disadvantage (little money, no schooling, stayed home) but achieved something positive anyway. The theme is that inner strength and hard work help people overcome difficulties.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"She had little money, but she was rich in spirit. She was unschooled, but the professors heeded her words. She rarely strayed from her home, but her name became known everywhere.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l10-q013","read_aloud":"Do you think Don Brown wrote this biography to inform, to entertain, or both? Use evidence from the text to support your answer. A. Only to inform, because there are no pictures B. Only to entertain, because there are no facts C. Both, because he tells true facts about Mary\u0027s life while using vivid, emotional language that keeps readers interested D. Neither, because the story is made up","excerpt":"Rare Treasure: Mary Anning and Her Remarkable Discoveries includes details about Mary Anning\u0027s life, fossil hunting, and scientific discoveries.","stem":"Do you think Don Brown wrote this biography to inform, to entertain, or both? Use evidence from the text to support your answer.","choices":{"A":"Only to inform, because there are no pictures","B":"Only to entertain, because there are no facts","C":"Both, because he tells true facts about Mary\u0027s life while using vivid, emotional language that keeps readers interested","D":"Neither, because the story is made up"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text is a biography, so it informs with true facts (dates, names, discoveries). But Brown also uses figurative language (\"hard as stone,\" \"shone like a gem\") and emotional details to entertain and engage readers. This matches the anchor chart\u0027s purpose: to inform AND to entertain.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l10-q014","read_aloud":"Which situation is an example of someone being pursued? A. A dog chasing a cat up a tree. B. A boy reading a book in a chair. C. A girl watching the sunset. D. A man sleeping in his bed.","excerpt":"\"It also must have been Mary\u0027s great delight because she pursued it despite the dangers on the rocky shore.\"","stem":"Which situation is an example of someone being pursued?","choices":{"A":"A dog chasing a cat up a tree.","B":"A boy reading a book in a chair.","C":"A girl watching the sunset.","D":"A man sleeping in his bed."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Pursued can mean chased or followed with determination, like a dog chasing a cat.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It also must have been Mary\u0027s great delight because she pursued it despite the dangers on the rocky shore.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l10-q015","read_aloud":"What can you infer about Mary\u0027s personality based on the text? A. She was lazy and unlucky. B. She was brave, curious, and hardworking. C. She was shy and did not like people. D. She was angry about being poor.","excerpt":"\"Mary Anning\u0027s fame grew as people learned that she was an extraordinary fossil collector and a talented scientist.\"","stem":"What can you infer about Mary\u0027s personality based on the text?","choices":{"A":"She was lazy and unlucky.","B":"She was brave, curious, and hardworking.","C":"She was shy and did not like people.","D":"She was angry about being poor."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Mary faced dangerous cliffs and studied hard, which shows she was brave, curious, and hardworking.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary Anning\u0027s fame grew as people learned that she was an extraordinary fossil collector and a talented scientist.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l10-q016","read_aloud":"How did Mary\u0027s name become known everywhere if she stayed home? A. She traveled to many countries to speak. B. She wrote a famous book about her life. C. Scientists visited her and shared her discoveries. D. She sent letters to every person in England.","excerpt":"\"Mary Anning lived from 1799 to 1847... She rarely strayed from her home, but her name became known everywhere.\"","stem":"How did Mary\u0027s name become known everywhere if she stayed home?","choices":{"A":"She traveled to many countries to speak.","B":"She wrote a famous book about her life.","C":"Scientists visited her and shared her discoveries.","D":"She sent letters to every person in England."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text mentions scientists like William Buckland came to see her. They shared her discoveries, which made her famous.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary Anning lived from 1799 to 1847... She rarely strayed from her home, but her name became known everywhere.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l10-q017","read_aloud":"What is the deeper meaning of this sentence? A. Mary was very strong at digging. B. Mary found bones, but her real gift was discovering scientific truth. C. Mary liked to look for gold in the ground. D. Mary was a miner, not a scientist.","excerpt":"\"Mary Anning pried fossils from the ground, but it was knowledge that she unearthed.\"","stem":"What is the deeper meaning of this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Mary was very strong at digging.","B":"Mary found bones, but her real gift was discovering scientific truth.","C":"Mary liked to look for gold in the ground.","D":"Mary was a miner, not a scientist."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Unearthed knowledge\" means she brought new understanding to the world. The sentence values her mind more than just the physical act of digging.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary Anning pried fossils from the ground, but it was knowledge that she unearthed.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l10-q018","read_aloud":"If Mary Anning had not survived the lightning storm as a baby, how might the world be different? A. The town of Lyme Regis would be richer. B. Scientists would have understood dinosaurs sooner. C. Some important fossil discoveries would have happened much later. D. Her brother Joseph would have been a scientist.","excerpt":"(Reviewing the whole text concept)","stem":"If Mary Anning had not survived the lightning storm as a baby, how might the world be different?","choices":{"A":"The town of Lyme Regis would be richer.","B":"Scientists would have understood dinosaurs sooner.","C":"Some important fossil discoveries would have happened much later.","D":"Her brother Joseph would have been a scientist."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Mary made many major discoveries. If she had not lived, those specific \"rare treasures\" would not have been found by her at that time.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: (Reviewing the whole text concept)"},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l10-q019","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about Use text evidence.? A. Having a lot of money and toys B. Having very little money or possessions C. Being very happy all the time D. Being sick and unable to work","excerpt":"\"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"Having a lot of money and toys","B":"Having very little money or possessions","C":"Being very happy all the time","D":"Being sick and unable to work"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Poor\" means not having much money. The text says Mary\u0027s life was hard, which shows she did not have many things.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l10-q020","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. Having a lot of money and toys B. Having very little money or possessions C. Being very happy all the time D. Being sick and unable to work","excerpt":"\"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"Having a lot of money and toys","B":"Having very little money or possessions","C":"Being very happy all the time","D":"Being sick and unable to work"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Poor\" means not having much money. The text says Mary\u0027s life was hard, which shows she did not have many things.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l10-q021","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? A. Having a lot of money and toys B. Having very little money or possessions C. Being very happy all the time D. Being sick and unable to work","excerpt":"\"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ?","choices":{"A":"Having a lot of money and toys","B":"Having very little money or possessions","C":"Being very happy all the time","D":"Being sick and unable to work"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Poor\" means not having much money. The text says Mary\u0027s life was hard, which shows she did not have many things.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l10-q022","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. The dog was afraid of Mary B. The dog was a loyal companion and helper C. The dog did not like going on fossil hunts D. The dog was trained by Mary\u0027s father","excerpt":"\"Mary\u0027s dog trotted faithfully beside her. People said the dog guarded her discoveries while she fetched her tools or got help.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"The dog was afraid of Mary","B":"The dog was a loyal companion and helper","C":"The dog did not like going on fossil hunts","D":"The dog was trained by Mary\u0027s father"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The dog trotted faithfully beside Mary and guarded her discoveries, which shows the dog was loyal and helpful.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary\u0027s dog trotted faithfully beside her. People said the dog guarded her discoveries while she fetched her tools or got help.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l10-q023","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. Seven feet long B. Nine feet long C. Twelve feet long D. Three feet long","excerpt":"\"In 1823, Mary discovered the first complete fossil of a plesiosaur, another reptile that had lived in the sea. It was an astonishing nine-foot-long creature with a long, serpentlike neck, a lizard\u0027s head, a crocodile\u0027s teeth, a chameleon\u0027s ribs, and the paddles of a whale.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"Seven feet long","B":"Nine feet long","C":"Twelve feet long","D":"Three feet long"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says \"It was an astonishing nine-foot-long creature.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1823, Mary discovered the first complete fossil of a plesiosaur, another reptile that had lived in the sea. It was an astonishing nine-foot-long creature with a long, serpentlike neck, a lizard\u0027s head, a crocodile\u0027s teeth, a chameleon\u0027s ribs, and the paddles of a whale.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l10-q024","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. To show that Mary was not a good fossil hunter B. To show that Mary did not receive the credit she deserved at first C. To show that Joseph found more fossils than Mary D. To show that fossils were not important discoveries","excerpt":"\"Almost everyone forgot that it had been found by twelve-year-old Mary Anning and her teenage brother.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"To show that Mary was not a good fossil hunter","B":"To show that Mary did not receive the credit she deserved at first","C":"To show that Joseph found more fossils than Mary","D":"To show that fossils were not important discoveries"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author includes this detail to show that even though Mary made an important discovery, people did not give her credit because she was young.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Almost everyone forgot that it had been found by twelve-year-old Mary Anning and her teenage brother.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-l10-q025","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. Yes, because Mary worked hard and became respected even though she was poor and had no formal education B. No, because Mary was lucky to live near cliffs with fossils C. Yes, because Mary wanted to become rich more than anything D. No, because Mary gave up collecting fossils when things got hard","excerpt":"\"She had little money, but she was rich in spirit. She was unschooled, but the professors heeded her words. She rarely strayed from her home, but her name became known everywhere.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"Yes, because Mary worked hard and became respected even though she was poor and had no formal education","B":"No, because Mary was lucky to live near cliffs with fossils","C":"Yes, because Mary wanted to become rich more than anything","D":"No, because Mary gave up collecting fossils when things got hard"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Mary faced poverty and a lack of education, but she followed her passion for fossils and earned respect through her hard work and knowledge.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"She had little money, but she was rich in spirit. She was unschooled, but the professors heeded her words. She rarely strayed from her home, but her name became known everywhere.\""}]}],"standardized_test":{"title":"Standardized Test","item_count":50,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q001","read_aloud":"What does the word \"poverty\" mean in this sentence? A. The state of being extremely poor B. The state of being very rich C. The state of being very happy D. The state of being very sick","excerpt":"\"The family struggled to survive on the earnings of Richard\u0027s carpentry work, and the extra money they earned by selling fossils helped. Then Mary\u0027s father died and the family was thrown into bitter poverty.\"","stem":"What does the word \"poverty\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"The state of being extremely poor","B":"The state of being very rich","C":"The state of being very happy","D":"The state of being very sick"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"\"Poverty\" means being extremely poor and not having enough money for basic needs like food and rent.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The family struggled to survive on the earnings of Richard\u0027s carpentry work, and the extra money they earned by selling fossils helped. Then Mary\u0027s father died and the family was thrown into bitter poverty.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q002","read_aloud":"In this sentence, the word \"sharp\" is used to describe Mary\u0027s eyes. What does \"sharp\" mean here? A. Pointed and able to cut B. Able to see small details very well C. Hurtful or mean D. Loud and sudden","excerpt":"\"Day after day, Mary searched in the shadows of the treacherous cliffs, sometimes walking ten miles in one day. Her sharp eyes spotted fossils where others saw nothing.\"","stem":"In this sentence, the word \"sharp\" is used to describe Mary\u0027s eyes. What does \"sharp\" mean here?","choices":{"A":"Pointed and able to cut","B":"Able to see small details very well","C":"Hurtful or mean","D":"Loud and sudden"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"When describing eyes or vision, \"sharp\" means able to see clearly and notice small details that others might miss.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Day after day, Mary searched in the shadows of the treacherous cliffs, sometimes walking ten miles in one day. Her sharp eyes spotted fossils where others saw nothing.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q003","read_aloud":"Why does the author compare Mary\u0027s life to stone and her spirit to a gem? A. To show that Mary worked with rocks and jewels B. To contrast her difficult life with her bright, strong spirit C. To show that Mary was hard and unfriendly D. To show that Mary collected gemstones for money","excerpt":"\"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\"","stem":"Why does the author compare Mary\u0027s life to stone and her spirit to a gem?","choices":{"A":"To show that Mary worked with rocks and jewels","B":"To contrast her difficult life with her bright, strong spirit","C":"To show that Mary was hard and unfriendly","D":"To show that Mary collected gemstones for money"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Stone is hard and difficult, which represents Mary\u0027s hard life. A gem shines brightly, representing her strong and bright spirit despite those difficulties.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q004","read_aloud":"What main idea does this excerpt support? A. Fossils were easy to understand from the beginning B. Fossils were once living things, but people were still learning about them C. Fossils are only found in England D. Fossils are not important to scientists","excerpt":"\"Fossils were strange and mysterious. Although they had been found before, scientists were just beginning to understand that they were the remains of animals or plants that no longer existed, living things that had died many, many years ago.\"","stem":"What main idea does this excerpt support?","choices":{"A":"Fossils were easy to understand from the beginning","B":"Fossils were once living things, but people were still learning about them","C":"Fossils are only found in England","D":"Fossils are not important to scientists"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt explains that fossils are remains of living things from long ago and that scientists were still learning about them.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Fossils were strange and mysterious. Although they had been found before, scientists were just beginning to understand that they were the remains of animals or plants that no longer existed, living things that had died many, many years ago.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q005","read_aloud":"What does this excerpt show about how Mary gained her knowledge? A. She went to a famous university B. She taught herself by reading books C. Her father taught her everything D. She learned only from scientists who visited","excerpt":"\"Mary still collected fossils and also earned money from small jobs she did for her neighbors. One of them, Mrs. Stock, gave her a geology book. From it Mary learned about rocks and mountains and the earth. She read other books and taught herself about animals, fish, and fossils.\"","stem":"What does this excerpt show about how Mary gained her knowledge?","choices":{"A":"She went to a famous university","B":"She taught herself by reading books","C":"Her father taught her everything","D":"She learned only from scientists who visited"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says Mary \"read other books and taught herself\" about animals, fish, and fossils.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary still collected fossils and also earned money from small jobs she did for her neighbors. One of them, Mrs. Stock, gave her a geology book. From it Mary learned about rocks and mountains and the earth. She read other books and taught herself about animals, fish, and fossils.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q006","read_aloud":"Based on this excerpt, what can you conclude about Mary\u0027s relationship with her dog? A. The dog was afraid of Mary B. The dog was a loyal companion and helper C. The dog did not like going on fossil hunts D. The dog was trained by Mary\u0027s father","excerpt":"\"Mary\u0027s dog trotted faithfully beside her. People said the dog guarded her discoveries while she fetched her tools or got help.\"","stem":"Based on this excerpt, what can you conclude about Mary\u0027s relationship with her dog?","choices":{"A":"The dog was afraid of Mary","B":"The dog was a loyal companion and helper","C":"The dog did not like going on fossil hunts","D":"The dog was trained by Mary\u0027s father"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The dog trotted faithfully beside Mary and guarded her discoveries, which shows the dog was loyal and helpful.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary\u0027s dog trotted faithfully beside her. People said the dog guarded her discoveries while she fetched her tools or got help.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q007","read_aloud":"How long was the plesiosaur fossil that Mary discovered? A. Seven feet long B. Nine feet long C. Twelve feet long D. Three feet long","excerpt":"\"In 1823, Mary discovered the first complete fossil of a plesiosaur, another reptile that had lived in the sea. It was an astonishing nine-foot-long creature with a long, serpentlike neck, a lizard\u0027s head, a crocodile\u0027s teeth, a chameleon\u0027s ribs, and the paddles of a whale.\"","stem":"How long was the plesiosaur fossil that Mary discovered?","choices":{"A":"Seven feet long","B":"Nine feet long","C":"Twelve feet long","D":"Three feet long"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says \"It was an astonishing nine-foot-long creature.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1823, Mary discovered the first complete fossil of a plesiosaur, another reptile that had lived in the sea. It was an astonishing nine-foot-long creature with a long, serpentlike neck, a lizard\u0027s head, a crocodile\u0027s teeth, a chameleon\u0027s ribs, and the paddles of a whale.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q008","read_aloud":"Why does the author include this detail about people forgetting who found the ichthyosaur fossil? A. To show that Mary was not a good fossil hunter B. To show that Mary did not receive the credit she deserved at first C. To show that Joseph found more fossils than Mary D. To show that fossils were not important discoveries","excerpt":"\"Almost everyone forgot that it had been found by twelve-year-old Mary Anning and her teenage brother.\"","stem":"Why does the author include this detail about people forgetting who found the ichthyosaur fossil?","choices":{"A":"To show that Mary was not a good fossil hunter","B":"To show that Mary did not receive the credit she deserved at first","C":"To show that Joseph found more fossils than Mary","D":"To show that fossils were not important discoveries"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author includes this detail to show that even though Mary made an important discovery, people did not give her credit because she was young.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Almost everyone forgot that it had been found by twelve-year-old Mary Anning and her teenage brother.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q009","read_aloud":"Do you think Mary Anning\u0027s story teaches an important lesson about following your passion even when things are hard? Why? A. Yes, because Mary worked hard and became respected even though she was poor and had no formal education B. No, because Mary was lucky to live near cliffs with fossils C. Yes, because Mary wanted to become rich more than anything D. No, because Mary gave up collecting fossils when things got hard","excerpt":"\"She had little money, but she was rich in spirit. She was unschooled, but the professors heeded her words. She rarely strayed from her home, but her name became known everywhere.\"","stem":"Do you think Mary Anning\u0027s story teaches an important lesson about following your passion even when things are hard? Why?","choices":{"A":"Yes, because Mary worked hard and became respected even though she was poor and had no formal education","B":"No, because Mary was lucky to live near cliffs with fossils","C":"Yes, because Mary wanted to become rich more than anything","D":"No, because Mary gave up collecting fossils when things got hard"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Mary faced poverty and a lack of education, but she followed her passion for fossils and earned respect through her hard work and knowledge.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"She had little money, but she was rich in spirit. She was unschooled, but the professors heeded her words. She rarely strayed from her home, but her name became known everywhere.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q010","read_aloud":"If Mary Anning had a famous quote on a statue in her honor, which message below would best represent her legacy? A. \"Get rich quickly by selling rocks\" B. \"Stay in school and never explore on your own\" C. \"With curiosity and hard work, anyone can help the world learn new things\" D. \"Only rich people can become scientists\"","excerpt":"\"Mary Anning pried fossils from the ground, but it was knowledge that she unearthed.\"","stem":"If Mary Anning had a famous quote on a statue in her honor, which message below would best represent her legacy?","choices":{"A":"\"Get rich quickly by selling rocks\"","B":"\"Stay in school and never explore on your own\"","C":"\"With curiosity and hard work, anyone can help the world learn new things\"","D":"\"Only rich people can become scientists\""},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Mary\u0027s life shows that curiosity, hard work, and dedication can lead to important discoveries that help everyone learn, even without wealth or formal education. Section A - Text Information Title: Rare Treasure: Mary Anning and Her Remarkable DiscoveriesAuthor: Don BrownText Type: Biography (Narrative Nonfiction)Preview Vocabulary Words: poverty, pursued, treacherous, remarkable, assembled","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary Anning pried fossils from the ground, but it was knowledge that she unearthed.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"poverty\" mean in this sentence? A. having many friends and family B. being extremely poor with little money C. living near the ocean D. having a large collection of fossils","excerpt":"Then Mary\u0027s father died and the family was thrown into bitter poverty.","stem":"What does \"poverty\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"having many friends and family","B":"being extremely poor with little money","C":"living near the ocean","D":"having a large collection of fossils"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Poverty means being very poor. The text says the family struggled after Mary\u0027s father died, which matches this meaning.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Then Mary\u0027s father died and the family was thrown into bitter poverty."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q012","read_aloud":"Which word means almost the same as \"pursued\"? A. gave up on B. worked hard to keep doing C. forgot about D. asked others to do","excerpt":"She made it her life\u0027s work. It also must have been Mary\u0027s great delight because she pursued it despite the dangers on the rocky shore.","stem":"Which word means almost the same as \"pursued\"?","choices":{"A":"gave up on","B":"worked hard to keep doing","C":"forgot about","D":"asked others to do"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Pursued means Mary kept working at fossil collecting with dedication. The other choices mean the opposite.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: She made it her life\u0027s work. It also must have been Mary\u0027s great delight because she pursued it despite the dangers on the rocky shore."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q013","read_aloud":"What does \"treacherous\" mean here? A. safe and easy to walk on B. unsafe because of hidden dangers C. colorful and beautiful D. flat and smooth","excerpt":"Day after day, Mary searched in the shadows of the treacherous cliffs, sometimes walking ten miles in one day.","stem":"What does \"treacherous\" mean here?","choices":{"A":"safe and easy to walk on","B":"unsafe because of hidden dangers","C":"colorful and beautiful","D":"flat and smooth"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Treacherous means dangerous with hidden risks, like falling rocks. The other choices do not fit the context.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Day after day, Mary searched in the shadows of the treacherous cliffs, sometimes walking ten miles in one day."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q014","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this sentence? A. Mary was born in a specific place with distinctive geography. B. Mary did not like living near the coast. C. Lyme Regis was a big city. D. Mary\u0027s birth year was not important.","excerpt":"In 1799, Mary Anning was born in Lyme Regis, a small English port tucked tightly between cliffs and coast.","stem":"What is the main idea of this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Mary was born in a specific place with distinctive geography.","B":"Mary did not like living near the coast.","C":"Lyme Regis was a big city.","D":"Mary\u0027s birth year was not important."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The sentence gives key details about where and when Mary was born, setting the scene for her story. The other choices misread the details.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: In 1799, Mary Anning was born in Lyme Regis, a small English port tucked tightly between cliffs and coast."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q015","read_aloud":"What detail helps explain why fossils are rare? A. All remains turn to stone quickly. B. Only a rare few remains stay undisturbed long enough to become fossils. C. Fossils are found on every beach. D. Scientists create fossils in labs.","excerpt":"Usually the remains of plants and animals decompose or are eaten, but sometimes they are covered by dirt or sink in mud. Of these, a rare few lie undisturbed for millions of years.","stem":"What detail helps explain why fossils are rare?","choices":{"A":"All remains turn to stone quickly.","B":"Only a rare few remains stay undisturbed long enough to become fossils.","C":"Fossils are found on every beach.","D":"Scientists create fossils in labs."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says only a \"rare few\" remains meet the conditions to become fossils. This explains their rarity.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Usually the remains of plants and animals decompose or are eaten, but sometimes they are covered by dirt or sink in mud. Of these, a rare few lie undisturbed for millions of years."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q016","read_aloud":"What text structure does the author use in this description? A. sequence B. description using comparisons C. cause and effect D. problem and solution","excerpt":"It was an astonishing nine-foot-long creature with a long, serpentlike neck, a lizard\u0027s head, a crocodile\u0027s teeth, a chameleon\u0027s ribs, and the paddles of a whale.","stem":"What text structure does the author use in this description?","choices":{"A":"sequence","B":"description using comparisons","C":"cause and effect","D":"problem and solution"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author uses vivid comparisons to familiar animals to help readers picture the plesiosaur. This is descriptive text structure.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: It was an astonishing nine-foot-long creature with a long, serpentlike neck, a lizard\u0027s head, a crocodile\u0027s teeth, a chameleon\u0027s ribs, and the paddles of a whale."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q017","read_aloud":"What did Mary discover in 1823? A. the first complete plesiosaur fossil B. a dinosaur bone C. a map of ancient seas D. a new type of rock","excerpt":"In 1823, Mary discovered the first complete fossil of a plesiosaur, another reptile that had lived in the sea.","stem":"What did Mary discover in 1823?","choices":{"A":"the first complete plesiosaur fossil","B":"a dinosaur bone","C":"a map of ancient seas","D":"a new type of rock"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text directly states Mary found the first complete plesiosaur fossil in 1823. The other items are not mentioned.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: In 1823, Mary discovered the first complete fossil of a plesiosaur, another reptile that had lived in the sea."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q018","read_aloud":"Why did scientists value Mary\u0027s ideas? A. Because she was rich and famous. B. Because she knew a lot about fossils from her own study and experience. C. Because she worked for the museum. D. Because she had a college degree.","excerpt":"Mary shared her ideas with the finest scientists. They prized the thoughts of the remarkable young woman who had left school when she was eleven.","stem":"Why did scientists value Mary\u0027s ideas?","choices":{"A":"Because she was rich and famous.","B":"Because she knew a lot about fossils from her own study and experience.","C":"Because she worked for the museum.","D":"Because she had a college degree."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text shows Mary learned on her own and knew more than others about fossils. Her knowledge, not her schooling, made scientists value her.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Mary shared her ideas with the finest scientists. They prized the thoughts of the remarkable young woman who had left school when she was eleven."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q019","read_aloud":"What pattern does the author use in these sentences, and why? A. The author lists facts in order of importance. B. The author uses contrast (but) to show how Mary\u0027s outer life differed from her inner impact. C. The author repeats the same idea three times. D. The author compares Mary to other scientists.","excerpt":"She had little money, but she was rich in spirit. She was unschooled, but the professors heeded her words. She rarely strayed from her home, but her name became known everywhere.","stem":"What pattern does the author use in these sentences, and why?","choices":{"A":"The author lists facts in order of importance.","B":"The author uses contrast (but) to show how Mary\u0027s outer life differed from her inner impact.","C":"The author repeats the same idea three times.","D":"The author compares Mary to other scientists."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Each sentence uses \"but\" to contrast Mary\u0027s humble circumstances with her great influence. This pattern highlights her remarkable life.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: She had little money, but she was rich in spirit. She was unschooled, but the professors heeded her words. She rarely strayed from her home, but her name became known everywhere."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q020","read_aloud":"Why is the phrase \"it was knowledge that she unearthed\" a powerful way to end Mary\u0027s story? A. It suggests digging was her only skill. B. It connects her fossil finds to the bigger gift of scientific understanding she gave the world. C. It complains that fossils are hard to find. D. It suggests knowledge is buried like treasure.","excerpt":"Mary Anning pried fossils from the ground, but it was knowledge that she unearthed.","stem":"Why is the phrase \"it was knowledge that she unearthed\" a powerful way to end Mary\u0027s story?","choices":{"A":"It suggests digging was her only skill.","B":"It connects her fossil finds to the bigger gift of scientific understanding she gave the world.","C":"It complains that fossils are hard to find.","D":"It suggests knowledge is buried like treasure."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"This phrase elevates Mary\u0027s work from collecting objects to advancing human knowledge. It celebrates her lasting impact on science. Section A - Text Information Title: Rare TreasureAuthor: Don BrownGenre: Biography (Narrative Nonfiction)Pages: 55-67 in the student interactive workbook","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Mary Anning pried fossils from the ground, but it was knowledge that she unearthed."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q021","read_aloud":"What does poverty mean? A. The state of being extremely poor B. The state of being famous C. The state of being happy D. The state of being healthy","excerpt":"\"Then Mary\u0027s father died and the family was thrown into bitter poverty.\"","stem":"What does poverty mean?","choices":{"A":"The state of being extremely poor","B":"The state of being famous","C":"The state of being happy","D":"The state of being healthy"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Poverty is the condition of having very little money or resources.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Then Mary\u0027s father died and the family was thrown into bitter poverty.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q022","read_aloud":"Which word is a synonym for remarkable? A. Ordinary B. Outstanding C. Boring D. Young","excerpt":"\"They prized the thoughts of the remarkable young woman who had left school when she was eleven.\"","stem":"Which word is a synonym for remarkable?","choices":{"A":"Ordinary","B":"Outstanding","C":"Boring","D":"Young"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Remarkable means extraordinary or outstanding, worthy of attention.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They prized the thoughts of the remarkable young woman who had left school when she was eleven.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q023","read_aloud":"Which word is an antonym for treacherous? A. Safe B. Risky C. Dangerous D. High","excerpt":"\"Day after day, Mary searched in the shadows of the treacherous cliffs, sometimes walking ten miles in one day.\"","stem":"Which word is an antonym for treacherous?","choices":{"A":"Safe","B":"Risky","C":"Dangerous","D":"High"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Treacherous means dangerous, so an antonym is safe.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Day after day, Mary searched in the shadows of the treacherous cliffs, sometimes walking ten miles in one day.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q024","read_aloud":"According to the sequence of events, who found the skull first? A. Mary found it before Joseph. B. Joseph found it a year before Mary found the skeleton. C. They found the skull and skeleton on the same day. D. Scientists found the skull for them.","excerpt":"\"In 1811, Mary found a fossilized skeleton beneath a cliff called Black Ven, where Joseph had found the skull.\"","stem":"According to the sequence of events, who found the skull first?","choices":{"A":"Mary found it before Joseph.","B":"Joseph found it a year before Mary found the skeleton.","C":"They found the skull and skeleton on the same day.","D":"Scientists found the skull for them."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says Joseph found the skull first, and a year passed before Mary found the rest of the skeleton.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1811, Mary found a fossilized skeleton beneath a cliff called Black Ven, where Joseph had found the skull.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q025","read_aloud":"What main idea does this detail support? A. Fossils are easy to find on the beach. B. Scientists in the 1800s knew everything about dinosaurs. C. Fossils help us learn about creatures from the past. D. Mary Anning was the only person who liked fossils.","excerpt":"\"Scientists were just beginning to understand that they were the remains of animals or plants that no longer existed...\"","stem":"What main idea does this detail support?","choices":{"A":"Fossils are easy to find on the beach.","B":"Scientists in the 1800s knew everything about dinosaurs.","C":"Fossils help us learn about creatures from the past.","D":"Mary Anning was the only person who liked fossils."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"This detail explains that fossils are remains of things that lived long ago, which helps us learn about history.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Scientists were just beginning to understand that they were the remains of animals or plants that no longer existed...\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q026","read_aloud":"What does this sentence suggest about the professors? A. They thought Mary was uneducated. B. They respected Mary\u0027s knowledge. C. They wanted Mary to go to school. D. They ignored Mary\u0027s ideas.","excerpt":"\"She was unschooled, but the professors heeded her words.\"","stem":"What does this sentence suggest about the professors?","choices":{"A":"They thought Mary was uneducated.","B":"They respected Mary\u0027s knowledge.","C":"They wanted Mary to go to school.","D":"They ignored Mary\u0027s ideas."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Heeded her words\" means they listened to and paid attention to what she said, showing respect.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"She was unschooled, but the professors heeded her words.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q027","read_aloud":"Why does the author compare Mary to a stone and a gem? A. To show she was rich and famous. B. To show her life was hard, but she was special inside. C. To show she wanted to be a rock collector. D. To show she was cold and unkind.","excerpt":"\"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\"","stem":"Why does the author compare Mary to a stone and a gem?","choices":{"A":"To show she was rich and famous.","B":"To show her life was hard, but she was special inside.","C":"To show she wanted to be a rock collector.","D":"To show she was cold and unkind."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The \"stone\" represents her hard life, but the \"gem\" represents her shining, smart spirit.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q028","read_aloud":"How does this description help the reader understand Mary\u0027s job? A. It shows that her job was easy and fun. B. It shows that she worked in very dangerous conditions. C. It shows that she worked inside a safe shop. D. It shows that she liked to swim in the ocean.","excerpt":"\"Boulders fell from the cliffs, torrents of thick black mud slid down from the heights, high seas pummeled the shore, and waves could sweep a careless visitor away.\"","stem":"How does this description help the reader understand Mary\u0027s job?","choices":{"A":"It shows that her job was easy and fun.","B":"It shows that she worked in very dangerous conditions.","C":"It shows that she worked inside a safe shop.","D":"It shows that she liked to swim in the ocean."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Describing falling boulders and mud slides shows that her work was very dangerous.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Boulders fell from the cliffs, torrents of thick black mud slid down from the heights, high seas pummeled the shore, and waves could sweep a careless visitor away.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q029","read_aloud":"Based on the text, why is Mary Anning considered an important person in history? A. She became very wealthy from selling fossils. B. She discovered important fossils and helped scientists learn. C. She opened the first museum in England. D. She wrote many famous books about her life.","excerpt":"\"She had little money, but she was rich in spirit. She was unschooled, but the professors heeded her words.\"","stem":"Based on the text, why is Mary Anning considered an important person in history?","choices":{"A":"She became very wealthy from selling fossils.","B":"She discovered important fossils and helped scientists learn.","C":"She opened the first museum in England.","D":"She wrote many famous books about her life."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Mary is important because she found rare fossils and shared knowledge that helped scientists understand the past.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"She had little money, but she was rich in spirit. She was unschooled, but the professors heeded her words.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q030","read_aloud":"What is the best summary of Mary Anning\u0027s life based on the text? A. Mary Anning was a poor girl who lived in Lyme Regis and sold shells to tourists. B. Mary Anning survived a lightning strike as a baby and had a dog that guarded her fossils. C. Mary Anning was a self-taught scientist who made important fossil discoveries despite being poor. D. Mary Anning walked ten miles a day looking for rocks on the beach with her brother Joseph.","excerpt":"\"Mary Anning pried fossils from the ground, but it was knowledge that she unearthed.\"","stem":"What is the best summary of Mary Anning\u0027s life based on the text?","choices":{"A":"Mary Anning was a poor girl who lived in Lyme Regis and sold shells to tourists.","B":"Mary Anning survived a lightning strike as a baby and had a dog that guarded her fossils.","C":"Mary Anning was a self-taught scientist who made important fossil discoveries despite being poor.","D":"Mary Anning walked ten miles a day looking for rocks on the beach with her brother Joseph."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"This summary captures the main points: she was self-taught, a scientist, made discoveries, and was poor.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary Anning pried fossils from the ground, but it was knowledge that she unearthed.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q031","read_aloud":"Read the excerpt and choose the best answer. Which choice is best supported about ? A. Having a lot of money and toys B. Having very little money or possessions C. Being very happy all the time D. Being sick and unable to work","excerpt":"\"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\"","stem":"Read the excerpt and choose the best answer. Which choice is best supported about ?","choices":{"A":"Having a lot of money and toys","B":"Having very little money or possessions","C":"Being very happy all the time","D":"Being sick and unable to work"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Poor\" means not having much money. The text says Mary\u0027s life was hard, which shows she did not have many things.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q032","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? A. Having a lot of money and toys B. Having very little money or possessions C. Being very happy all the time D. Being sick and unable to work","excerpt":"\"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ?","choices":{"A":"Having a lot of money and toys","B":"Having very little money or possessions","C":"Being very happy all the time","D":"Being sick and unable to work"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Poor\" means not having much money. The text says Mary\u0027s life was hard, which shows she did not have many things.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q033","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? A. Having a lot of money and toys B. Having very little money or possessions C. Being very happy all the time D. Being sick and unable to work","excerpt":"\"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ?","choices":{"A":"Having a lot of money and toys","B":"Having very little money or possessions","C":"Being very happy all the time","D":"Being sick and unable to work"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Poor\" means not having much money. The text says Mary\u0027s life was hard, which shows she did not have many things.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone. But she was also curious and smart and her spirit shone-it shone like a gem.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q034","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. The dog was afraid of Mary B. The dog was a loyal companion and helper C. The dog did not like going on fossil hunts D. The dog was trained by Mary\u0027s father","excerpt":"\"Mary\u0027s dog trotted faithfully beside her. People said the dog guarded her discoveries while she fetched her tools or got help.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"The dog was afraid of Mary","B":"The dog was a loyal companion and helper","C":"The dog did not like going on fossil hunts","D":"The dog was trained by Mary\u0027s father"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The dog trotted faithfully beside Mary and guarded her discoveries, which shows the dog was loyal and helpful.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary\u0027s dog trotted faithfully beside her. People said the dog guarded her discoveries while she fetched her tools or got help.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q035","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. Seven feet long B. Nine feet long C. Twelve feet long D. Three feet long","excerpt":"\"In 1823, Mary discovered the first complete fossil of a plesiosaur, another reptile that had lived in the sea. It was an astonishing nine-foot-long creature with a long, serpentlike neck, a lizard\u0027s head, a crocodile\u0027s teeth, a chameleon\u0027s ribs, and the paddles of a whale.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"Seven feet long","B":"Nine feet long","C":"Twelve feet long","D":"Three feet long"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says \"It was an astonishing nine-foot-long creature.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1823, Mary discovered the first complete fossil of a plesiosaur, another reptile that had lived in the sea. It was an astonishing nine-foot-long creature with a long, serpentlike neck, a lizard\u0027s head, a crocodile\u0027s teeth, a chameleon\u0027s ribs, and the paddles of a whale.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q036","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. To show that Mary was not a good fossil hunter B. To show that Mary did not receive the credit she deserved at first C. To show that Joseph found more fossils than Mary D. To show that fossils were not important discoveries","excerpt":"\"Almost everyone forgot that it had been found by twelve-year-old Mary Anning and her teenage brother.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"To show that Mary was not a good fossil hunter","B":"To show that Mary did not receive the credit she deserved at first","C":"To show that Joseph found more fossils than Mary","D":"To show that fossils were not important discoveries"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author includes this detail to show that even though Mary made an important discovery, people did not give her credit because she was young.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Almost everyone forgot that it had been found by twelve-year-old Mary Anning and her teenage brother.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q037","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. Yes, because Mary worked hard and became respected even though she was poor and had no formal education B. No, because Mary was lucky to live near cliffs with fossils C. Yes, because Mary wanted to become rich more than anything D. No, because Mary gave up collecting fossils when things got hard","excerpt":"\"She had little money, but she was rich in spirit. She was unschooled, but the professors heeded her words. She rarely strayed from her home, but her name became known everywhere.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"Yes, because Mary worked hard and became respected even though she was poor and had no formal education","B":"No, because Mary was lucky to live near cliffs with fossils","C":"Yes, because Mary wanted to become rich more than anything","D":"No, because Mary gave up collecting fossils when things got hard"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Mary faced poverty and a lack of education, but she followed her passion for fossils and earned respect through her hard work and knowledge.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"She had little money, but she was rich in spirit. She was unschooled, but the professors heeded her words. She rarely strayed from her home, but her name became known everywhere.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q038","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505. A. \"Get rich quickly by selling rocks\" B. \"Stay in school and never explore on your own\" C. \"With curiosity and hard work, anyone can help the world learn new things\" D. \"Only rich people can become scientists\"","excerpt":"\"Mary Anning pried fossils from the ground, but it was knowledge that she unearthed.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505.","choices":{"A":"\"Get rich quickly by selling rocks\"","B":"\"Stay in school and never explore on your own\"","C":"\"With curiosity and hard work, anyone can help the world learn new things\"","D":"\"Only rich people can become scientists\""},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Mary\u0027s life shows that curiosity, hard work, and dedication can lead to important discoveries that help everyone learn, even without wealth or formal education. Section A - Text Information Title: Rare Treasure: Mary Anning and Her Remarkable DiscoveriesAuthor: Don BrownText Type: Biography (Narrative Nonfiction)Preview Vocabulary Words: poverty, pursued, treacherous, remarkable, assembled","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mary Anning pried fossils from the ground, but it was knowledge that she unearthed.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q039","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 506. A. having lots of money and toys B. being extremely poor with little money C. living in a big, fancy house D. having many friends to help","excerpt":"Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone.","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 506.","choices":{"A":"having lots of money and toys","B":"being extremely poor with little money","C":"living in a big, fancy house","D":"having many friends to help"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Poverty means being very poor and not having enough money. The text says Mary\u0027s life was hard, which matches this meaning.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Mary was poor and her life was hard-as hard as stone."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q040","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 507. A. in a big city in France B. in Lyme Regis, a small English port C. on a farm in America D. in a castle in Scotland","excerpt":"In 1799, Mary Anning was born in Lyme Regis, a small English port tucked tightly between cliffs and coast.","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 507.","choices":{"A":"in a big city in France","B":"in Lyme Regis, a small English port","C":"on a farm in America","D":"in a castle in Scotland"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text clearly says Mary was born in Lyme Regis, a small English port. The other places are not mentioned.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: In 1799, Mary Anning was born in Lyme Regis, a small English port tucked tightly between cliffs and coast."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q041","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 508. A. their mother B. their teacher at school C. their father, Richard Anning D. a scientist from London","excerpt":"Mary and her older brother, Joseph, were just a few years old when they began visiting the nearby rocky beaches with their father.","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 508.","choices":{"A":"their mother","B":"their teacher at school","C":"their father, Richard Anning","D":"a scientist from London"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says their father, Richard Anning, taught them how to hunt for fossils. The other people are not mentioned here.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Mary and her older brother, Joseph, were just a few years old when they began visiting the nearby rocky beaches with their father."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q042","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 509. A. Mary was hurt badly. B. Mary was the only one who survived. C. Everyone ran away safely. D. The nursemaid saved everyone.","excerpt":"Only Mary survived. It was a miraculous escape.","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 509.","choices":{"A":"Mary was hurt badly.","B":"Mary was the only one who survived.","C":"Everyone ran away safely.","D":"The nursemaid saved everyone."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says only Mary survived the lightning strike. The other choices do not match what happened.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Only Mary survived. It was a miraculous escape."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q043","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 510. A. They were worth a lot of money. B. They were beautiful and belonged to her. C. Her father gave them to her. D. Scientists wanted to buy them.","excerpt":"Those rocks were precious, they were beautiful, and-most importantly-they were mine.","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 510.","choices":{"A":"They were worth a lot of money.","B":"They were beautiful and belonged to her.","C":"Her father gave them to her.","D":"Scientists wanted to buy them."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Mary says the rocks were precious because they were beautiful and hers. The text does not mention money, her father, or scientists here.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Those rocks were precious, they were beautiful, and-most importantly-they were mine."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q044","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 511. A. gave up on B. worked hard to keep doing C. forgot about D. asked others to do","excerpt":"She made it her life\u0027s work. It also must have been Mary\u0027s great delight because she pursued it despite the dangers on the rocky shore.","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 511.","choices":{"A":"gave up on","B":"worked hard to keep doing","C":"forgot about","D":"asked others to do"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Pursued means Mary kept working hard at fossil collecting. The other choices mean the opposite.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: She made it her life\u0027s work. It also must have been Mary\u0027s great delight because she pursued it despite the dangers on the rocky shore."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q045","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 512. A. living animals that hide in rocks B. remains of ancient plants or animals that turned to stone C. colorful stones found on beaches D. toys that children collect","excerpt":"Fossils were strange and mysterious. Although they had been found before, scientists were just beginning to understand that they were the remains of animals or plants that no longer existed.","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 512.","choices":{"A":"living animals that hide in rocks","B":"remains of ancient plants or animals that turned to stone","C":"colorful stones found on beaches","D":"toys that children collect"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains fossils are remains of ancient life that became stone. The other choices do not match this definition.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Fossils were strange and mysterious. Although they had been found before, scientists were just beginning to understand that they were the remains of animals or plants that no longer existed."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q046","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 513. A. small and round with no teeth B. long with a snout and many sharp teeth C. flat and smooth like a plate D. colorful and shiny like a gem","excerpt":"One day Joseph found a fantastic fossil skull. It was nearly the length of a man\u0027s arm and had a long snout that held many sharp teeth.","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 513.","choices":{"A":"small and round with no teeth","B":"long with a snout and many sharp teeth","C":"flat and smooth like a plate","D":"colorful and shiny like a gem"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text describes the skull as long with a snout and sharp teeth. The other descriptions do not match.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: One day Joseph found a fantastic fossil skull. It was nearly the length of a man\u0027s arm and had a long snout that held many sharp teeth."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q047","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 514. A. a fossilized skeleton B. a bag of gold coins C. a map to treasure D. a rare bird\u0027s nest","excerpt":"In 1811, Mary found a fossilized skeleton beneath a cliff called Black Ven, where Joseph had found the skull.","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 514.","choices":{"A":"a fossilized skeleton","B":"a bag of gold coins","C":"a map to treasure","D":"a rare bird\u0027s nest"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text clearly says Mary found a fossilized skeleton in 1811. The other items are not mentioned.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: In 1811, Mary found a fossilized skeleton beneath a cliff called Black Ven, where Joseph had found the skull."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q048","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 515. A. It was the first fossil ever found. B. It was a nearly perfect ichthyosaur fossil, which was very rare. C. It was made of gold. D. It was easy to carry home.","excerpt":"The scientists called the creature ichthyosaur, which means fish lizard. Only a few ichthyosaur fossils had ever been found and none were as nearly perfect as this one.","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 515.","choices":{"A":"It was the first fossil ever found.","B":"It was a nearly perfect ichthyosaur fossil, which was very rare.","C":"It was made of gold.","D":"It was easy to carry home."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the fossil was rare and nearly perfect, which made scientists excited. The other choices are not supported.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The scientists called the creature ichthyosaur, which means fish lizard. Only a few ichthyosaur fossils had ever been found and none were as nearly perfect as this one."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q049","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 516. A. safe and easy to walk on B. unsafe because of hidden dangers C. colorful and beautiful D. flat and smooth","excerpt":"Day after day, Mary searched in the shadows of the treacherous cliffs, sometimes walking ten miles in one day.","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 516.","choices":{"A":"safe and easy to walk on","B":"unsafe because of hidden dangers","C":"colorful and beautiful","D":"flat and smooth"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Treacherous means dangerous with hidden risks, like falling rocks or mudslides. The other choices do not fit.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Day after day, Mary searched in the shadows of the treacherous cliffs, sometimes walking ten miles in one day."},{"item_id":"g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure-std-q050","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 517. A. Animals and plants turn into water quickly. B. Remains are covered, undisturbed for millions of years, and minerals turn them to stone. C. People dig them up right after an animal dies. D. Rocks grow around living animals.","excerpt":"Usually the remains of plants and animals decompose or are eaten, but sometimes they are covered by dirt or sink in mud. Of these, a rare few lie undisturbed for millions of years.","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 517.","choices":{"A":"Animals and plants turn into water quickly.","B":"Remains are covered, undisturbed for millions of years, and minerals turn them to stone.","C":"People dig them up right after an animal dies.","D":"Rocks grow around living animals."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains the process: remains get covered, stay undisturbed, and minerals turn them to stone. The other choices are incorrect.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Usually the remains of plants and animals decompose or are eaten, but sometimes they are covered by dirt or sink in mud. Of these, a rare few lie undisturbed for millions of years."}]}}]};const target=window.READING_SELECTIONS_DATA||{selections:[]};target.selections=(target.selections||[]).filter((selection)=>selection.selection_id!=="g4-u1-w2-rare-treasure" && !(/^Rare Treasure/i.test(selection.title||"") && Number(selection.grade)===4 && Number(selection.unit)===1));rareTreasureFix.selections.forEach((selection)=>target.selections.push(selection));window.READING_SELECTIONS_DATA=target;})();
